Marijan Bloudek (October 7, 2019 \u2013 October 18, 2019)\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Milenko Bo\u0161njakovi\u0107 (October 18, 2019 \u2013 December 13, 2019)\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} [[Gradimir Crnogorac]] (December 18, 2019 \u2013 present)\n\n==Presidents==\n*{{flagicon|Yugoslavia}} Ante Raos\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Salko Bukvarevi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Enver Bijedi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Salih \u0160abovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Davud Zahirovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Mersad Kova\u010devi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Azmir Husi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Senad Mujkanovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Sead Kozli\u0107\n*{{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Elmir \u0160e\u0107erbegovi\u0107\n\n==Club ranking==\n\n===UEFA coefficient===\n====2019/2020 season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Rank !! Team !! Points\n|-\n|380||align=left|{{flagicon|MKD}} [[FK Sileks|Sileks]]||1.475\n|-\n|381||align=left|{{flagicon|MKD}} [[FK Renova|Renova]]||1.475\n|-\n|382||align=left|{{flagicon|BIH}} [[FK Radnik Bijeljina|Radnik]]||1.375\n|-bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|'''383'''||align=left|{{flagicon|BIH}} '''Sloboda'''||'''1.375'''\n|-\n|384||align=left|{{flagicon|BIH}} [[FK Olimpik|Olimpik]]||1.375\n|-\n|385||align=left|{{flagicon|MDA}} [[Speran\u021ba Nisporeni]]||1.350\n|-\n|386||align=left|{{flagicon|MDA}} [[FC Dacia Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Dacia]]||1.350\n|}\nAs of 8 November 2019. [https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/uefarankings/club/#/yr/2020 Source]\n{{details|UEFA coefficient}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|FK Sloboda Tuzla}}\n*[https://m.facebook.com/FKSlobodaTuzlaOfficial/ FK Sloboda Tuzla] at [[Facebook]]\n\n{{FK Sloboda Tuzla}}\n{{Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Yugoslav First League}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sloboda}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Sport in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Sport in Tuzla]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:FK Sloboda Tuzla| ]]\n", "name_user": "Red Jay", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(removedCategory:Football clubs in YugoslaviausingHotCatin B&H category)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FK_Sloboda_Tuzla"}
{"title_page": "Mandleshwar", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = www.Mandleshwar.in\n| native_name             = Mandala\n| native_name_lang        = Nimari\n| other_name              = Mundlesir\n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = town\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Madhya Pradesh, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|22.18|N|75.67|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = India\n| subdivision_country       = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Khargone district|Khargone]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = Mandan Mishra\n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 153\n| population_total        = 11345\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages-Hindi, Nimari.\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = 451221\n| registration_plate      = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Mandleshwar.in''' is a town and [[nagar panchayat]] in the [[Khargone district]] of the [[India]] state of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. It is on the banks of [[Narmada River]],<ref name=mapia>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/923036/Mandleshwar-Town |title=Mandleshwar Town |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref> {{convert|8|km}} east of [[Maheshwar]] and {{convert|99|km}} south of [[Indore]]. It is a \"Pavitra nagri\" as termed by the government of Madhya Pradesh, as it is an ancient town. It is the education centre of Maheshwar block, the location of the district court and district jail of Khargone, and is also the political centre of Maheshwar block.\n\n==History== \nMandleshwar is {{convert|8|km}} from [[Maheshwar]], capital of the [[Holkar]] states.\n\nThe eighth-century philosopher [[Ma\u1e47\u1e0dana Mi\u015bra]] reportedly lived in the town and debated with [[Adi Shankara|Aadya Guru Shankarachaarya]] at the Gupteshwar Mahadev Temple. \n\nThe British Raj is memorialized in the [[Sub-Divisional Magistrate]], PWD office, the district jail, fort and the 'ghat'. ('Ghat' means a flight of steps leading down to a waterfront.) Mandleshwar was the headquarters for the Nimar Agency and cantonment from 1819 to 1864. In 1823, it became the headquarters for the District of Nimar (which, until 1864, was managed by the agent of the governor-general at Indore. \n\nRiver Narmada is considered by the Hindus to be a holy river and Mandleshwar has tanks, temples and ghats. Hindu temples here include Shree Gupteshwar Mahadev Mandir, Chhappan-Dev, Shree Ram Temple, Shree Datta Temple, Ganga-Zira, and Kaashi Vishweshwar Temple. Dhawal-kunda and Hathani (islands), Sahastradhara, and Ram kund are other places of historical significance. A flight of 123 steps leads down to the river and expands into the Ram Ghat, where the Ram, Hanuman, Dattatraya and Ratneshwar Temples are located. Ghat is located is at a narrow point of the Narmada River where, during the [[monsoon]], the river often rises {{convert|60|ft}} above its normal level, hence those many steps. \n\nMandleshwar also has a temple dedicated to [[Brahma Chaitanya|Brahmachaitanya Maharaj Gondwalekar]]. \n\n[[Vasudevanand Saraswati]] (a saint) lived in Mandleshwar for a long time. \n\n[[Swami Vivekananda]] reportedly lived in the town on his way to [[Raipur]]. \n\n[[Vinoba Bhave]], an advocate of nonviolence and human rights, visited Mandleshwar; [[Indira Gandhi]] visited in 1971 to inaugurate the water-supply-system plant run by the [[Public Health Engineering Department]] and the [[Government of Madhya Pradesh]].\n\nThe Maheshwar Dam produce 400 MW of electricity.{{cn|date=June 2016}} A one-kilometer bridge crosses the river.\n\n==Geography==\nMandleshwar is located at {{Coord|22.18|N|75.67|E|}},<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/35/Mandleshwar.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc \u2013 Mandleshwar]</ref> and has an average elevation of 153&nbsp;metres (501&nbsp;feet).\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the 2001 India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> the town had a population of 11,345. Males made up 51 percent of the population, and females 49 percent. Mandleshwar had an average literacy rate of 68 percent, higher than the national average of 59.5 percent; male literacy was 76 percent, and female literacy 59 percent. Fourteen percent of the population was under six years of age.\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Mandleshwar \n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|77.83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|18.15}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|1.89}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.03}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|1.15}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Sikh]]s (0.49%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.01%).</small>\n}}\n\n==Economy==\nMandleshwar's economy is largely based on [[agriculture]], and it is noted for [[Hydroelectricity|hydroelectric power generation]]. The Maheshwar Hydro-electric Project (10 X 40 MW) is under construction between Mandleshwar and the village of Jalud.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==Education==  \nThe Charak Institute of Pharmacy and the Sardar Patel Institute of Technology and Management, an engineering college, are located in Mandleshwar. The town has one government college, three private colleges, the Sardar Patel International School Mandleshwar, two government higher secondary schools and nine public schools Among them 2 are CBSE affiliated schools and most popular ones in the town \"sandipani Academy\" and \"Shri kanwartara senior secondary school\". An organization, Maa Umiya Sansthan, operates a higher secondary school affiliated to the M. P. Board in Bhopal, a women's college, a B. Ed college and a women's hostel serving students from across India. Courses are offered by the Shri Umiya Girls College in [[bioinformatics]] (a three-year degree), [[biotechnology]] and computer science. Mandleshwar's oldest school is the Mahatma Gandhi Govt Higher Secondary School, established in 1947 and the only school within a 50-km radius at the time.\n\n==Culture==\nFestivals celebrated in Mandleshwar include [[Holi]], [[Diwali]], [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]], [[Christmas]], [[Guru Nanak Gurpurab|Gurunanak Jayanti]], Narmada Jayanti, Gangour Navratri, and [[Ganesh Chaturthi]]. [[Gangaur]] is the most popular.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==Access==\nMandleshwar can be reached by road from [[Indore]], [[Dhamnod]], [[Omkareshwar]], [[Barwaha]], and [[Khargone]], with direct bus service available from [[Ujjain]] and Indore.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Indore Division}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Khargone district]]\n[[Category:Khargone]]\n[[Category:Religion in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Mandleshwar\n| native_name             = Mandala\n| native_name_lang        = Nimari\n| other_name              = Mundlesir\n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = town\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Madhya Pradesh, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|22.18|N|75.67|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = India\n| subdivision_country       = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Khargone district|Khargone]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = Mandan Mishra\n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 153\n| population_total        = 11345\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages-Hindi, Nimari.\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = 451221\n| registration_plate      = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Mandleshwar''' is a town and [[nagar panchayat]] in the [[Khargone district]] of the [[India]] state of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. It is on the banks of [[Narmada River]],<ref name=mapia>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/923036/Mandleshwar-Town |title=Mandleshwar Town |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=2016-06-19}}</ref> {{convert|8|km}} east of [[Maheshwar]] and {{convert|99|km}} south of [[Indore]]. It is a \"Pavitra nagri\" as termed by the government of Madhya Pradesh, as it is an ancient town. It is the education centre of Maheshwar block, the location of the district court and district jail of Khargone, and is also the political centre of Maheshwar block.\n\n==History== \nMandleshwar is {{convert|8|km}} from [[Maheshwar]], capital of the [[Holkar]] states.\n\nThe eighth-century philosopher [[Ma\u1e47\u1e0dana Mi\u015bra]] reportedly lived in the town and debated with [[Adi Shankara|Aadya Guru Shankarachaarya]] at the Gupteshwar Mahadev Temple. \n\nThe British Raj is memorialized in the [[Sub-Divisional Magistrate]], PWD office, the district jail, fort and the 'ghat'. ('Ghat' means a flight of steps leading down to a waterfront.) Mandleshwar was the headquarters for the Nimar Agency and cantonment from 1819 to 1864. In 1823, it became the headquarters for the District of Nimar (which, until 1864, was managed by the agent of the governor-general at Indore. \n\nRiver Narmada is considered by the Hindus to be a holy river and Mandleshwar has tanks, temples and ghats. Hindu temples here include Shree Gupteshwar Mahadev Mandir, Chhappan-Dev, Shree Ram Temple, Shree Datta Temple, Ganga-Zira, and Kaashi Vishweshwar Temple. Dhawal-kunda and Hathani (islands), Sahastradhara, and Ram kund are other places of historical significance. A flight of 123 steps leads down to the river and expands into the Ram Ghat, where the Ram, Hanuman, Dattatraya and Ratneshwar Temples are located. Ghat is located is at a narrow point of the Narmada River where, during the [[monsoon]], the river often rises {{convert|60|ft}} above its normal level, hence those many steps. \n\nMandleshwar also has a temple dedicated to [[Brahma Chaitanya|Brahmachaitanya Maharaj Gondwalekar]]. \n\n[[Vasudevanand Saraswati]] (a saint) lived in Mandleshwar for a long time. \n\n[[Swami Vivekananda]] reportedly lived in the town on his way to [[Raipur]]. \n\n[[Vinoba Bhave]], an advocate of nonviolence and human rights, visited Mandleshwar; [[Indira Gandhi]] visited in 1971 to inaugurate the water-supply-system plant run by the [[Public Health Engineering Department]] and the [[Government of Madhya Pradesh]].\n\nThe Maheshwar Dam produce 400 MW of electricity.{{cn|date=June 2016}} A one-kilometer bridge crosses the river.\n\n==Geography==\nMandleshwar is located at {{Coord|22.18|N|75.67|E|}},<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/35/Mandleshwar.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc \u2013 Mandleshwar]</ref> and has an average elevation of 153&nbsp;metres (501&nbsp;feet).\n\n==Demographics==\nIn the 2001 India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> the town had a population of 11,345. Males made up 51 percent of the population, and females 49 percent. Mandleshwar had an average literacy rate of 68 percent, higher than the national average of 59.5 percent; male literacy was 76 percent, and female literacy 59 percent. Fourteen percent of the population was under six years of age.\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Mandleshwar \n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|77.83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|18.15}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|1.89}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.03}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|1.15}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Sikh]]s (0.49%), [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.01%).</small>\n}}\n\n==Economy==\nMandleshwar's economy is largely based on [[agriculture]], and it is noted for [[Hydroelectricity|hydroelectric power generation]]. The Maheshwar Hydro-electric Project (10 X 40 MW) is under construction between Mandleshwar and the village of Jalud.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==Education==  \nThe Charak Institute of Pharmacy and the Sardar Patel Institute of Technology and Management, an engineering college, are located in Mandleshwar. The town has one government college, three private colleges, the Sardar Patel International School Mandleshwar, two government higher secondary schools and nine public schools Among them 2 are CBSE affiliated schools and most popular ones in the town \"sandipani Academy\" and \"Shri kanwartara senior secondary school\". An organization, Maa Umiya Sansthan, operates a higher secondary school affiliated to the M. P. Board in Bhopal, a women's college, a B. Ed college and a women's hostel serving students from across India. Courses are offered by the Shri Umiya Girls College in [[bioinformatics]] (a three-year degree), [[biotechnology]] and computer science. Mandleshwar's oldest school is the Mahatma Gandhi Govt Higher Secondary School, established in 1947 and the only school within a 50-km radius at the time.\n\n==Culture==\nFestivals celebrated in Mandleshwar include [[Holi]], [[Diwali]], [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]], [[Christmas]], [[Guru Nanak Gurpurab|Gurunanak Jayanti]], Narmada Jayanti, Gangour Navratri, and [[Ganesh Chaturthi]]. [[Gangaur]] is the most popular.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==Access==\nMandleshwar can be reached by road from [[Indore]], [[Dhamnod]], [[Omkareshwar]], [[Barwaha]], and [[Khargone]], with direct bus service available from [[Ujjain]] and Indore.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Indore Division}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Khargone district]]\n[[Category:Khargone]]\n[[Category:Religion in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4043:2e04:2808::dca:2210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandleshwar"}
{"title_page": "Kleinstaaterei", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{History of Germany}}\n[[File:HRR 1789 EN.png|thumb|Map showing the Holy Roman Empire in 1789]]\n[[File:Deutscher Bund.png|thumb|right|The 39-state German Confederation (1815\u20131866) still included several microscopic states.]]\n[[File:Kleinstaaterei 1834.jpg|thumb|left|A German cartoon from 1834 poking fun at the microscopic size of the [[Principality of Schaumburg-Lippe]], one of the many tiny states of the German Confederation]]\n[[File:Zollschranken.jpg|thumb|left|Early 19th century anti-Kleinstaaterei cartoon calling for the elimination of the myriad custom barriers between statelets]]\n[[File:Principality of Ansbach 1791.png|thumb|right|The hyper-fragmented [[Principality of Ansbach]]]]\n[[File:Locator Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge (1560).svg|thumb|right|The ancient [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]], with its tormented geography, was the French-speaking counterpart of German Kleinstaaterei. Li\u00e8ge was part of the Holy Roman Empire for 800 years.]]\n'''{{lang|de|Kleinstaaterei}}''' ({{IPA-de|\u02cckla\u026an\u0283ta\u02d0t\u0259\u02c8\u0281a\u026a|lang}}, ''\"small-state[[wikt:-ery#English|-ery]]\"'') is a German word used, often pejoratively, to denote the territorial fragmentation in Germany and neighboring regions during the [[Holy Roman Empire]] (especially after the end of the [[Thirty Years' War]]) and during the [[German Confederation]] in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>Historian J. Whaley defines {{lang|de|Kleinstaaterei}} as \"A (pejorative) term coined in the early 19th century to denote the extreme territorial fragmentation of the Reich\". J. Whaley, ''Germany and the Holy Roman Empire (1493\u20131806)'', Oxford University Press, 2011, vol. 2, p. 653 (Glossary).</ref> It refers to the large number of virtually sovereign small and medium-sized secular and ecclesiastical principalities and Free Imperial cities, some of which were little larger than a single town or the grounds of the monastery of an [[List of Imperial abbeys|Imperial abbey]]. Estimates of the total number of German states at any given time during the 18th century vary, ranging from 294 to 348<ref>The Times, ''Atlas of European History'', Harper Collins, 1994, p. 127</ref> or more.\n\nFurthermore, many German states were composed of two or more non-contiguous parts, often politically united through a marriage. Most states had at least one or two [[enclave]]s or [[exclave]]s, and some considerably more. In the summer of 1789, young [[Wilhelm von Humboldt]] and some friends, leaving [[Braunschweig|Brunswick]], capital of the [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel]], for France to observe the revolutionary events unfolding in Paris, needed to enter and exit six duchies, four bishoprics and one Free Imperial City (Aachen) before reaching the French border.<ref>E. D. Brose, ''German History 1789\u20131871, From the Holy Roman Empire to the Bismarckian Reich'', Berghahn Books, 1997, p. 4.</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe powerful and autonomous German [[Stem duchy|stem duchies]], that already existed before the demise of the [[Carolingian Empire]] and the formation of [[East Francia]] during the 9th century have basically shaped the federal character of the kingdom. Unlike in other European kingdoms, a college of the [[Princes of the Holy Roman Empire|Imperial princes]] elected the king from among the territorial dukes after the Carolingian line had died out around the year 898.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/gnd115495622.html#ndbcontent |title=Lambert von Spoleto  |publisher= Deutsche Biographie  | date=   | author=  | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref> This system prevented the development of a strong centralized monarchy as local rulers, who sought to promote their own interests and autonomy often rebelled against the sovereign ruler and conflicts had to be solved on the battlefield.<ref name=\"Solsten1999\">{{cite book|author=Eric Solsten|title=Germany: A Country Study|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vnocWI0_fywC&pg=PR24|date=August 1999|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-0-7881-8179-5|pages=24\u2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Interregnum (Holy Roman Empire)|imperial interregna]] between 1245 and 1312 and between 1378 and 1433 increased political instability and strengthened the communal movements, such as the [[Swabian League of Cities]], the [[Hanseatic League]] and the [[Swiss Confederacy]]. [[Feud]]ing among the lesser ''Territorial nobility'', who received their [[fief]] from the [[Imperial Estate|territorial princes]] lead to conflicts such as the [[Thuringian Counts' War]] and further territorial fragmentation. The [[Free imperial city|Free imperial cities]], many of them founded by the German kings and emperors during the 10th to 13th century, had initially been administered by the ''Imperial nobility'' (''{{lang|de|[[Vogt|V\u00f6gte]]}}''), direct vassals of the emperor. These towns gradually gained independence as their [[Patrician (post-Roman Europe)|patrician]] city magistrates assumed full control of administration and justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holyromanempireassociation.com/imperial-nobility-of-germany.html  |title=The Imperial Nobility of Germany  |publisher= Holy Roman Empire Association  | date=  | author=  | accessdate= April 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Imperial Cities or Towns |volume=14 |page=342 |first=Arthur William |last=Holland}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unterrichtstools.ch/ |title= Warum gibt es die Schweiz? - 2.1.1. Das Heilige R\u00f6mische Reich  |publisher= Unterrichstools Schweiz  | date=   | author=  | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first=David | last=Nicholas | title=The Growth of the Medieval City: From Late Antiquity to the Early Fourteenth Century | publisher=Longman | year=1997 | pages=69\u201372, 133\u201342, 202\u201320, 244\u201345, 300\u2013307}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>The political fragmentation of the Empire was the single most salient characteristic of German history throughout the ''[[early modern]]'' period; it underlay and conditioned development in all areas of public life.<ref>John Gagliardo, ''Germany Under the Old Regime, 1600-1790'', Longman, 1991, p. viii.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile in other European kingdoms such as France, coherent [[nation state]]s emerged as a result of [[early modern period|early modern]] ideas of political concentration and centralisation, the [[Habsburg]] dynasty, who already controlled the Duchy of Austria, [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], ruled the Holy Roman Empire since 1438 and managed to permanently occupy the imperial throne until 1806 (with a brief exception between 1742 and 1745). The Habsburg family, however pursued its ''Grand Strateg''y policy, that focused on long-term dynastic reign at the center of a vast, multi-layered and multi-ethnic realm against [[House of Bourbon|Bourbon France]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The imperial lands rather served to retain buffer zones, that were at odds with any concepts of patriotism and national identity.<ref name=\"Mitchell2018\">{{cite book|author=A. Wess Mitchell|title=The Grand Strategy of the Habsburg Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qxtEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA307|date=26 June 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8996-9|pages=307\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TeichPorter1993\">{{cite book|author1=Mikulas Teich|author2=Roy Porter|author3=Former Professor of the Social History of Medicine Wellcome Trust Centre for the History of Medicine Roy Porter|title=The National Question in Europe in Historical Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hu2SnETtV3kC&pg=PA153|date=6 May 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-36441-6|pages=153\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1495 emperor [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] attempted to [[Imperial Reform|reform]] the empire. An Imperial supreme court (''Reichskammergericht'') was established, imperial taxes were levied, and the power of the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]] (''Reichstag'') was increased. The reforms, however, were frustrated by the continued territorial fragmentation of the Empire.<ref name=\"Whaley2012\">{{cite book|author=Joachim Whaley|title=Germany and the Holy Roman Empire: Volume I: Maximilian I to the Peace of Westphalia, 1493-1648|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UiFWYsG-t7UC|year=2012|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-873101-6}}</ref> The [[Reformation|Protestant Reformation]] represented a major threat to imperial integrity. Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] stated in 1546: ''...if we failed to intervene now, all the Estates of Germany would be in danger of breaking with the faith...''. With the 1548 [[Augsburg Interim]] he attempted to reconcile the religious schism in Germany, but instead only prompted new Protestant defiance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assets.press.princeton.edu/chapters/s8934.pdf |title= The Struggle for Power in Early Modern Europe  | publisher = Princeton University Press |date=   |author=Daniel H. Nexon |accessdate= May 18, 2019  }}</ref>\n\nSince the 17th century the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] emerged as the second dominant power, that also incorporated substantial non-German territories and lands beyond the borders of the empire, while excluding major parts of Germany proper.<ref name=\"Solsten1999\"/><ref name=\"Bendix1980\">{{cite book|author=Reinhard Bendix|title=Kings Or People: Power and the Mandate to Rule|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxAb4kAtzMYC&pg=PA141|date=8 April 1980|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04090-8|pages=141\u2013}}</ref>\n\nApart from these two states, the Holy Roman Empire consisted of hundreds of small, German-speaking [[principality|principalities]], most of which derived from successive [[dynastic]] splits ([[feudal fragmentation]]), sometimes reflected in compound names such as [[Saxe-Coburg]]; some of these were united through royal marriages, although the resulting entity was often not a contiguous territory. During the early modern period, these small states modernised their military, judicial, and economic administrations. These hardly existed at the imperial level, and the emperor was little more than a [[feudalism|feudalistic]] [[confederation|confederal]] figurehead, without political or military clout. After the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]], the Empire's small states were divided along religious lines. Those headed by Roman Catholic dynasties faced those ruled by [[Protestantism|Protestant]] dynasties in the [[Thirty Years' War]] and other conflicts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.helsinki.fi/iehc2006/papers3/Denzel106.pdf  |title=State and Finance in the Holy Roman Empire from c.1650 to c.1800  |publisher= University of Helsinki  | date=   | author= Markus A. Denzel | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Solsten1999\"/>\n\nAfter French Emperor [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] forced the Holy Roman Emperor, [[Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor|Francis II]], to dissolve the Empire in 1806, ''Kleinstaaterei'' was altered, but not eliminated. Through the elimination of territories ruled by [[prince-bishop]]s ([[secularisation]]) and through the [[German mediatization|consolidation of neighbouring principalities, enclaves and exclaves]], Napoleon reduced several hundred states into a relative concentration of a little over two dozen states in the [[Confederation of the Rhine]]. This confederation did not survive Napoleon's military defeat at the hands of the allies, but the previous principalities were not entirely restored. [[Prussia]] and the [[Austrian Empire]]\u2014the successor state to the Habsburg Monarchy\u2014were the only major German powers, and neither had been part of the Confederation of the Rhine. The victorious allies, including Prussia and Austria, decided at the [[Congress of Vienna]] (1814\u201315) on widespread dynastic [[European Restoration|restorations]], although some of Napoleon's consolidations were maintained, and Austria and Prussia helped themselves to some formerly independent territories. The resulting territorial division resulted in a consolidated version\u2014around 40 states\u2014of the pre-Napoleonic ''Kleinstaaterei''.\n\nThe rise of [[nationalism]] across Europe brought movements striving for \"[[Nation state|nation-states]]\", each governing an entire (ethno-cultural) [[Race (human classification)|people]]. [[German nationalism|German nationalists]] began to insist on a unified Germany. The call for a unified nation-state was one of the central demands of the [[Revolutions of 1848]], but the ruling dynasties of the smaller German states and of multinational Austria and Prussia managed to resist nationalist efforts at unification. Also German writer and statesman Goethe had always opposed this, writing: \"Frankfurt, Bremen, Hamburg, Luebeck are large and brilliant, and their impact on the prosperity of Germany is incalculable. Yet, would they remain what they are if they were to lose their independence and be incorporated as provincial cities into one great German Empire? I have reason to doubt this.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mises.org/library/politics-johann-wolfgang-goethe  |title=The Politics of Johann Wolfgang Goethe  |publisher= Mises Institute  | date=February 1, 2012   | author= Hans-Hermann Hoppe | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOnly after [[Prussia]]n Chancellor [[Otto von Bismarck]] gradually built a unified German state under the Prussian royal [[house of Hohenzollern]] did ''Kleinstaaterei'' largely end in 1871 with the founding of the [[German Empire]]. (The only surviving petty states\u2014[[Luxembourg]] and [[Liechtenstein]]\u2014lie at the periphery of the German-speaking world.) The founding of the German Empire created a largely German nation-state. While the German Empire excluded the partly German but multinational [[Habsburg]] domains of [[Austria-Hungary|Austria\u2013Hungary]], it included a substantial Polish minority in parts of eastern Prussia and other minorities along its northern and western borders.<ref name=build>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/14039014 |title= Building the Nation among Visions of German Empire |journal= Stefan Berger/Alexei Miller (Eds.): National Empires, Pp. 247-308 | publisher = Academia |date=    |author=Stefan Berger  |accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref> The unification of the German Empire put Germany on the map as a [[world power|major European power]], albeit too late to become a major [[German colonial empire|colonial presence]].  Internally in the nation some of these fragmented boundaries and small political units continued to exist until the modern [[States of Germany]] were established in the Federal Republic after [[World War II]].\n\nThe decentralised nature of ''Kleinstaaterei'' made it difficult for the German economy to live up to its potential. Varying systems of weights and measures, different currencies and numerous [[tariff]]s impeded trade and investment, although the creation of the [[Zollverein|German Customs Union]] had begun to lift these barriers.<ref>{{citation | first=Richard | last=Tilly | chapter=Germany: 1815\u20131870 | editor-first=Rondo |editor-last=Cameron | title=Banking in the Early Stages of Industrialization: A Study in Comparative Economic History | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=1967 | pages=151\u2013182}}</ref> The startling rapidity of Germany's economic growth after unification under Bismarck provided further evidence that the ''Kleinstaaterei'' had been economically repressive. The system did contribute to cultural diversity within Germany, and the numerous rival courts\u2014though usually politically insignificant\u2014often gained some renown through [[patronage]].\n\n==Modern German usage==\nToday,  the term ''Kleinstaaterei'' is sometimes used in the German media and elsewhere in a figurative sense to describe the [[Politics of Germany|German political system]] of [[federation|federalism]] in a critical way, especially referring to its seeming inefficiency to decide on reforms in political fields that are the responsibility of the ''[[States of Germany|L\u00e4nder]]'' and thus are under the auspices of sixteen different administrations. As of 2010, ''Kleinstaaterei'' is most often invoked in matters of [[Education|educational policy]], such as the difficulties caused by the different school systems for children of families that move from one ''Land'' to another.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Balkanisation]]\n* [[List of Imperial Diet participants (1792)]]\n* [[List of states in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n* [[Petty kingdom]]\n* [[Federalism in Germany]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Political history of Germany]]\n[[Category:Political history of the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:German words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{History of Germany}}\n[[File:HRR 1789 EN.png|thumb|Map showing the Holy Roman Empire in 1789]]\n[[File:Deutscher Bund.png|thumb|right|The 39-state German Confederation (1815\u20131866) still included several microscopic states.]]\n[[File:Kleinstaaterei 1834.jpg|thumb|left|A German cartoon from 1834 poking fun at the microscopic size of the [[Principality of Schaumburg-Lippe]], one of the many tiny states of the German Confederation]]\n[[File:Zollschranken.jpg|thumb|left|Early 19th century anti-Kleinstaaterei cartoon calling for the elimination of the myriad custom barriers between statelets]]\n[[File:Principality of Ansbach 1791.png|thumb|right|The hyper-fragmented [[Principality of Ansbach]]]]\n[[File:Locator Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge (1560).svg|thumb|right|The ancient [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]], with its tormented geography, was the French-speaking counterpart of German Kleinstaaterei. Li\u00e8ge was part of the Holy Roman Empire for 800 years.]]\n'''{{lang|de|Kleinstaaterei}}''' ({{IPA-de|\u02cckla\u026an\u0283ta\u02d0t\u0259\u02c8\u0281a\u026a|lang}}, ''\"small-state[[wikt:-ery#English|-ery]]\"'') is a German word used, often pejoratively, to denote the territorial fragmentation in Germany and neighboring regions during the [[Holy Roman Empire]] (especially after the end of the [[Thirty Years' War]]) and during the [[German Confederation]] in the first half of the 19th century.<ref>Historian J. Whaley defines {{lang|de|Kleinstaaterei}} as \"A (pejorative) term coined in the early 19th century to denote the extreme territorial fragmentation of the Reich\". J. Whaley, ''Germany and the Holy Roman Empire (1493\u20131806)'', Oxford University Press, 2011, vol. 2, p. 653 (Glossary).</ref> It refers to the large number of virtually sovereign small and medium-sized secular and ecclesiastical principalities and Free Imperial cities, some of which were little larger than a single town or the grounds of the monastery of an [[List of Imperial abbeys|Imperial abbey]]. Estimates of the total number of German states at any given time during the 18th century vary, ranging from 294 to 348<ref>The Times, ''Atlas of European History'', Harper Collins, 1994, p. 127</ref> or more.\n\nFurthermore, many German states were composed of two or more non-contiguous parts, often politically united through a marriage. Most states had at least one or two [[enclave]]s or [[exclave]]s, and some considerably more. In the summer of 1789, young [[Wilhelm von Humboldt]] and some friends, leaving [[Braunschweig|Brunswick]], capital of the [[Principality of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel]], for France to observe the revolutionary events unfolding in Paris, needed to enter and exit six duchies, four bishoprics and one Free Imperial City (Aachen) before reaching the French border.<ref>E. D. Brose, ''German History 1789\u20131871, From the Holy Roman Empire to the Bismarckian Reich'', Berghahn Books, 1997, p. 4.</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe powerful and autonomous German [[Stem duchy|stem duchies]], that already existed before the demise of the [[Carolingian Empire]] and the formation of [[East Francia]] during the 9th century have basically shaped the federal character of the kingdom. Unlike in other European kingdoms, a college of the [[Princes of the Holy Roman Empire|Imperial princes]] elected the king among one of the territorial dukes after the Carolingian line had died out around the year 898.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/gnd115495622.html#ndbcontent |title=Lambert von Spoleto  |publisher= Deutsche Biographie  | date=   | author=  | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref> This system prevented the development of a strong centralized monarchy as local rulers, who sought to promote their own interests and autonomy often rebelled against the sovereign ruler and conflicts had to be solved on the battlefield.<ref name=\"Solsten1999\">{{cite book|author=Eric Solsten|title=Germany: A Country Study|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vnocWI0_fywC&pg=PR24|date=August 1999|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-0-7881-8179-5|pages=24\u2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Interregnum (Holy Roman Empire)|imperial interregna]] between 1245 and 1312 and between 1378 and 1433 increased political instability and strengthened the communal movements, such as the [[Swabian League of Cities]], the [[Hanseatic League]] and the [[Swiss Confederacy]]. [[Feud]]ing among the lesser ''Territorial nobility'', who received their [[fief]] from the [[Imperial Estate|territorial princes]] lead to conflicts such as the [[Thuringian Counts' War]] and further territorial fragmentation. The [[Free imperial city|Free imperial cities]], many of them founded by the German kings and emperors during the 10th to 13th century, had initially been administered by the ''Imperial nobility'' (''{{lang|de|[[Vogt|V\u00f6gte]]}}''), direct vassals of the emperor. These towns gradually gained independence as their [[Patrician (post-Roman Europe)|patrician]] city magistrates assumed full control of administration and justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holyromanempireassociation.com/imperial-nobility-of-germany.html  |title=The Imperial Nobility of Germany  |publisher= Holy Roman Empire Association  | date=  | author=  | accessdate= April 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Imperial Cities or Towns |volume=14 |page=342 |first=Arthur William |last=Holland}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unterrichtstools.ch/ |title= Warum gibt es die Schweiz? - 2.1.1. Das Heilige R\u00f6mische Reich  |publisher= Unterrichstools Schweiz  | date=   | author=  | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first=David | last=Nicholas | title=The Growth of the Medieval City: From Late Antiquity to the Early Fourteenth Century | publisher=Longman | year=1997 | pages=69\u201372, 133\u201342, 202\u201320, 244\u201345, 300\u2013307}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>The political fragmentation of the Empire was the single most salient characteristic of German history throughout the ''[[early modern]]'' period; it underlay and conditioned development in all areas of public life.<ref>John Gagliardo, ''Germany Under the Old Regime, 1600-1790'', Longman, 1991, p. viii.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile in other European kingdoms such as France, coherent [[nation state]]s emerged as a result of [[early modern period|early modern]] ideas of political concentration and centralisation, the [[Habsburg]] dynasty, who already controlled the Duchy of Austria, [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]], ruled the Holy Roman Empire since 1438 and managed to permanently occupy the imperial throne until 1806 (with a brief exception between 1742 and 1745). The Habsburg family, however pursued its ''Grand Strateg''y policy, that focused on long-term dynastic reign at the center of a vast, multi-layered and multi-ethnic realm against [[House of Bourbon|Bourbon France]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The imperial lands rather served to retain buffer zones, that were at odds with any concepts of patriotism and national identity.<ref name=\"Mitchell2018\">{{cite book|author=A. Wess Mitchell|title=The Grand Strategy of the Habsburg Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qxtEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA307|date=26 June 2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-8996-9|pages=307\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TeichPorter1993\">{{cite book|author1=Mikulas Teich|author2=Roy Porter|author3=Former Professor of the Social History of Medicine Wellcome Trust Centre for the History of Medicine Roy Porter|title=The National Question in Europe in Historical Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hu2SnETtV3kC&pg=PA153|date=6 May 1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-36441-6|pages=153\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1495 emperor [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] attempted to [[Imperial Reform|reform]] the empire. An Imperial supreme court (''Reichskammergericht'') was established, imperial taxes were levied, and the power of the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]] (''Reichstag'') was increased. The reforms, however, were frustrated by the continued territorial fragmentation of the Empire.<ref name=\"Whaley2012\">{{cite book|author=Joachim Whaley|title=Germany and the Holy Roman Empire: Volume I: Maximilian I to the Peace of Westphalia, 1493-1648|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UiFWYsG-t7UC|year=2012|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-873101-6}}</ref> The [[Reformation|Protestant Reformation]] represented a major threat to imperial integrity. Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] stated in 1546: ''...if we failed to intervene now, all the Estates of Germany would be in danger of breaking with the faith...''. With the 1548 [[Augsburg Interim]] he attempted to reconcile the religious schism in Germany, but instead only prompted new Protestant defiance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assets.press.princeton.edu/chapters/s8934.pdf |title= The Struggle for Power in Early Modern Europe  | publisher = Princeton University Press |date=   |author=Daniel H. Nexon |accessdate= May 18, 2019  }}</ref>\n\nSince the 17th century the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] emerged as the second dominant power, that also incorporated substantial non-German territories and lands beyond the borders of the empire, while excluding major parts of Germany proper.<ref name=\"Solsten1999\"/><ref name=\"Bendix1980\">{{cite book|author=Reinhard Bendix|title=Kings Or People: Power and the Mandate to Rule|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxAb4kAtzMYC&pg=PA141|date=8 April 1980|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04090-8|pages=141\u2013}}</ref>\n\nApart from these two states, the Holy Roman Empire consisted of hundreds of small, German-speaking [[principality|principalities]], most of which derived from successive [[dynastic]] splits ([[feudal fragmentation]]), sometimes reflected in compound names such as [[Saxe-Coburg]]; some of these were united through royal marriages, although the resulting entity was often not a contiguous territory. During the early modern period, these small states modernised their military, judicial, and economic administrations. These hardly existed at the imperial level, and the emperor was little more than a [[feudalism|feudalistic]] [[confederation|confederal]] figurehead, without political or military clout. After the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]], the Empire's small states were divided along religious lines. Those headed by Roman Catholic dynasties faced those ruled by [[Protestantism|Protestant]] dynasties in the [[Thirty Years' War]] and other conflicts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.helsinki.fi/iehc2006/papers3/Denzel106.pdf  |title=State and Finance in the Holy Roman Empire from c.1650 to c.1800  |publisher= University of Helsinki  | date=   | author= Markus A. Denzel | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Solsten1999\"/>\n\nAfter French Emperor [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] forced the Holy Roman Emperor, [[Francis II, Holy Roman Emperor|Francis II]], to dissolve the Empire in 1806, ''Kleinstaaterei'' was altered, but not eliminated. Through the elimination of territories ruled by [[prince-bishop]]s ([[secularisation]]) and through the [[German mediatization|consolidation of neighbouring principalities, enclaves and exclaves]], Napoleon reduced several hundred states into a relative concentration of a little over two dozen states in the [[Confederation of the Rhine]]. This confederation did not survive Napoleon's military defeat at the hands of the allies, but the previous principalities were not entirely restored. [[Prussia]] and the [[Austrian Empire]]\u2014the successor state to the Habsburg Monarchy\u2014were the only major German powers, and neither had been part of the Confederation of the Rhine. The victorious allies, including Prussia and Austria, decided at the [[Congress of Vienna]] (1814\u201315) on widespread dynastic [[European Restoration|restorations]], although some of Napoleon's consolidations were maintained, and Austria and Prussia helped themselves to some formerly independent territories. The resulting territorial division resulted in a consolidated version\u2014around 40 states\u2014of the pre-Napoleonic ''Kleinstaaterei''.\n\nThe rise of [[nationalism]] across Europe brought movements striving for \"[[Nation state|nation-states]]\", each governing an entire (ethno-cultural) [[Race (human classification)|people]]. [[German nationalism|German nationalists]] began to insist on a unified Germany. The call for a unified nation-state was one of the central demands of the [[Revolutions of 1848]], but the ruling dynasties of the smaller German states and of multinational Austria and Prussia managed to resist nationalist efforts at unification. Also German writer and statesman Goethe had always opposed this, writing: \"Frankfurt, Bremen, Hamburg, Luebeck are large and brilliant, and their impact on the prosperity of Germany is incalculable. Yet, would they remain what they are if they were to lose their independence and be incorporated as provincial cities into one great German Empire? I have reason to doubt this.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mises.org/library/politics-johann-wolfgang-goethe  |title=The Politics of Johann Wolfgang Goethe  |publisher= Mises Institute  | date=February 1, 2012   | author= Hans-Hermann Hoppe | accessdate= May 17, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOnly after [[Prussia]]n Chancellor [[Otto von Bismarck]] gradually built a unified German state under the Prussian royal [[house of Hohenzollern]] did ''Kleinstaaterei'' largely end in 1871 with the founding of the [[German Empire]]. (The only surviving petty states\u2014[[Luxembourg]] and [[Liechtenstein]]\u2014lie at the periphery of the German-speaking world.) The founding of the German Empire created a largely German nation-state. While the German Empire excluded the partly German but multinational [[Habsburg]] domains of [[Austria-Hungary|Austria\u2013Hungary]], it included a substantial Polish minority in parts of eastern Prussia and other minorities along its northern and western borders.<ref name=build>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/14039014 |title= Building the Nation among Visions of German Empire |journal= Stefan Berger/Alexei Miller (Eds.): National Empires, Pp. 247-308 | publisher = Academia |date=    |author=Stefan Berger  |accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref> The unification of the German Empire put Germany on the map as a [[world power|major European power]], albeit too late to become a major [[German colonial empire|colonial presence]].  Internally in the nation some of these fragmented boundaries and small political units continued to exist until the modern [[States of Germany]] were established in the Federal Republic after [[World War II]].\n\nThe decentralised nature of ''Kleinstaaterei'' made it difficult for the German economy to live up to its potential. Varying systems of weights and measures, different currencies and numerous [[tariff]]s impeded trade and investment, although the creation of the [[Zollverein|German Customs Union]] had begun to lift these barriers.<ref>{{citation | first=Richard | last=Tilly | chapter=Germany: 1815\u20131870 | editor-first=Rondo |editor-last=Cameron | title=Banking in the Early Stages of Industrialization: A Study in Comparative Economic History | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=1967 | pages=151\u2013182}}</ref> The startling rapidity of Germany's economic growth after unification under Bismarck provided further evidence that the ''Kleinstaaterei'' had been economically repressive. The system did contribute to cultural diversity within Germany, and the numerous rival courts\u2014though usually politically insignificant\u2014often gained some renown through [[patronage]].\n\n==Modern German usage==\nToday,  the term ''Kleinstaaterei'' is sometimes used in the German media and elsewhere in a figurative sense to describe the [[Politics of Germany|German political system]] of [[federation|federalism]] in a critical way, especially referring to its seeming inefficiency to decide on reforms in political fields that are the responsibility of the ''[[States of Germany|L\u00e4nder]]'' and thus are under the auspices of sixteen different administrations. As of 2010, ''Kleinstaaterei'' is most often invoked in matters of [[Education|educational policy]], such as the difficulties caused by the different school systems for children of families that move from one ''Land'' to another.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Balkanisation]]\n* [[List of Imperial Diet participants (1792)]]\n* [[List of states in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n* [[Petty kingdom]]\n* [[Federalism in Germany]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Political history of Germany]]\n[[Category:Political history of the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:German words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kleinstaaterei"}
{"title_page": "Eric Yuan", "text_new": "{{short description|American billionaire businessman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Eric Yuan\n| image        =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Eric S. Yuan, \u8881\u5f81\n| birth_date   = {{birth based on age as of date|49|2019|04|19}}<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2019/04/19/zoom-zoom-zoom-the-exclusive-inside-story-of-the-new-billionaire-behind-techs-hottest-ipo/|title=Zoom, Zoom, Zoom! The Exclusive Inside Story Of The New Billionaire Behind Tech's Hottest IPO|first=Alex|last=Konrad|date=|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Tai'an]], [[Shandong]], China\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = United States <ref> https://radio.foxnews.com/2019/07/31/ceo-eric-yuan-zooms-past-obstacles/ </ref>\n| education    = [[Shandong University of Science and Technology]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| known for    = CEO of Zoom, Technical VC at WebEx and Cisco<ref name=Forbes />\n| home_town    = Santa Clara, California<ref name=ForbesProfile>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/eric-yuan/|title=Forbes Profile Page|website=www.forbes.com}}</ref>\n| salary       = \n| networth     = US$7.4 billion (2020)<ref name=\"Bloomberg<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeff Bezos Gains $24 Billion While World's Rich Reap Bailout Rewards |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-14/bezos-gains-24-billion-while-world-s-rich-reap-bailout-rewards |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\"/>\n| title        = Founder and CEO, [[Zoom Video Communications]]\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| boards       = \n| spouse       = Married\n| children     = 3 <ref name=ForbesProfile></ref>\n| parents      = \n| relatives    = \n| website      =\n}}\n'''Eric S. Yuan''' ({{zh|t=\u8881\u5f81|p=Yu\u00e1n Zh\u0113ng}}; born 1969/1970) is an American <ref> https://radio.foxnews.com/2019/07/31/ceo-eric-yuan-zooms-past-obstacles/ </ref> [[billionaire]] businessman and the founder of cloud-based [[Zoom Video Communications]].<ref name=\"Fortune\">{{cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-social-distancing-zoom-stock-video-meetings-founder-eric-yuan-net-worth/|title=The rise of social distancing during coronavirus pandemic pushes Zoom founder's net worth up by $2 billion in 2020|last=Pendleton|first=Devon|date=21 March 2020|website=www.fortune.com|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> In 2020, Yuan was included on Forbes' list of billionaires, for the first time, with a net worth of [[USD|US$]]5.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/zoom-eric-yuan-forbes-billionaires-list-2020-4|title=Zoom's CEO has joined Forbes' billionaires list for the first time as use of the company's videoconferencing service skyrockets during the coronavirus outbreak|work=This is an amazing truth.[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nYuan is the son of [[mining engineer]]s. He was born and raised in [[Tai'an]], [[Shandong]] Province, China.<ref name=Forbes/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/thrive-global/the-inspiring-backstory-of-eric-s-yuan-founder-and-ceo-of-zoom-98b7fab8cacc|title=The Inspiring Backstory of Eric S. Yuan, Founder and CEO of Zoom|first=Yitzi|last=Weiner|date=2 October 2017|website=medium.com|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.21so.com/2019/weixin_0430/434641.html|title=\u8eab\u4ef7\u8d8530\u4ebf\u7f8e\u5143\uff0c\u5c71\u4e1c\"\u7801\u519c\"\u7684\u7845\u8c37\u5947\u5e7b\u6f02\u6d41\u8d22\u7ecf\u65b0\u95fb_21\u8d22\u7ecf\u641c\u7d22|website=news.21so.com|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref> He earned bachelor's and master's degrees in applied mathematics and computer science from [[Shandong University of Science and Technology]].<ref name=Forbes/> \n\nYuan worked in Japan four years after graduation. After listening to Bill Gates to talk about the dot-com bubble, he decided to move to\u00a0Silicon Valley.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=565e98d0-7f76-11ea-860e-d125f0aef2df&url=L2JpbGxpb25haXJlcy9wcm9maWxlcy9lcmljLXMteXVhbi8=|title=Eric Yuan|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nYuan moved to the US in the mid-1990s, after obtaining a visa on the ninth try<ref name=\"auto1\" /> when he was 27 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/18/zoom-ceo-eric-yuan-worth-3-billion-after-ipo-profile.html|title=Zoom's CEO emigrated from China 22 years ago and spoke little English \u2014 now he's worth almost $3 billion|last=Levy|first=Ari|date=2019-04-19|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1997, Yuan joined [[WebEx]], which was acquired by [[Cisco Systems]] in 2007; he became vice president of engineering.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  In Cisco, Yuan pitched a new smartphone-friendly video conferencing system in 2011.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/meet-zoom-billionaire-eric-yuan-career-net-worth-life|title=Meet Eric Yuan, the founder and CEO of Zoom, who has made nearly $4 billion in 3 months as usage of his video conferencing software skyrockets amid the coronavirus pandemic|last=Rogers|first=Taylor Nicole|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Due to the idea being rejected, he left his job in Cisco for founding Zoom, a video conferencing software company. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://executives.technology/eric-yuan-3/|title=Eric Yuan|date=2020-04-12|work=Executives in Technology|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn the beginning, he struggled to find investors because many of them considered that it was market covered by competence.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nUpon Zoom release like an IPO, Yuan became a billionaire. He owns a fortune of $ 7.5 billion.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nYuan married at age 22, while he was a master's student.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yuan, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Shandong University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Shandong]]\n[[Category:Cisco people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American billionaire businessman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Eric Yuan\n| image        =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Eric S. Yuan, \u8881\u5f81\n| birth_date   = {{birth based on age as of date|49|2019|04|19}}<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2019/04/19/zoom-zoom-zoom-the-exclusive-inside-story-of-the-new-billionaire-behind-techs-hottest-ipo/|title=Zoom, Zoom, Zoom! The Exclusive Inside Story Of The New Billionaire Behind Tech's Hottest IPO|first=Alex|last=Konrad|date=|website=Forbes|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Tai'an]], [[Shandong]], China\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = United States <ref> https://radio.foxnews.com/2019/07/31/ceo-eric-yuan-zooms-past-obstacles/ </ref>\n| education    = [[Shandong University of Science and Technology]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| known for    = CEO of Zoom, Technical VC at WebEx and Cisco<ref name=Forbes />\n| home_town    = Santa Clara, California<ref name=ForbesProfile>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/eric-yuan/|title=Forbes Profile Page|website=www.forbes.com}}</ref>\n| salary       = \n| networth     = US$7.4 billion (2020)<ref name=\"Bloomberg<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeff Bezos Gains $24 Billion While World's Rich Reap Bailout Rewards |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-14/bezos-gains-24-billion-while-world-s-rich-reap-bailout-rewards |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\"/>\n| title        = Founder and CEO, [[Zoom Video Communications]]\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| boards       = \n| spouse       = Married\n| children     = 3 <ref name=ForbesProfile></ref>\n| parents      = \n| relatives    = \n| website      =\n}}\n'''Eric S. Yuan''' ({{zh|t=\u8881\u5f81|p=Yu\u00e1n Zh\u0113ng}}; born 1969/1970) is an American <ref> https://radio.foxnews.com/2019/07/31/ceo-eric-yuan-zooms-past-obstacles/ </ref> [[billionaire]] businessman and the founder of cloud-based [[Zoom Video Communications]].<ref name=\"Fortune\">{{cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-social-distancing-zoom-stock-video-meetings-founder-eric-yuan-net-worth/|title=The rise of social distancing during coronavirus pandemic pushes Zoom founder's net worth up by $2 billion in 2020|last=Pendleton|first=Devon|date=21 March 2020|website=www.fortune.com|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> In 2020, Yuan was included on Forbes' list of billionaires, for the first time, with a net worth of [[USD|US$]]5.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/zoom-eric-yuan-forbes-billionaires-list-2020-4|title=Zoom's CEO has joined Forbes' billionaires list for the first time as use of the company's videoconferencing service skyrockets during the coronavirus outbreak|work=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nYuan is the son of [[mining engineer]]s. He was born and raised in [[Tai'an]], [[Shandong]] Province, China.<ref name=Forbes/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/thrive-global/the-inspiring-backstory-of-eric-s-yuan-founder-and-ceo-of-zoom-98b7fab8cacc|title=The Inspiring Backstory of Eric S. Yuan, Founder and CEO of Zoom|first=Yitzi|last=Weiner|date=2 October 2017|website=medium.com|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.21so.com/2019/weixin_0430/434641.html|title=\u8eab\u4ef7\u8d8530\u4ebf\u7f8e\u5143\uff0c\u5c71\u4e1c\"\u7801\u519c\"\u7684\u78