{"title_page": "Ruth Wightman", "text_new": "{{short description|American screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ruth Wightman\n| birth_name         = Ruth C. Wightman\n| birth_date         = August 15, 1897\n| birth_place        = Jamestown, New York, USA\n| death_date         = April 19, 1939 (aged 42)\n| death_place        = Alameda, New Mexico, USA\n| occupation         = Novelist, screenwriter\n| spouse             = [[Gouverneur Morris (author)|Gouverneur Morris]] (m. 1923)\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Ruth Wightman''' was an American screenwriter and race car driver who was married to the novelist [[Gouverneur Morris (novelist)|Gouveneur Morris]].\n\n== Biography ==\nRuth, an only child, was born in [[Jamestown, New York]], to John Wightman and Lulu Russell.\n\nEver the adventurer, she had a passion for flying, and was noted as being one of the first women in the United States to be granted a pilot's license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/348600389/?terms=%22ruth%2Bwightman%22|title=Late Deaths|last=|first=|date=20 Apr 1939|website=The Casper Star-Tribune|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> She also competed in car races in [[Stockton, California]], as a young woman, and was involved in a fatal crash in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/469145561/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Woman Auto Racer Killed; Five Other Persons Hurt|last=|first=|date=4 Mar 1918|website=The New York Tribune|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923, she married author [[Gouverneur Morris (novelist)|Governeur Morris]], for whom she had formerly worked as a secretary before beginning a career in the scenario department at [[Samuel Goldwyn Studio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/367423800/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Writers Will Eschew Golf on Second Honeymoon|last=|first=|date=28 Jul 1924|website=The Evening Sun|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> The pair kept their marriage out of the newspapers for a year, as Morris was still waiting to be granted a divorce from his first wife, Elsie; they then held a second marriage ceremony to seal the deal and comply with California law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/113683345/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Man Weds Wife|last=|first=|date=27 Jul 1924|website=The Morning Register|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\nWightman died at a sanitarium in Alameda, New Mexico, in 1939 after a brief illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/429882955/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Obituary: Wife of Noted Writer|last=|first=|date=20 Apr 1939|website=The Daily News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> She was survived by her husband; the pair had no children.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n* ''[[The Beautiful Liar]]'' (1921)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/171016066/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Screen Plays|last=|first=|date=20 Aug 1922|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Ace of Hearts (1921 film)|The Ace of Hearts]]'' (1921)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wightman, Ruth}}\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ruth Wightman\n| birth_name         = Ruth C. Wightman\n| birth_date         = August 15, 1897\n| birth_place        = Jamestown, New York, USA\n| death_date         = April 19, 1939 (aged 42)\n| death_place        = Alameda, New Mexico, USA\n| occupation         = Novelist, screenwriter\n| spouse             = [[Gouverneur Morris (author)|Gouverneur Morris]] (m. 1923)\n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Ruth Wightman''' was an American screenwriter and race car driver who was married to the novelist [[Gouverneur Morris (novelist)|Gouveneur Morris]].\n\n== Biography ==\nRuth, an only child, was born in [[Jamestown, New York]], to John Wightman and Lulu Russell.\n\nEver the adventurer, she had a passion for flying, and was noted as being one of the first women in the United States to be granted a pilot's license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/348600389/?terms=%22ruth%2Bwightman%22|title=Late Deaths|last=|first=|date=20 Apr 1939|website=The Casper Star-Tribune|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> She also competed in car races in [[Stockton, California]], as a young woman, and was involved in a fatal crash in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/469145561/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Woman Auto Racer Killed; Five Other Persons Hurt|last=|first=|date=4 Mar 1918|website=The New York Tribune|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923, she married author [[Gouverneur Morris (novelist)|Governeur Morris]], for whom she had formerly worked as a secretary before beginning a career in the scenario department at [[Samuel Goldwyn Studio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/367423800/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Writers Will Eschew Golf on Second Honeymoon|last=|first=|date=28 Jul 1924|website=The Evening Sun|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> The pair kept their marriage out of the newspapers for a year, as Morris was still waiting to be granted a divorce from his first wife, Elsie; they then held a second marriage ceremony to seal the deal and comply with California law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/113683345/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Man Weds Wife|last=|first=|date=27 Jul 1924|website=The Morning Register|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\nWightman died at a sanitarium in Alameda, New Mexico, in 1939 after a brief illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/429882955/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Obituary: Wife of Noted Writer|last=|first=|date=20 Apr 1939|website=The Daily News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> She was survived by her husband; the pair had no children.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n* ''[[The Beautiful Liar]]'' (1921)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/171016066/?terms=%22ruth+wightman%22|title=Screen Plays|last=|first=|date=20 Aug 1922|website=The Philadelphia Inquirer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Ace of Hearts (1921 film)|The Ace of Hearts]]'' (1921)\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wightman, Ruth}}\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_Wightman"}
{"title_page": "Clara Oswald", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character in the TV series Doctor Who}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Clara Oswald\n| series      = [[Doctor Who]]\n| image       = [[File:Clara Oswald.jpg|centre|200px]]\n| caption     = [[Jenna Coleman]] as Clara Oswald\n| first       = \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012)\n| last        = \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\" (2017)\n| portrayer   = [[Jenna Coleman]]\n| species     = [[Human]]\n| affiliation = [[Eleventh Doctor]]<br>[[Twelfth Doctor]]\n| home        = [[Earth]]\n}}\n'''Clara Oswald''' is a fictional character created by [[Steven Moffat]] and portrayed by [[Jenna Coleman]] in the long-running [[Television in the United Kingdom|British]] [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. First appearing in the show's [[Doctor Who (series 7)|seventh series]], Clara served as a companion of the [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] [[time travel in fiction|time traveller]] known as [[The Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]] in his [[Eleventh Doctor|eleventh]] ([[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]) and [[Twelfth Doctor|twelfth]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]) incarnations. She remains the longest serving companion since the show's revival in 2005.\n\nClara is initially presented to the audience during the seventh series as three distinct, though similarly named, people living in different eras. The first two incarnations, Oswin Oswald and Clara Oswin Oswald, each die during the episode in which they appear. The third incarnation becomes the Doctor's companion, travelling with him for the remainder of the series as he tries to uncover the mystery of her multiple lives. She continues to travel with the Doctor after the mystery is resolved at the end of the series, witnessing him regenerate into his twelfth incarnation in \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\" (2013). The pair have various adventures together in the [[Doctor Who (series 8)|eighth]] and [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] until she departs the show in \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\" (2015). She reappears briefly in the Christmas special \"[[Twice Upon A Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\" (2017).\n\nColeman's performance as Clara was well received by critics, however many of the ''Doctor Who fanbase'' have found the character very divisive.\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Television===\nOswin Oswald is introduced in the [[Doctor Who (series 7)|series 7]] premiere, \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012). She is the sole survivor of the [[starship]] ''Alaska'', which crashed on the Asylum, a prison planet for insane [[Dalek]]s. Oswin then learns from the [[Eleventh Doctor]] (Matt Smith) that she has been converted from human into a Dalek and has coped by retreating into a fantasy of her own intact survival. She assists the Doctor and his [[Companion (Doctor Who)|travelling companions]], [[Amy Pond]] ([[Karen Gillan]]) and [[Rory Williams]] ([[Arthur Darvill]]), to escape the planet unharmed, but at the cost of her own life.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Asylum of the Daleks |episode-link=Asylum of the Daleks |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Nick (director) |last2=Hurran |author-link2=Nick Hurran |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 September 2012 |season= |series-no=7 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Later, in the 2012 Christmas special \"[[The Snowmen]]\", the Doctor meets a woman named Clara Oswin Oswald, whom he initially knows only as Clara. She is a [[Victorian era|Victorian]] [[barmaid]] and [[governess]] whom the Doctor invites to be his newest companion, but who dies from an attack by one of the [[Great Intelligence]]'s minions. Seeing her full name on her tombstone and finally recognising her voice, the Doctor realises she is the same woman as Oswin from the Dalek Asylum, whom he had never seen in her human form. Intrigued by the mystery of the woman who has lived and died twice in different [[era]]s, he begins searching across time for another Clara.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Snowmen |episode-link=The Snowmen |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Saul (director) |last2=Metzstein |author-link2=Saul Metzstein |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2012 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n[[File:Dr Who Experience, Cardiff (11034641744).jpg|thumb|left|Clara's book of ''101 Places to See'' and the leaf, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nIn \"[[The Bells of Saint John]]\" (2013), Clara receives a phone number to the Doctor's time and space vessel, the [[TARDIS]], from a mysterious woman. The Doctor finds Clara Oswald (this time with no middle name) in contemporary London through her phone call, and takes her on as a companion with a goal to solving the mystery of the \"impossible girl\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Bells of Saint John |episode-link=The Bells of Saint John |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Colm (director) |last2=McCarthy |author-link2=Colm McCarthy (director) |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=30 March 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> The Doctor's repeated attempts at investigating Clara's origins over the course of \"[[The Rings of Akhaten]]\", \"[[Hide (Doctor Who)|Hide]]\", and \"[[Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS]]\" consistently turn up compelling evidence that she is just a normal young human woman.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Rings of Akhaten |episode-link=The Rings of Akhaten |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Neil (writer) |last=Cross |author-link=Neil Cross |first2=Farren (director) |last2=Blackburn |author-link2=Farren Blackburn |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=6 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=7 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Hide |episode-link=Hide (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Neil (writer) |last=Cross |author-link=Neil Cross |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Payne  |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=20 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=9 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref name=\"centre\">{{Cite episode |title=Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS |episode-link=Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steve (writer) |last=Thompson |author-link=Stephen Thompson (writer) |first2=Mat (director) |last2=King |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=27 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=10 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS\", the Doctor confronts Clara in an averted timeline about the two previous versions of her he had met, but she does not know what he is talking about.<ref name=\"centre\"/> The mystery surrounding Clara is finally resolved in \"[[The Name of the Doctor]]\" when she sacrifices her existence by entering the Doctor's timestream to undo the harm caused by the Great Intelligence ([[Richard E Grant]]). This results in the creation of numerous incarnations of Clara throughout the Doctor's history who appear to every known face of the Doctor, saving his life in numerous ways. Very few Claras are noticed by the Doctor. One version of Clara successfully persuades the [[First Doctor]] ([[William Hartnell]]) to pick the \"right\" TARDIS on his home planet [[Gallifrey]], prior to the events of the show's [[An Unearthly Child|first episode]]. Lost in the Doctor's timestream, she is eventually rescued and brought back into existence by the Eleventh Doctor.<ref name=\"name of the doctor\">{{Cite episode |title=The Name of the Doctor |episode-link=The Name of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Saul (director) |last2=Metzstein |author-link2=Saul Metzstein |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 May 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\", the show's 50th anniversary special, Clara is shown to have become a teacher at [[Coal Hill School]]. While on an adventure with the Doctor, she meets the [[Tenth Doctor]] ([[David Tennant]]) and the [[War Doctor]] ([[John Hurt]]) in person.  She manages to convince the War Doctor to change his history (and thereby save Gallifrey and his people, the [[Time Lord]]s, from destruction in the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]]), by sealing the planet in a \"parallel pocket universe\", where it remains.<ref name=TDOTD>{{Cite episode |title=The Day of the Doctor |episode-link=The Day of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Nick (director) |last2=Hurran |author-link2=Nick Hurran |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=23 November 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nIn \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\", the Time Lords try to return to the universe through a crack in time, but if they do so, the Time War will begin anew. The Doctor sends Clara home to her family at Christmas twice while the Doctor stays on the planet Trenzalore to try and prevent this war, but she returns in the TARDIS each time, after two centuries-long intervals. With the Doctor facing certain death at the end of his [[regeneration (Doctor Who)|regeneration cycle]] during this siege, she pleads with the Time Lords through the crack to save the Doctor; they grant him a new regeneration cycle and the crack closes. She then witnesses the Doctor regenerate into the [[Twelfth Doctor]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]).<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Time of the Doctor |episode-link=The Time of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Payne  |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Clara spends some time grappling with losing the Doctor she knew and loved throughout the events of \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\" (2014), until a call from the Eleventh Doctor prior to his regeneration convinces her to stay by his side and help him adjust to his new persona.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Deep Breath |episode-link=Deep Breath (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Ben (director) |last2=Wheatley |author-link2=Ben Wheatley |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=23 August 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Into the Dalek]]\", Clara and fellow teacher [[Danny Pink]] ([[Samuel Anderson (actor)|Samuel Anderson]]) agree to go for drinks together,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Into the Dalek |episode-link=Into the Dalek |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Phil |last=Ford |author-link=Phil Ford (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Ben (director) |last3=Wheatley |author-link3=Ben Wheatley |first4=Nikki (producer) |last4=Wilson |author-link4=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=30 August 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> and over the course of the episodes \"[[Listen (Doctor Who)|Listen]]\", \"[[Time Heist]]\", and \"[[The Caretaker (Doctor Who)|The Caretaker]]\", the two enter into a romantic relationship.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Listen |episode-link=Listen (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=13 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Time Heist |episode-link=Time Heist |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steve |last=Thompson |author-link=Stephen Thompson (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Douglas (director) |last3=Mackinnon |author-link3=Douglas Mackinnon |first4=Peter (producer) |last4=Bennett |author-link4=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=20 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=5 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Caretaker |episode-link=The Caretaker (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Gareth |last=Roberts |author-link=Gareth Roberts (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Paul (director) |last3=Murphy |first4=Peter (producer) |last4=Bennett |author-link4=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=27 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> For a while, she keeps secrets between the Doctor and Danny due to their misgivings about each other, and experiences turbulence in her friendship with the Doctor, particularly in \"[[Kill the Moon]]\", when he abandons her to face a traumatic decision on her own.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Kill the Moon |episode-link=Kill the Moon |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Peter (writer) |last=Harness |author-link=Peter Harness |first2=Paul (director) |last2=Wilmshurst |author-link2=Paul Wilmshurst |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=4 October 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=7 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Flatline (Doctor Who)|Flatline]]\", she is forced to take the Doctor's role in averting an alien invasion, and realises she is capable of making the same ruthless and pragmatic decisions he often has to make.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Flatline |episode-link=Flatline (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Jamie (writer) |last=Mathieson |author-link=Jamie Mathieson |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 October 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=9 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Dark Water (Doctor Who)|Dark Water]]\", Danny dies while crossing the road before Clara can announce her intent to commit to him fully. After attempting to blackmail the Doctor into changing history to avert his death, which is impossible, Clara and the Doctor decide to pursue contacting him from beyond the grave, and end up at a facility where evil Time Lord [[The Master (Doctor Who)#Missy|Missy]] ([[Michelle Gomez]]) has [[Matrix (Doctor Who)|stored the consciousnesses]] of Earth's dead as part of a plot to convert all of the deceased into an army of [[Cyberman|Cybermen]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Dark Water |episode-link=Dark Water (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Death in Heaven]]\", Missy reveals that she was the aforementioned woman who gave Clara the TARDIS telephone number and had also been secretly keeping the two together after their first meeting as part of her plan. After Danny is brought back as a Cyberman in the episode, he resists his programming in order to destroy Missy's Cyberman army and avert her plans. Two weeks after these events, Clara and the Doctor meet to say goodbye to one another. The Doctor lies to Clara; he pretends he has found Gallifrey and a home to go back to. Clara lies too; she pretends Danny returned from the dead through Missy's device, when in fact he sacrificed his opportunity to save the life of the child he killed in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episode-link=Death in Heaven |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nThe two later reunite in the 2014 Christmas special \"[[Last Christmas (Doctor Who)|Last Christmas]]\", when alien creatures induce a dream state in both the Doctor and Clara. Clara confesses that Danny is still dead, and the Doctor admits he did not find Gallifrey. Their shared dream experience on the North Pole ends with them regretting their parting. The Doctor asks Clara to resume travelling with him, and she happily agrees.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Last Christmas |episode-link=Last Christmas (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Paul (director) |last2=Wilmshurst |author-link2=Paul Wilmshurst |first3=Paul (producer) |last3=Frift |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2014 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In [[Doctor Who (series 9)|series 9]], Clara accompanies  Missy and the Doctor to [[Skaro]] when he is summoned by [[Davros]] ([[Julian Bleach]]), barely escaping the ordeal with her life.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Magician's Apprentice |episode-link=The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=19 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Witch's Familiar |episode-link=The Witch's Familiar |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=26 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Now an experienced companion, Clara shows greater confidence when dealing with alien races and volatile humans, but the Doctor finds himself concerned by her reckless streak.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Girl Who Died |episode-link=The Girl Who Died |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Jamie |last=Mathieson |author-link=Jamie Mathieson |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Ed (director) |last3=Bazalgette |first4=Derek (producer) |last4=Ritchie |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=17 October 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=5 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Clara's recklessness gets the better of her in \"[[Face the Raven]]\", when she attempts to outsmart the Doctor's adversary [[Ashildr]] ([[Maisie Williams]]) by taking on a death sentence, but later learns that it cannot be revoked. She cautions the Doctor not to give in to his darker nature in response to her passing, and faces death with bravery.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Face the Raven |episode-link=Face the Raven |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Sarah (writer) |last=Dollard |author-link=Sarah Dollard |first2=Justin (director) |last2=Molotnikov |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=21 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=10 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> She is seen once more in the following episode \"[[Heaven Sent (Doctor Who)|Heaven Sent]]\", as a grief-stricken Doctor imagines conversations with her to clarify his ideas.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Heaven Sent |episode-link=Heaven Sent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\", the Doctor uses Time Lord technology on Gallifrey to extract Clara from her last moments of life, and attempts to run away with her and cheat death. He later realises from Ashildr that travelling together will only cause more harm than good, and prepares to wipe Clara's memories of him with a device. Clara tampers with the device so that it wipes the Doctor's memories of her instead. She leaves the Doctor on Earth to start his adventures anew, and begins travelling with Ashildr in a stolen TARDIS with the intention of one day returning to Gallifrey to meet her end, although vowing to \"take the long way around\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Hell Bent |episode-link=Hell Bent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=5 December 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nIn \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\", the Doctor encounters Testimony, a futuristic organisation who use time travel to copy people's memories at the moment of death and install them in sentient glass avatars. At the end of an adventure, an avatar of [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]] restores the Doctor's memories of Clara with a mental image of her telling him not to forget her again.\n\n{{Multiple images\n| align = centre\n| footer = Costumes worn by Clara throughout the series, on display at the Doctor Who Experience\n| total_width = 1100\n| image1    = Doctor Who Experience (25307761419).jpg\n| width1 = 4288\n| height1   =  2848\n| image2 = Clara from The Snowmen (10634572106).jpg\n| width2  = 1227\n| height2 = 2439\n| image3  = Doctor Who Experience (30907346786).jpg\n| width3  = 4288\n| height3 = 2848\n| image4  = Doctor Who Experience (22764800208) (cropped).jpg\n| width4  = 1159\n| height4 = 2230\n| image5  = Doctor Who Experience (30907321066).jpg\n| width5  = 1277\n| height5 = 2964\n| image6  = Doctor Who Experience (22764798728) (cropped).jpg\n| width6  = 1045\n| height6 =  2397\n| image7  = Doctor Who Experience (25307730849).jpg\n| width7  = 2060\n| height7 = 4041\n| image8  = Doctor Who Experience (30907323426).jpg\n| width8  = 1142\n| height8 = 2450\n| image9  = Doctor Who Experience (30641592730) (cropped 2).jpg\n| width9  = 643 \n| height9 = 2140\n| image10  = Doctor Who Experience (30855116111).jpg\n| width10  = 1174\n| height10 =  2387\n\n}}\n\n===Other media===\nClara (Sophie Downham) appears in a short prelude to \"The Bells of Saint John\" as a child who talks to the Doctor at a playground. The Doctor does not realise her identity, which is revealed to the viewer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p016r6pw|title=The Bells of Saint John: A Prequel|publisher=BBC|date=23 March 2013|accessdate=23 March 2013|format=Video}}</ref> Coleman also played Clara in \"She Said, He Said\", an online prelude to \"The Name of the Doctor\" that breaks the [[fourth wall]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-05-03/doctor-who-finale-prequel-starring-matt-smith-and-jenna-louise-coleman-to-screen-via-bbc-red-button|title=Doctor Who finale prequel starring Matt Smith and Jenna-Louise Coleman to screen via BBC Red Button|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=3 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> The DVD and Blu-ray releases for Series 7 also include Coleman in a solo performance as Clara in the home media-exclusive short \"Clara and the TARDIS\".\n\nClara also features alongside the Eleventh Doctor in the [[New Series Adventures]] novel ''Shroud of Sorrow'' (2013).<ref>{{cite book |last=Donbavand |first=Tommy |author-link=Tommy Donbavand |date=11 April 2013 |title=Shroud of Sorrow |series=[[New Series Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |page= |isbn=978-1-84990-576-3 |access-date= }}</ref> From 2014, she has been featured in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] novels including: ''[[The Blood Cell]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Goss|first=James|author-link=James Goss (producer)|date=11 September 2014|title=The Blood Cell|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-774-3|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Silhouette (Doctor Who)|Silhouette]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Richards|first=Justin|author-link=Justin Richards|date=11 September 2014|title=Silhouette|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-772-9|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[The Crawling Terror]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Mike|author-link=Mike Tucker|date=11 September 2014|title=The Crawling Terror|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-773-6|access-date=}}</ref> and as of 2015, ''[[Royal Blood (Doctor Who)|Royal Blood]]''<ref>{{cite book|last=McCormack|first=Una|author-link=|date=10 September 2015|title=Royal Blood|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-992-1|access-date=}}</ref> and ''[[Deep Time (Doctor Who)|Deep Time]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Baxendale|first=Trevor|author-link=Trevor Baxendale|date=10 September 2015|title=Deep Time|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-990-7|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in [[IDW Publishing]]'s comic story ''Deadwood''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rich|last=Johnson|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2013/06/14/the-launch-of-the-powerpuff-girls-idw-solicitations-for-september-2013-including-transformers-my-little-pony-star-trek-doctor-who-gi-joe-and-locke-and-key/|title=The Launch Of The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 IDW Solicitations For September 2013, Including Transformers, My Little Pony, Star Trek, Doctor Who, GI Joe And Locke And Key|publisher=[[Bleeding Cool]]|date=14 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Clara appeared briefly in issues 11 and 12 of IDW 50th anniversary Doctor Who mini-series \"Prisoners of Time\". Beginning with Issue #462 (August 2013), Clara appears regularly in the ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' comic strips.<ref>{{Cite comic\n| writer = [[Scott Gray (writer)|Gray, Scott]]\n| penciller = [[Mike Collins (comics)|Collins, Mike]]\n| inker = [[David Roach (comics)|Roach, David A.]]\n| story = A Wing and a Prayer: Part One\n| title = [[Doctor Who Magazine]]\n| volume = \n| issue = #462\n| date = August 2013\n| publisher = [[Panini Comics]]\n| location = Tunbridge Wells\n| page = \n| panel = \n| id =\n}}</ref> In the 2015 ''Doctor Who Magazine'' comic storyline ''Blood and Ice'' (DWM #485\u2013488), Clara meets another incarnation of herself she created called \"Winnie Clarence\", a university research graduate from the year 2048.<ref>{{Cite comic\n| writer = [[Jacqueline Rayner|Rayner, Jacqueline]]\n| penciller = [[Martin Geraghty|Geraghty, Martin]]\n| inker = [[David Roach (comics)|Roach, David A]]\n| story = Blood and Ice\n| title = [[Doctor Who Magazine]]\n| volume = \n| issue = #485\u2013488\n| date = May \u2013 August 2015\n| publisher = [[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]]\n| location = Tunbridge Wells\n| page = \n| panel = \n| id =\n}}</ref>\n\n==Casting and development==\n[[File:Jenna Coleman Peabody 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Jenna Coleman plays Clara.]]\nOn 21 March 2012, it was announced that [[Jenna Coleman]] would replace [[Karen Gillan]] and [[Arthur Darvill]] as the next companion.<ref name=\"new companion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17456505|title=Doctor Who's latest companion is unveiled|publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> She auditioned for the role in secrecy, pretending it was for something called ''Men on Waves'', an anagram for \"Woman Seven\".<ref>{{cite web|first=William|last=Gallagher|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-27/doctor-who's-secret-history-of-codenames-revealed|title=Doctor Who's secret history of codenames revealed|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Executive producer and lead writer [[Steven Moffat]] chose her for the role because she worked the best alongside Smith and could talk faster than he did.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a372323/doctor-who-jenna-louise-coleman-the-press-conference-in-full.html|title='Doctor Who': Jenna-Louise Coleman&nbsp;\u2014 The press conference in full|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Coleman had never seen ''Doctor Who'' before her audition, and watched \"[[The Eleventh Hour (Doctor Who)|The Eleventh Hour]]\" (2010) and \"completely fell in love with the show\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/videos/jenna-joins-the-doctor-who-family/|title='Doctor Who': Insider&nbsp;\u2014 Jenna Joins the 'Doctor Who' Family|publisher=[[BBC America]]|format=Video|date=22 March 2013|accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> However, she only watched the first five episodes of the seventh series \u2013 the final five featuring Gillan and Darvill \u2013 because she did not want to learn more about their relationship to the Doctor, as she wanted her acting alongside Smith to be \"spontaneous\".<ref name=\"red eye\">{{cite web|first=Curt|last=Wagner|url=http://articles.redeyechicago.com/2013-03-27/entertainment/38077234_1_jenna-louise-coleman-arthur-darvill-doctor-who|title='Doctor Who': 3rd Clara's a charm for new star Coleman|work=[[RedEye]]|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> Moffat stated that her character is different from previous companions,<ref name=\"different\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/05/30/new-companion-makes-doctor-who-a-different-show-says-moffat/|title=New Companion Makes Doctor Who A Different Show, Says Moffat|work=SFX|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> though he attempted to keep the details of her character a secret until she debuted in the Christmas special.<ref name=\"BAFTA\">{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a382427/steven-moffat-on-doctor-who-sherlock-and-his-bafta-special-award.html|title=Steven Moffat on 'Doctor Who', 'Sherlock' and his BAFTA Special Award|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=19 May 2012|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> In \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012), Coleman appears as the character Oswin Oswald, a secret which was kept from the public before transmission.<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Martinovic|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a403217/steven-moffat-thanks-press-and-fans-for-saving-doctor-who-surprise.html|title=Steven Moffat thanks press and fans for saving 'Doctor Who' surprise|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Coleman was originally given the role of a Victorian governess named Jasmine, and then for the second audition she was given both the characters of Oswin and Clara. She originally thought that the producers were looking for the right character, but later realised it was part of Moffat's \"soft mystery\" plan.<ref name=\"Coleman advent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01205ht|title=Jenna-Louise Coleman: Becoming the Companion|format=Video|publisher=BBC|date=1 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"EW interview\">{{cite web|first=Clark|last=Collis|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/11/28/doctor-who-jenna-louise-coleman/|title='Doctor Who': Jenna-Louise Coleman talks about becoming the Doctor's new companion -- Exclusive|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> [[Neil Gaiman]] (writer of \"[[Nightmare in Silver]]\", 2013) revealed that the character was originally intended to stay as a Victorian governess.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Patrick|last1=Mulkern|first2=Paul|last2=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-05-15/neil-gaiman-on-re-writing-doctor-who-clara-was-originally-going-to-stay-as-a-victorian-governess|title=Neil Gaiman on re-writing Doctor Who: Clara was originally going to stay as a Victorian governess|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=15 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Coleman stated that Moffat came up with the mystery during the audition process.<ref name=\"red eye\"/> Coleman played each version of the character as individuals with \"trust that there would be a payoff\" to her mystery.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a469162/doctor-who-plot-is-mystifying-exciting-says-jenna-louise-coleman.html|title='Doctor Who' plot is \"mystifying, exciting\" says Jenna-Louise Coleman|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Moffat told [[Neil Cross]], who wrote \"[[Hide (Doctor Who)|Hide]]\" (2013), the first episode Coleman filmed as the new companion, that Clara was \"a normal girl\".<ref name=\"Cross Akhaten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten-writer-neil-cross-interview/|title=Doctor Who \"The Rings of Akhaten\": Writer Neil Cross Interview|date=5 April 2013|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nMoffat felt that the introduction of a new companion made \"the show feel different\" and brought the story to \"a new beginning\" with a different person meeting the Doctor.<ref name=\"different\"/> Executive producer Caroline Skinner remarked that her introduction allowed the series to return to a more \"classic ''Doctor Who'' format\".<ref name=\"io9 Skinner\">{{cite web|first=Meredith|last=Woerner|url=http://io9.com/5971019/producer-caroline-skinner-explains-why-doctor-who-is-getting-a-new-companion-for-christmas|title=Producer Caroline Skinner explains why Doctor Who is getting a new Companion for Christmas|publisher=[[io9]]|date=24 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Smith said that Clara was different from her predecessor [[Amy Pond]] (Gillan), which allowed the audience to see a different side of the Doctor.<ref name=\"bbc interviews\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Steven-Moffat-and-the-Cast-on-The-Snowmen| title=Steven Moffat and the Cast on The Snowmen| publisher=BBC| date=8 December 2012| accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Moffat said that Coleman brings \"a speed and wit and an unimpressed quality that makes the Doctor dance a bit harder\".<ref name=\"collider 7b\">{{cite web|first=Christina|last=Radish|url=http://collider.com/steven-moffat-doctor-who-season-7-interview/|title=Steven Moffat Talks DOCTOR WHO, His Favorite Upcoming Episodes, Writing the Doctor and Sherlock Holmes, the 50th Anniversary, and More|publisher=Collider|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Coleman stated that her character \"holds her own\" and was competitive with the Doctor, providing \"a nice double act\".<ref name=\"CNN Coleman\"/> With her place in the series' narrative, Clara was intended to reawaken the Doctor's \"curiosity in the universe and gives him his mojo back\".<ref name=\"reignite\">{{cite web|first=Justin|last=Harp|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a469255/doctor-who-star-matt-smith-clara-reignites-the-doctors-curiosity.html|title='Doctor Who' star Matt Smith: 'Clara reignites The Doctor's curiosity'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Concerning Clara's relationship to the Doctor, Coleman said, \"It's been interesting how it's changed Matt's Doctor. There is a natural bounce between them, and a flirtation, and attraction. But, again, they've always got this friction because they're a bit magnetic and drawn to each other, but she can't quite figure him out. He's got loads of secrets and he's always looking at her, trying to figure her out.\"<ref name=\"CNN Coleman\">{{cite web|first=Aaron|last=Sagers|url= http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/18/showbiz/tv/jenna-louise-coleman-doctor-who/index.html|title=Actress Jenna-Louise Coleman talks 'Doctor Who'|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> The dynamic between [[Katharine Hepburn]] and [[Spencer Tracy]] was an influence on Coleman and Smith.<ref name=\"dance\">{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a463675/jenna-louise-coleman-on-doctor-who-dynamic-its-like-a-dance.html|title=Jenna-Louise Coleman on 'Doctor Who' dynamic: 'It's like a dance'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref> In addition, Coleman revealed that Clara and the TARDIS have a \"relationship\", as there is a running joke about the TARDIS (previously established in the series as being sentient) not liking Clara or making fun of her.<ref name=\"TARDIS\">{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-04-12/doctor-whos-jenna-louise-coleman-clara-and-the-tardis-have-a-relationship--it-makes-fun-of-her|title=Doctor Who's Jenna-Louise Coleman: \"Clara and the Tardis have a relationship \u2013 it makes fun of her\"|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=12 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nMany fans and critics noticed similarities between Clara and [[Billie Piper]]'s [[Rose Tyler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2013/03/is-clara-oswin-oswald-destined-to-be-rose-tyler-20|title=Is Clara Oswin Oswald Destined to Be Rose Tyler 2.0?|work=Tor.com|date=2013-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/recaps/a592751/doctor-who-series-8-into-the-dalek-recap-meet-the-new-doctor.html|title=Doctor Who series 8 'Into the Dalek' recap: Meet the new Doctor|work=Digital Spy|date=2014-08-30}}</ref> Clara helps the Doctor recover at a dark point in his life, as Rose does during a much darker time; both companions lose a parent; each has a close relationship with the Doctor, who sees part of their childhood.<ref name=\"LBC Akhaten\">{{cite web| first=Laura| last=Byrne-Cristiano| title='Doctor Who's' 'The Rings of Akhaten' has a 9th Doctor feel| url=http://www.hypable.com/2013/04/04/doctor-whos-the-rings-of-akhaten-has-a-9th-doctor-feel/| work=hypable| date=4 April 2013| access-date=12 May 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101113025/http://www.hypable.com/2013/04/04/doctor-whos-the-rings-of-akhaten-has-a-9th-doctor-feel/| archive-date=1 January 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| first=Alicia| last=Lutes| title='Doctor Who' Recap: Let Me Upgrade You (Season 7, Episode 12)|url=http://www.hollywood.com/recaps/55013290/doctor-who-recap-nightmare-in-silver-neil-gaiman-cybermen-return| work=hollywood.com| date=11 May 2013| accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> The Doctor does the same thing to Clara in \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\" (2013) as he does to Rose in \"[[The Parting of the Ways]]\" (2005) by sending her back home to keep her safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/tv/doctor-10-beautiful-things-time-doctor.php/4|title=Doctor Who: 10 Beautiful Things About 'The Time Of The Doctor'|work=WhatCulture.com|date=2013-12-26}}</ref>\n\nIt was widely expected that Coleman would leave the show at the end of 2014. Moffat has confirmed in numerous interviews that he wrote the character out twice \u2014 once for the end of Series 8 and again for the 2014 Christmas special \u2014 but ultimately convinced Coleman to stay on for one more series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-03-05/jenna-coleman-was-originally-going-to-leave-doctor-who-at-the-end-of-series-8 |title=Jenna Coleman was originally going to leave Doctor Who at the end of series 8|publisher=[[Radio Times]] |date=5 March 2015 |accessdate=18 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2015, Coleman officially announced on BBC Radio 1 that she would leave the show at the end of the ninth series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/2a2689a8-5c52-46af-8e69-2fad42c46da3 |title=Jenna Coleman is Leaving Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=18 September 2015 |accessdate=18 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nColeman reprised the role of Clara for a cameo appearance in the 2017 Christmas Special [[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|\"Twice Upon a Time\"]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{Update|section|date=October 2015}}\nNick Setchfield of ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'' praised the effective surprise debut of Coleman as Oswin in \"Asylum of the Daleks\". He wrote, \"Coleman brings sauce and sparkiness, and while she initially seems a familiar Moffat archetype, all snarky cracks about the Doctor's chin and throwaway lines about sexual experimentation... there's a deeper vulnerability there too, which makes her eventual fate in this episode genuinely heart-skewering.\"<ref name= \"SFX asylum\">{{cite web| first = Nick | last = Setfield|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/09/01/doctor-who-7-01-asylum-of-the-daleks-review/|title=Doctor Who 7.01 \"Asylum of the Daleks\" Review|work= [[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]| date= 1 September 2012| accessdate= 2 September 2012}}</ref> Michael Hogan, writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', also found her debut promising and described her as \"enchanting in an elfin way&nbsp;\u2013 rather like a brunette, curvier, less annoying [[Fearne Cotton]]\".<ref name=\"telegraph2\">{{cite news|first = Michael |last= Hogan| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/9512002/A-bold-debut-for-the-new-Doctor-Who-assistant-review.html| title= A bold debut for the new Doctor Who assistant | type = review|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2 September 2012|accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe character's reintroduction as Clara in \"The Snowmen\" received generally positive reviews from critics. ''[[The Guardian]]''<nowiki />'s Dan Martin wrote, \"The masterstroke behind Jenna-Louise Coleman's surprise introduction is that it made us want to see more of her before Karen Gillan had even gone. The cheeky, self-assured Clara won a place in our hearts from the off.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Dan |url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2012/dec/25/doctor-who-snowmen-christmas-special |title=Doctor Who: The Snowmen&nbsp;\u2013 Christmas special 2012 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 December 2012 |accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref> Setchfield called her \"less of a motormouthed quip-merchant than [Oswin], but Coleman makes her equally winning&nbsp;\u2013 plucky, smart and riffing on a very promising chemistry with Matt Smith\".<ref name=\"SFX snowmen\">{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Setchfield|url= http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/12/25/doctor-who-the-snowmen-review/|title = Doctor Who \"The Snowmen\" Review|work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=25 December 2012|accessdate= 23 March 2013}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Matt Risley felt that Clara \"trumped her already-bombastic debut with a character both fully formed and utterly unpredictable\". He praised the mystery surrounding her and her independence, commenting that she seemed to be the \"[[antithesis]]\" of Amy Pond as she was \"a girl who will wait for no-one\".<ref name=\"IGN snowmen\">{{cite web|first= Matt|last= Risley|url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/12/26/doctor-who-the-snowmen-review |title= Mary Poppins Got Game!|publisher= [[IGN]]| date= 25 December 2012| accessdate= 23 March 2013}}</ref> ''[[Radio Times]]'' reviewer Patrick Mulkern admitted that he had \"found Oswin's perkiness a tad wearing\", but he was \"completely won over\" by Coleman's Clara in \"The Snowmen\".<ref name=\"RT snowmen\">{{cite web|first=Patrick|last= Mulkern|url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-12-25/doctor-who--the-snowmen-review | title =Doctor Who&nbsp;\u2014 The Snowmen | type = review|work= [[Radio Times]]|date=25 December 2012|accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> Neela Debanth of ''[[The Independent]]'' felt that Clara's demise in \"The Snowmen\" made the episode \"a bit of a tease\" and set up the question of what the travelling Clara would be like. Unlike Mulkern, she favoured the Oswin version, describing her as \"much more fun and flirtatious\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/12/25/review-of-doctor-who-the-snowmen/ |title=Review of Doctor Who 'The Snowmen' |work=[[The Independent]] |date=25 December 2012 |accessdate=26 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228035143/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/12/25/review-of-doctor-who-the-snowmen/ |archivedate=28 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing \"The Bells of Saint John\", [[Digital Spy]]'s Morgan Jeffery said that the new Clara was \"more grounded and so far easier for the viewer to latch on to\" than her two predecessors, both of whom could have been harder to sustain as companions.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url= http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/recaps/a468861/doctor-who-new-episode-the-bells-of-saint-john-review.html|title='Doctor Who': New episode 'The Bells of Saint John' review|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Mulkern said that he did not bother with the character's mystery and found it pleasing that Coleman played her as \"a straightforward modern companion with no baggage\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Patrick|last=Mulkern|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-03-30/doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john-review-steven-moffat-at-his-confident-playful-best|title=Doctor Who The Bells of Saint John review: \"Steven Moffat at his confident, playful best\"|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Setchfield described Clara as \"equally sparky and winning but altogether younger and possibly just a tad more vulnerable than her previous incarnations\" with a \"helplessly watchable chemistry\" with Smith.<ref>{{cite web |first= Nick|last= Setchfield | url = http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/03/30/doctor-who-7-6-the-bells-of-saint-john-review/|title=Doctor Who 7.06 \"The Bells of Saint John\" | type = review|work= [[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Debnath described her as a \"softer version\" of Oswin, still hoping that \"the character will be taken up a notch, challenging the Doctor more and bouncing off him like Oswin did.<ref>{{cite web | first = Neela | last = Debnath | url = http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/03/30/review-of-doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john/ | type = review | title = Doctor Who 'The Bells of Saint John' | work = [[The Independent]] | date = 30 March 2013 | accessdate = 31 March 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130402005827/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/03/30/review-of-doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john/ | archivedate = 2 April 2013 }}</ref> However, the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''<nowiki />'s Jon Cooper expressed concern that Clara, despite Coleman's success, was too similar to Amy.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jon|last=Cooper|url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-reviews/doctor-who-review-jenna-louise-coleman-1792420|title= Doctor Who review: Jenna-Louise Coleman is great, but The Bells of Saint John required a bit more heart|work= The [[Daily Mirror]]|date= 30 March 2013|accessdate= 31 March 2013}}</ref> Mike Higgins of ''The Independent'' felt that Coleman was \"an improvement\" upon Gillan, but wrote that \"the pairing of an intellectually bright but emotionally dim male with a techno-illiterate but wised up female is a tired old trope of much drama and comedy\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Higgins|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/tv-review-doctor-who--the-doctors-back-with-his-snog-box-8555083.html | type =TV review | title = Doctor Who&nbsp;\u2014 The Doctor's back, with his snog box|work=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe character's development has also been met with positive reviews. Martin praised how her backstory was fleshed out in \"The Rings of Akhaten\", as otherwise the character \"was danger of becoming simply a story arc in the shape of a girl\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Dan|last=Martin|url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/06/doctor-who-rings-of-akhaten |title= Doctor Who: The Rings of Akhaten&nbsp;\u2013 series 33, episode seven|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 6 April 2013| accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref>  ''SFX''<nowiki />'s Richard Edwards wrote that she had the potential to be \"a truly great companion\", and that it was \"refreshing to see a companion who isn't in total awe of the Doctor... and she's not afraid to take the lead when she needs to\".<ref name=\"SFX\">{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Edwards |url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/04/06/doctor-who-7-07-the-rings-of-akhaten-review/ |title=Doctor Who 7.07 \"The Rings of Akhaten\" Review |work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]] |date=6 April 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130408235001/http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/04/06/doctor-who-7-07-the-rings-of-akhaten-review/ |archivedate=8 April 2013 }}</ref> Debnath praised her \"caring nature\" and \"lovely maternal side\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Neela |last=Debnath |url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/06/review-of-doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten/ |type=review |title=Doctor Who 'The Rings of Akhaten' |work=[[The Independent]] |date=6 April 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130408103203/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/06/review-of-doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten/ |archivedate=8 April 2013 }}</ref> but felt that she could be \"annoyingly na\u00efve\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Neela|last=Debnath|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/13/review-of-doctor-who-cold-war/|title=Review of 'Cold War'|work=[[The Independent]]|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413205025/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/13/review-of-doctor-who-cold-war/|archivedate=13 April 2013}}</ref> Dave Golder of ''SFX'' stated that Clara was \"to an extent, a bit of a cartoon character\" and that Moffat was better at writing her in \"The Name of the Doctor\" than some of the preceding writers. He also commented that she \"still feels too new a companion (and an underdeveloped one) to really care about her sacrifice\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=Golder|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/05/18/doctor-who-7-13-the-name-of-the-doctor-review-2/|title=Doctor Who 7.13 \"The Name of The Doctor\" | type = review |work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=18 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nClara Oswald has been very divisive among the ''Doctor Who fanbase'' with many criticizing her character traits such as being a \"control freak\" as \"irritating\" and \"unlikeable\" as well as her character progression throughout her journey in the TARDIS as \"boring\" and \"bland\". However Coleman's performance has been widely praised.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rryyj/profiles/clara-oswald Clara Oswald] at the [[BBC One]] ''Doctor Who'' website\n*[http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/characters/clara/ Clara] at [[BBC America]]'s ''Doctor Who'' website\n{{TardisDataCore|Clara Oswald}}\n\n{{Doctor Who companions|11|12}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oswald, Clara}}\n[[Category:Doctor Who companions]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Fictional nannies]]\n[[Category:Fictional hackers]]\n[[Category:Fictional governesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional schoolteachers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character in the TV series Doctor Who}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Clara Oswald\n| series      = [[Doctor Who]]\n| image       = [[File:Clara Oswald.jpg|centre|200px]]\n| caption     = [[Jenna Coleman]] as Clara Oswald\n| first       = \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012)\n| last        = \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\" (2017)\n| portrayer   = [[Jenna Coleman]]\n| species     = [[Human]]\n| affiliation = [[Eleventh Doctor]]<br>[[Twelfth Doctor]]\n| home        = [[Earth]]\n}}\n'''Clara Oswald''' is a fictional character created by [[Steven Moffat]] and portrayed by [[Jenna Coleman]] in the long-running [[Television in the United Kingdom|British]] [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. First appearing in the show's [[Doctor Who (series 7)|seventh series]], Clara served as a companion of the [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] [[time travel in fiction|time traveller]] known as [[The Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]] in his [[Eleventh Doctor|eleventh]] ([[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]) and [[Twelfth Doctor|twelfth]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]) incarnations. She remains the longest serving companion since the show's revival in 2005.\n\nClara is initially presented to the audience during the seventh series as three distinct, though similarly named, people living in different eras. The first two incarnations, Oswin Oswald and Clara Oswin Oswald, each die during the episode in which they appear. The third incarnation becomes the Doctor's companion, travelling with him for the remainder of the series as he tries to uncover the mystery of her multiple lives. She continues to travel with the Doctor after the mystery is resolved at the end of the series, witnessing him regenerate into his twelfth incarnation in \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\" (2013). The pair have various adventures together in the [[Doctor Who (series 8)|eighth]] and [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] until she departs the show in \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\" (2015). She reappears briefly in the Christmas special \"[[Twice Upon A Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\" (2017).\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Television===\nOswin Oswald is introduced in the [[Doctor Who (series 7)|series 7]] premiere, \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012). She is the sole survivor of the [[starship]] ''Alaska'', which crashed on the Asylum, a prison planet for insane [[Dalek]]s. Oswin then learns from the [[Eleventh Doctor]] (Matt Smith) that she has been converted from human into a Dalek and has coped by retreating into a fantasy of her own intact survival. She assists the Doctor and his [[Companion (Doctor Who)|travelling companions]], [[Amy Pond]] ([[Karen Gillan]]) and [[Rory Williams]] ([[Arthur Darvill]]), to escape the planet unharmed, but at the cost of her own life.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Asylum of the Daleks |episode-link=Asylum of the Daleks |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Nick (director) |last2=Hurran |author-link2=Nick Hurran |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 September 2012 |season= |series-no=7 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Later, in the 2012 Christmas special \"[[The Snowmen]]\", the Doctor meets a woman named Clara Oswin Oswald, whom he initially knows only as Clara. She is a [[Victorian era|Victorian]] [[barmaid]] and [[governess]] whom the Doctor invites to be his newest companion, but who dies from an attack by one of the [[Great Intelligence]]'s minions. Seeing her full name on her tombstone and finally recognising her voice, the Doctor realises she is the same woman as Oswin from the Dalek Asylum, whom he had never seen in her human form. Intrigued by the mystery of the woman who has lived and died twice in different [[era]]s, he begins searching across time for another Clara.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Snowmen |episode-link=The Snowmen |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Saul (director) |last2=Metzstein |author-link2=Saul Metzstein |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2012 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n[[File:Dr Who Experience, Cardiff (11034641744).jpg|thumb|left|Clara's book of ''101 Places to See'' and the leaf, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nIn \"[[The Bells of Saint John]]\" (2013), Clara receives a phone number to the Doctor's time and space vessel, the [[TARDIS]], from a mysterious woman. The Doctor finds Clara Oswald (this time with no middle name) in contemporary London through her phone call, and takes her on as a companion with a goal to solving the mystery of the \"impossible girl\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Bells of Saint John |episode-link=The Bells of Saint John |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Colm (director) |last2=McCarthy |author-link2=Colm McCarthy (director) |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=30 March 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> The Doctor's repeated attempts at investigating Clara's origins over the course of \"[[The Rings of Akhaten]]\", \"[[Hide (Doctor Who)|Hide]]\", and \"[[Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS]]\" consistently turn up compelling evidence that she is just a normal young human woman.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Rings of Akhaten |episode-link=The Rings of Akhaten |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Neil (writer) |last=Cross |author-link=Neil Cross |first2=Farren (director) |last2=Blackburn |author-link2=Farren Blackburn |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=6 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=7 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Hide |episode-link=Hide (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Neil (writer) |last=Cross |author-link=Neil Cross |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Payne  |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=20 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=9 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref name=\"centre\">{{Cite episode |title=Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS |episode-link=Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steve (writer) |last=Thompson |author-link=Stephen Thompson (writer) |first2=Mat (director) |last2=King |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=27 April 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=10 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"Journey to the Centre of the TARDIS\", the Doctor confronts Clara in an averted timeline about the two previous versions of her he had met, but she does not know what he is talking about.<ref name=\"centre\"/> The mystery surrounding Clara is finally resolved in \"[[The Name of the Doctor]]\" when she sacrifices her existence by entering the Doctor's timestream to undo the harm caused by the Great Intelligence ([[Richard E Grant]]). This results in the creation of numerous incarnations of Clara throughout the Doctor's history who appear to every known face of the Doctor, saving his life in numerous ways. Very few Claras are noticed by the Doctor. One version of Clara successfully persuades the [[First Doctor]] ([[William Hartnell]]) to pick the \"right\" TARDIS on his home planet [[Gallifrey]], prior to the events of the show's [[An Unearthly Child|first episode]]. Lost in the Doctor's timestream, she is eventually rescued and brought back into existence by the Eleventh Doctor.<ref name=\"name of the doctor\">{{Cite episode |title=The Name of the Doctor |episode-link=The Name of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Saul (director) |last2=Metzstein |author-link2=Saul Metzstein |first3=Denise (producer) |last3=Paul |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 May 2013 |season= |series-no=7 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\", the show's 50th anniversary special, Clara is shown to have become a teacher at [[Coal Hill School]]. While on an adventure with the Doctor, she meets the [[Tenth Doctor]] ([[David Tennant]]) and the [[War Doctor]] ([[John Hurt]]) in person.  She manages to convince the War Doctor to change his history (and thereby save Gallifrey and his people, the [[Time Lord]]s, from destruction in the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]]), by sealing the planet in a \"parallel pocket universe\", where it remains.<ref name=TDOTD>{{Cite episode |title=The Day of the Doctor |episode-link=The Day of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Nick (director) |last2=Hurran |author-link2=Nick Hurran |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=23 November 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nIn \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\", the Time Lords try to return to the universe through a crack in time, but if they do so, the Time War will begin anew. The Doctor sends Clara home to her family at Christmas twice while the Doctor stays on the planet Trenzalore to try and prevent this war, but she returns in the TARDIS each time, after two centuries-long intervals. With the Doctor facing certain death at the end of his [[regeneration (Doctor Who)|regeneration cycle]] during this siege, she pleads with the Time Lords through the crack to save the Doctor; they grant him a new regeneration cycle and the crack closes. She then witnesses the Doctor regenerate into the [[Twelfth Doctor]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]).<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Time of the Doctor |episode-link=The Time of the Doctor |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Payne  |first3=Marcus (producer) |last3=Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Clara spends some time grappling with losing the Doctor she knew and loved throughout the events of \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\" (2014), until a call from the Eleventh Doctor prior to his regeneration convinces her to stay by his side and help him adjust to his new persona.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Deep Breath |episode-link=Deep Breath (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Ben (director) |last2=Wheatley |author-link2=Ben Wheatley |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=23 August 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Into the Dalek]]\", Clara and fellow teacher [[Danny Pink]] ([[Samuel Anderson (actor)|Samuel Anderson]]) agree to go for drinks together,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Into the Dalek |episode-link=Into the Dalek |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Phil |last=Ford |author-link=Phil Ford (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Ben (director) |last3=Wheatley |author-link3=Ben Wheatley |first4=Nikki (producer) |last4=Wilson |author-link4=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=30 August 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> and over the course of the episodes \"[[Listen (Doctor Who)|Listen]]\", \"[[Time Heist]]\", and \"[[The Caretaker (Doctor Who)|The Caretaker]]\", the two enter into a romantic relationship.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Listen |episode-link=Listen (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=13 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Time Heist |episode-link=Time Heist |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steve |last=Thompson |author-link=Stephen Thompson (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Douglas (director) |last3=Mackinnon |author-link3=Douglas Mackinnon |first4=Peter (producer) |last4=Bennett |author-link4=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=20 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=5 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Caretaker |episode-link=The Caretaker (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Gareth |last=Roberts |author-link=Gareth Roberts (writer) |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Paul (director) |last3=Murphy |first4=Peter (producer) |last4=Bennett |author-link4=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=27 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> For a while, she keeps secrets between the Doctor and Danny due to their misgivings about each other, and experiences turbulence in her friendship with the Doctor, particularly in \"[[Kill the Moon]]\", when he abandons her to face a traumatic decision on her own.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Kill the Moon |episode-link=Kill the Moon |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Peter (writer) |last=Harness |author-link=Peter Harness |first2=Paul (director) |last2=Wilmshurst |author-link2=Paul Wilmshurst |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=4 October 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=7 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Flatline (Doctor Who)|Flatline]]\", she is forced to take the Doctor's role in averting an alien invasion, and realises she is capable of making the same ruthless and pragmatic decisions he often has to make.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Flatline |episode-link=Flatline (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Jamie (writer) |last=Mathieson |author-link=Jamie Mathieson |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 October 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=9 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Dark Water (Doctor Who)|Dark Water]]\", Danny dies while crossing the road before Clara can announce her intent to commit to him fully. After attempting to blackmail the Doctor into changing history to avert his death, which is impossible, Clara and the Doctor decide to pursue contacting him from beyond the grave, and end up at a facility where evil Time Lord [[The Master (Doctor Who)#Missy|Missy]] ([[Michelle Gomez]]) has [[Matrix (Doctor Who)|stored the consciousnesses]] of Earth's dead as part of a plot to convert all of the deceased into an army of [[Cyberman|Cybermen]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Dark Water |episode-link=Dark Water (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Death in Heaven]]\", Missy reveals that she was the aforementioned woman who gave Clara the TARDIS telephone number and had also been secretly keeping the two together after their first meeting as part of her plan. After Danny is brought back as a Cyberman in the episode, he resists his programming in order to destroy Missy's Cyberman army and avert her plans. Two weeks after these events, Clara and the Doctor meet to say goodbye to one another. The Doctor lies to Clara; he pretends he has found Gallifrey and a home to go back to. Clara lies too; she pretends Danny returned from the dead through Missy's device, when in fact he sacrificed his opportunity to save the life of the child he killed in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episode-link=Death in Heaven |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nThe two later reunite in the 2014 Christmas special \"[[Last Christmas (Doctor Who)|Last Christmas]]\", when alien creatures induce a dream state in both the Doctor and Clara. Clara confesses that Danny is still dead, and the Doctor admits he did not find Gallifrey. Their shared dream experience on the North Pole ends with them regretting their parting. The Doctor asks Clara to resume travelling with him, and she happily agrees.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Last Christmas |episode-link=Last Christmas (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Paul (director) |last2=Wilmshurst |author-link2=Paul Wilmshurst |first3=Paul (producer) |last3=Frift |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2014 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In [[Doctor Who (series 9)|series 9]], Clara accompanies  Missy and the Doctor to [[Skaro]] when he is summoned by [[Davros]] ([[Julian Bleach]]), barely escaping the ordeal with her life.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Magician's Apprentice |episode-link=The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=19 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Witch's Familiar |episode-link=The Witch's Familiar |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=26 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Now an experienced companion, Clara shows greater confidence when dealing with alien races and volatile humans, but the Doctor finds himself concerned by her reckless streak.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Girl Who Died |episode-link=The Girl Who Died |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Jamie |last=Mathieson |author-link=Jamie Mathieson |first2=Steven (writers) |last2=Moffat |author-link2=Steven Moffat |first3=Ed (director) |last3=Bazalgette |first4=Derek (producer) |last4=Ritchie |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=17 October 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=5 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Clara's recklessness gets the better of her in \"[[Face the Raven]]\", when she attempts to outsmart the Doctor's adversary [[Ashildr]] ([[Maisie Williams]]) by taking on a death sentence, but later learns that it cannot be revoked. She cautions the Doctor not to give in to his darker nature in response to her passing, and faces death with bravery.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Face the Raven |episode-link=Face the Raven |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Sarah (writer) |last=Dollard |author-link=Sarah Dollard |first2=Justin (director) |last2=Molotnikov |first3=Nikki (producer) |last3=Wilson |author-link3=Nikki Wilson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=21 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=10 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> She is seen once more in the following episode \"[[Heaven Sent (Doctor Who)|Heaven Sent]]\", as a grief-stricken Doctor imagines conversations with her to clarify his ideas.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Heaven Sent |episode-link=Heaven Sent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In \"[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]\", the Doctor uses Time Lord technology on Gallifrey to extract Clara from her last moments of life, and attempts to run away with her and cheat death. He later realises from Ashildr that travelling together will only cause more harm than good, and prepares to wipe Clara's memories of him with a device. Clara tampers with the device so that it wipes the Doctor's memories of her instead. She leaves the Doctor on Earth to start his adventures anew, and begins travelling with Ashildr in a stolen TARDIS with the intention of one day returning to Gallifrey to meet her end, although vowing to \"take the long way around\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Hell Bent |episode-link=Hell Bent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |first3=Peter (producer) |last3=Bennett |author-link3=Peter Bennett (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=5 December 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nIn \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\", the Doctor encounters Testimony, a futuristic organisation who use time travel to copy people's memories at the moment of death and install them in sentient glass avatars. At the end of an adventure, an avatar of [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]] restores the Doctor's memories of Clara with a mental image of her telling him not to forget her again.\n\n{{Multiple images\n| align = centre\n| footer = Costumes worn by Clara throughout the series, on display at the Doctor Who Experience\n| total_width = 1100\n| image1    = Doctor Who Experience (25307761419).jpg\n| width1 = 4288\n| height1   =  2848\n| image2 = Clara from The Snowmen (10634572106).jpg\n| width2  = 1227\n| height2 = 2439\n| image3  = Doctor Who Experience (30907346786).jpg\n| width3  = 4288\n| height3 = 2848\n| image4  = Doctor Who Experience (22764800208) (cropped).jpg\n| width4  = 1159\n| height4 = 2230\n| image5  = Doctor Who Experience (30907321066).jpg\n| width5  = 1277\n| height5 = 2964\n| image6  = Doctor Who Experience (22764798728) (cropped).jpg\n| width6  = 1045\n| height6 =  2397\n| image7  = Doctor Who Experience (25307730849).jpg\n| width7  = 2060\n| height7 = 4041\n| image8  = Doctor Who Experience (30907323426).jpg\n| width8  = 1142\n| height8 = 2450\n| image9  = Doctor Who Experience (30641592730) (cropped 2).jpg\n| width9  = 643 \n| height9 = 2140\n| image10  = Doctor Who Experience (30855116111).jpg\n| width10  = 1174\n| height10 =  2387\n\n}}\n\n===Other media===\nClara (Sophie Downham) appears in a short prelude to \"The Bells of Saint John\" as a child who talks to the Doctor at a playground. The Doctor does not realise her identity, which is revealed to the viewer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p016r6pw|title=The Bells of Saint John: A Prequel|publisher=BBC|date=23 March 2013|accessdate=23 March 2013|format=Video}}</ref> Coleman also played Clara in \"She Said, He Said\", an online prelude to \"The Name of the Doctor\" that breaks the [[fourth wall]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-05-03/doctor-who-finale-prequel-starring-matt-smith-and-jenna-louise-coleman-to-screen-via-bbc-red-button|title=Doctor Who finale prequel starring Matt Smith and Jenna-Louise Coleman to screen via BBC Red Button|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=3 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> The DVD and Blu-ray releases for Series 7 also include Coleman in a solo performance as Clara in the home media-exclusive short \"Clara and the TARDIS\".\n\nClara also features alongside the Eleventh Doctor in the [[New Series Adventures]] novel ''Shroud of Sorrow'' (2013).<ref>{{cite book |last=Donbavand |first=Tommy |author-link=Tommy Donbavand |date=11 April 2013 |title=Shroud of Sorrow |series=[[New Series Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |page= |isbn=978-1-84990-576-3 |access-date= }}</ref> From 2014, she has been featured in the [[Twelfth Doctor]] novels including: ''[[The Blood Cell]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Goss|first=James|author-link=James Goss (producer)|date=11 September 2014|title=The Blood Cell|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-774-3|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[Silhouette (Doctor Who)|Silhouette]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Richards|first=Justin|author-link=Justin Richards|date=11 September 2014|title=Silhouette|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-772-9|access-date=}}</ref> ''[[The Crawling Terror]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Mike|author-link=Mike Tucker|date=11 September 2014|title=The Crawling Terror|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-773-6|access-date=}}</ref> and as of 2015, ''[[Royal Blood (Doctor Who)|Royal Blood]]''<ref>{{cite book|last=McCormack|first=Una|author-link=|date=10 September 2015|title=Royal Blood|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-992-1|access-date=}}</ref> and ''[[Deep Time (Doctor Who)|Deep Time]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Baxendale|first=Trevor|author-link=Trevor Baxendale|date=10 September 2015|title=Deep Time|series=[[New Series Adventures]]|url=|location=|publisher=[[BBC Books]]|page=|isbn=978-1-84990-990-7|access-date=}}</ref> She appeared in [[IDW Publishing]]'s comic story ''Deadwood''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rich|last=Johnson|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2013/06/14/the-launch-of-the-powerpuff-girls-idw-solicitations-for-september-2013-including-transformers-my-little-pony-star-trek-doctor-who-gi-joe-and-locke-and-key/|title=The Launch Of The Powerpuff Girls&nbsp;\u2013 IDW Solicitations For September 2013, Including Transformers, My Little Pony, Star Trek, Doctor Who, GI Joe And Locke And Key|publisher=[[Bleeding Cool]]|date=14 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Clara appeared briefly in issues 11 and 12 of IDW 50th anniversary Doctor Who mini-series \"Prisoners of Time\". Beginning with Issue #462 (August 2013), Clara appears regularly in the ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' comic strips.<ref>{{Cite comic\n| writer = [[Scott Gray (writer)|Gray, Scott]]\n| penciller = [[Mike Collins (comics)|Collins, Mike]]\n| inker = [[David Roach (comics)|Roach, David A.]]\n| story = A Wing and a Prayer: Part One\n| title = [[Doctor Who Magazine]]\n| volume = \n| issue = #462\n| date = August 2013\n| publisher = [[Panini Comics]]\n| location = Tunbridge Wells\n| page = \n| panel = \n| id =\n}}</ref> In the 2015 ''Doctor Who Magazine'' comic storyline ''Blood and Ice'' (DWM #485\u2013488), Clara meets another incarnation of herself she created called \"Winnie Clarence\", a university research graduate from the year 2048.<ref>{{Cite comic\n| writer = [[Jacqueline Rayner|Rayner, Jacqueline]]\n| penciller = [[Martin Geraghty|Geraghty, Martin]]\n| inker = [[David Roach (comics)|Roach, David A]]\n| story = Blood and Ice\n| title = [[Doctor Who Magazine]]\n| volume = \n| issue = #485\u2013488\n| date = May \u2013 August 2015\n| publisher = [[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]]\n| location = Tunbridge Wells\n| page = \n| panel = \n| id =\n}}</ref>\n\n==Casting and development==\n[[File:Jenna Coleman Peabody 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Jenna Coleman plays Clara.]]\nOn 21 March 2012, it was announced that [[Jenna Coleman]] would replace [[Karen Gillan]] and [[Arthur Darvill]] as the next companion.<ref name=\"new companion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17456505|title=Doctor Who's latest companion is unveiled|publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> She auditioned for the role in secrecy, pretending it was for something called ''Men on Waves'', an anagram for \"Woman Seven\".<ref>{{cite web|first=William|last=Gallagher|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-03-27/doctor-who's-secret-history-of-codenames-revealed|title=Doctor Who's secret history of codenames revealed|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Executive producer and lead writer [[Steven Moffat]] chose her for the role because she worked the best alongside Smith and could talk faster than he did.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a372323/doctor-who-jenna-louise-coleman-the-press-conference-in-full.html|title='Doctor Who': Jenna-Louise Coleman&nbsp;\u2014 The press conference in full|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Coleman had never seen ''Doctor Who'' before her audition, and watched \"[[The Eleventh Hour (Doctor Who)|The Eleventh Hour]]\" (2010) and \"completely fell in love with the show\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/videos/jenna-joins-the-doctor-who-family/|title='Doctor Who': Insider&nbsp;\u2014 Jenna Joins the 'Doctor Who' Family|publisher=[[BBC America]]|format=Video|date=22 March 2013|accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> However, she only watched the first five episodes of the seventh series \u2013 the final five featuring Gillan and Darvill \u2013 because she did not want to learn more about their relationship to the Doctor, as she wanted her acting alongside Smith to be \"spontaneous\".<ref name=\"red eye\">{{cite web|first=Curt|last=Wagner|url=http://articles.redeyechicago.com/2013-03-27/entertainment/38077234_1_jenna-louise-coleman-arthur-darvill-doctor-who|title='Doctor Who': 3rd Clara's a charm for new star Coleman|work=[[RedEye]]|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> Moffat stated that her character is different from previous companions,<ref name=\"different\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/05/30/new-companion-makes-doctor-who-a-different-show-says-moffat/|title=New Companion Makes Doctor Who A Different Show, Says Moffat|work=SFX|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> though he attempted to keep the details of her character a secret until she debuted in the Christmas special.<ref name=\"BAFTA\">{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a382427/steven-moffat-on-doctor-who-sherlock-and-his-bafta-special-award.html|title=Steven Moffat on 'Doctor Who', 'Sherlock' and his BAFTA Special Award|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=19 May 2012|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> In \"[[Asylum of the Daleks]]\" (2012), Coleman appears as the character Oswin Oswald, a secret which was kept from the public before transmission.<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Martinovic|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a403217/steven-moffat-thanks-press-and-fans-for-saving-doctor-who-surprise.html|title=Steven Moffat thanks press and fans for saving 'Doctor Who' surprise|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Coleman was originally given the role of a Victorian governess named Jasmine, and then for the second audition she was given both the characters of Oswin and Clara. She originally thought that the producers were looking for the right character, but later realised it was part of Moffat's \"soft mystery\" plan.<ref name=\"Coleman advent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01205ht|title=Jenna-Louise Coleman: Becoming the Companion|format=Video|publisher=BBC|date=1 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"EW interview\">{{cite web|first=Clark|last=Collis|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/11/28/doctor-who-jenna-louise-coleman/|title='Doctor Who': Jenna-Louise Coleman talks about becoming the Doctor's new companion -- Exclusive|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> [[Neil Gaiman]] (writer of \"[[Nightmare in Silver]]\", 2013) revealed that the character was originally intended to stay as a Victorian governess.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Patrick|last1=Mulkern|first2=Paul|last2=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-05-15/neil-gaiman-on-re-writing-doctor-who-clara-was-originally-going-to-stay-as-a-victorian-governess|title=Neil Gaiman on re-writing Doctor Who: Clara was originally going to stay as a Victorian governess|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=15 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Coleman stated that Moffat came up with the mystery during the audition process.<ref name=\"red eye\"/> Coleman played each version of the character as individuals with \"trust that there would be a payoff\" to her mystery.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a469162/doctor-who-plot-is-mystifying-exciting-says-jenna-louise-coleman.html|title='Doctor Who' plot is \"mystifying, exciting\" says Jenna-Louise Coleman|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Moffat told [[Neil Cross]], who wrote \"[[Hide (Doctor Who)|Hide]]\" (2013), the first episode Coleman filmed as the new companion, that Clara was \"a normal girl\".<ref name=\"Cross Akhaten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten-writer-neil-cross-interview/|title=Doctor Who \"The Rings of Akhaten\": Writer Neil Cross Interview|date=5 April 2013|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nMoffat felt that the introduction of a new companion made \"the show feel different\" and brought the story to \"a new beginning\" with a different person meeting the Doctor.<ref name=\"different\"/> Executive producer Caroline Skinner remarked that her introduction allowed the series to return to a more \"classic ''Doctor Who'' format\".<ref name=\"io9 Skinner\">{{cite web|first=Meredith|last=Woerner|url=http://io9.com/5971019/producer-caroline-skinner-explains-why-doctor-who-is-getting-a-new-companion-for-christmas|title=Producer Caroline Skinner explains why Doctor Who is getting a new Companion for Christmas|publisher=[[io9]]|date=24 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Smith said that Clara was different from her predecessor [[Amy Pond]] (Gillan), which allowed the audience to see a different side of the Doctor.<ref name=\"bbc interviews\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/articles/Steven-Moffat-and-the-Cast-on-The-Snowmen| title=Steven Moffat and the Cast on The Snowmen| publisher=BBC| date=8 December 2012| accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> Moffat said that Coleman brings \"a speed and wit and an unimpressed quality that makes the Doctor dance a bit harder\".<ref name=\"collider 7b\">{{cite web|first=Christina|last=Radish|url=http://collider.com/steven-moffat-doctor-who-season-7-interview/|title=Steven Moffat Talks DOCTOR WHO, His Favorite Upcoming Episodes, Writing the Doctor and Sherlock Holmes, the 50th Anniversary, and More|publisher=Collider|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Coleman stated that her character \"holds her own\" and was competitive with the Doctor, providing \"a nice double act\".<ref name=\"CNN Coleman\"/> With her place in the series' narrative, Clara was intended to reawaken the Doctor's \"curiosity in the universe and gives him his mojo back\".<ref name=\"reignite\">{{cite web|first=Justin|last=Harp|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a469255/doctor-who-star-matt-smith-clara-reignites-the-doctors-curiosity.html|title='Doctor Who' star Matt Smith: 'Clara reignites The Doctor's curiosity'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Concerning Clara's relationship to the Doctor, Coleman said, \"It's been interesting how it's changed Matt's Doctor. There is a natural bounce between them, and a flirtation, and attraction. But, again, they've always got this friction because they're a bit magnetic and drawn to each other, but she can't quite figure him out. He's got loads of secrets and he's always looking at her, trying to figure her out.\"<ref name=\"CNN Coleman\">{{cite web|first=Aaron|last=Sagers|url= http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/18/showbiz/tv/jenna-louise-coleman-doctor-who/index.html|title=Actress Jenna-Louise Coleman talks 'Doctor Who'|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> The dynamic between [[Katharine Hepburn]] and [[Spencer Tracy]] was an influence on Coleman and Smith.<ref name=\"dance\">{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/news/a463675/jenna-louise-coleman-on-doctor-who-dynamic-its-like-a-dance.html|title=Jenna-Louise Coleman on 'Doctor Who' dynamic: 'It's like a dance'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref> In addition, Coleman revealed that Clara and the TARDIS have a \"relationship\", as there is a running joke about the TARDIS (previously established in the series as being sentient) not liking Clara or making fun of her.<ref name=\"TARDIS\">{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Jones|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-04-12/doctor-whos-jenna-louise-coleman-clara-and-the-tardis-have-a-relationship--it-makes-fun-of-her|title=Doctor Who's Jenna-Louise Coleman: \"Clara and the Tardis have a relationship \u2013 it makes fun of her\"|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=12 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nMany fans and critics noticed similarities between Clara and [[Billie Piper]]'s [[Rose Tyler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2013/03/is-clara-oswin-oswald-destined-to-be-rose-tyler-20|title=Is Clara Oswin Oswald Destined to Be Rose Tyler 2.0?|work=Tor.com|date=2013-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/recaps/a592751/doctor-who-series-8-into-the-dalek-recap-meet-the-new-doctor.html|title=Doctor Who series 8 'Into the Dalek' recap: Meet the new Doctor|work=Digital Spy|date=2014-08-30}}</ref> Clara helps the Doctor recover at a dark point in his life, as Rose does during a much darker time; both companions lose a parent; each has a close relationship with the Doctor, who sees part of their childhood.<ref name=\"LBC Akhaten\">{{cite web| first=Laura| last=Byrne-Cristiano| title='Doctor Who's' 'The Rings of Akhaten' has a 9th Doctor feel| url=http://www.hypable.com/2013/04/04/doctor-whos-the-rings-of-akhaten-has-a-9th-doctor-feel/| work=hypable| date=4 April 2013| access-date=12 May 2013| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101113025/http://www.hypable.com/2013/04/04/doctor-whos-the-rings-of-akhaten-has-a-9th-doctor-feel/| archive-date=1 January 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| first=Alicia| last=Lutes| title='Doctor Who' Recap: Let Me Upgrade You (Season 7, Episode 12)|url=http://www.hollywood.com/recaps/55013290/doctor-who-recap-nightmare-in-silver-neil-gaiman-cybermen-return| work=hollywood.com| date=11 May 2013| accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> The Doctor does the same thing to Clara in \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\" (2013) as he does to Rose in \"[[The Parting of the Ways]]\" (2005) by sending her back home to keep her safe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/tv/doctor-10-beautiful-things-time-doctor.php/4|title=Doctor Who: 10 Beautiful Things About 'The Time Of The Doctor'|work=WhatCulture.com|date=2013-12-26}}</ref>\n\nIt was widely expected that Coleman would leave the show at the end of 2014. Moffat has confirmed in numerous interviews that he wrote the character out twice \u2014 once for the end of Series 8 and again for the 2014 Christmas special \u2014 but ultimately convinced Coleman to stay on for one more series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-03-05/jenna-coleman-was-originally-going-to-leave-doctor-who-at-the-end-of-series-8 |title=Jenna Coleman was originally going to leave Doctor Who at the end of series 8|publisher=[[Radio Times]] |date=5 March 2015 |accessdate=18 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2015, Coleman officially announced on BBC Radio 1 that she would leave the show at the end of the ninth series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/doctorwho/entries/2a2689a8-5c52-46af-8e69-2fad42c46da3 |title=Jenna Coleman is Leaving Doctor Who |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=18 September 2015 |accessdate=18 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nColeman reprised the role of Clara for a cameo appearance in the 2017 Christmas Special [[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|\"Twice Upon a Time\"]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{Update|section|date=October 2015}}\nNick Setchfield of ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'' praised the effective surprise debut of Coleman as Oswin in \"Asylum of the Daleks\". He wrote, \"Coleman brings sauce and sparkiness, and while she initially seems a familiar Moffat archetype, all snarky cracks about the Doctor's chin and throwaway lines about sexual experimentation... there's a deeper vulnerability there too, which makes her eventual fate in this episode genuinely heart-skewering.\"<ref name= \"SFX asylum\">{{cite web| first = Nick | last = Setfield|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/09/01/doctor-who-7-01-asylum-of-the-daleks-review/|title=Doctor Who 7.01 \"Asylum of the Daleks\" Review|work= [[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]| date= 1 September 2012| accessdate= 2 September 2012}}</ref> Michael Hogan, writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', also found her debut promising and described her as \"enchanting in an elfin way&nbsp;\u2013 rather like a brunette, curvier, less annoying [[Fearne Cotton]]\".<ref name=\"telegraph2\">{{cite news|first = Michael |last= Hogan| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/9512002/A-bold-debut-for-the-new-Doctor-Who-assistant-review.html| title= A bold debut for the new Doctor Who assistant | type = review|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2 September 2012|accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe character's reintroduction as Clara in \"The Snowmen\" received generally positive reviews from critics. ''[[The Guardian]]''<nowiki />'s Dan Martin wrote, \"The masterstroke behind Jenna-Louise Coleman's surprise introduction is that it made us want to see more of her before Karen Gillan had even gone. The cheeky, self-assured Clara won a place in our hearts from the off.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Dan |url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2012/dec/25/doctor-who-snowmen-christmas-special |title=Doctor Who: The Snowmen&nbsp;\u2013 Christmas special 2012 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 December 2012 |accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref> Setchfield called her \"less of a motormouthed quip-merchant than [Oswin], but Coleman makes her equally winning&nbsp;\u2013 plucky, smart and riffing on a very promising chemistry with Matt Smith\".<ref name=\"SFX snowmen\">{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Setchfield|url= http://www.sfx.co.uk/2012/12/25/doctor-who-the-snowmen-review/|title = Doctor Who \"The Snowmen\" Review|work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=25 December 2012|accessdate= 23 March 2013}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Matt Risley felt that Clara \"trumped her already-bombastic debut with a character both fully formed and utterly unpredictable\". He praised the mystery surrounding her and her independence, commenting that she seemed to be the \"[[antithesis]]\" of Amy Pond as she was \"a girl who will wait for no-one\".<ref name=\"IGN snowmen\">{{cite web|first= Matt|last= Risley|url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/12/26/doctor-who-the-snowmen-review |title= Mary Poppins Got Game!|publisher= [[IGN]]| date= 25 December 2012| accessdate= 23 March 2013}}</ref> ''[[Radio Times]]'' reviewer Patrick Mulkern admitted that he had \"found Oswin's perkiness a tad wearing\", but he was \"completely won over\" by Coleman's Clara in \"The Snowmen\".<ref name=\"RT snowmen\">{{cite web|first=Patrick|last= Mulkern|url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-12-25/doctor-who--the-snowmen-review | title =Doctor Who&nbsp;\u2014 The Snowmen | type = review|work= [[Radio Times]]|date=25 December 2012|accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> Neela Debanth of ''[[The Independent]]'' felt that Clara's demise in \"The Snowmen\" made the episode \"a bit of a tease\" and set up the question of what the travelling Clara would be like. Unlike Mulkern, she favoured the Oswin version, describing her as \"much more fun and flirtatious\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/12/25/review-of-doctor-who-the-snowmen/ |title=Review of Doctor Who 'The Snowmen' |work=[[The Independent]] |date=25 December 2012 |accessdate=26 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228035143/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2012/12/25/review-of-doctor-who-the-snowmen/ |archivedate=28 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing \"The Bells of Saint John\", [[Digital Spy]]'s Morgan Jeffery said that the new Clara was \"more grounded and so far easier for the viewer to latch on to\" than her two predecessors, both of whom could have been harder to sustain as companions.<ref>{{cite web|first=Morgan|last=Jeffery|url= http://www.digitalspy.com/british-tv/s7/doctor-who/recaps/a468861/doctor-who-new-episode-the-bells-of-saint-john-review.html|title='Doctor Who': New episode 'The Bells of Saint John' review|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Mulkern said that he did not bother with the character's mystery and found it pleasing that Coleman played her as \"a straightforward modern companion with no baggage\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Patrick|last=Mulkern|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-03-30/doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john-review-steven-moffat-at-his-confident-playful-best|title=Doctor Who The Bells of Saint John review: \"Steven Moffat at his confident, playful best\"|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Setchfield described Clara as \"equally sparky and winning but altogether younger and possibly just a tad more vulnerable than her previous incarnations\" with a \"helplessly watchable chemistry\" with Smith.<ref>{{cite web |first= Nick|last= Setchfield | url = http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/03/30/doctor-who-7-6-the-bells-of-saint-john-review/|title=Doctor Who 7.06 \"The Bells of Saint John\" | type = review|work= [[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=30 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref> Debnath described her as a \"softer version\" of Oswin, still hoping that \"the character will be taken up a notch, challenging the Doctor more and bouncing off him like Oswin did.<ref>{{cite web | first = Neela | last = Debnath | url = http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/03/30/review-of-doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john/ | type = review | title = Doctor Who 'The Bells of Saint John' | work = [[The Independent]] | date = 30 March 2013 | accessdate = 31 March 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130402005827/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/03/30/review-of-doctor-who-the-bells-of-saint-john/ | archivedate = 2 April 2013 }}</ref> However, the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''<nowiki />'s Jon Cooper expressed concern that Clara, despite Coleman's success, was too similar to Amy.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jon|last=Cooper|url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-reviews/doctor-who-review-jenna-louise-coleman-1792420|title= Doctor Who review: Jenna-Louise Coleman is great, but The Bells of Saint John required a bit more heart|work= The [[Daily Mirror]]|date= 30 March 2013|accessdate= 31 March 2013}}</ref> Mike Higgins of ''The Independent'' felt that Coleman was \"an improvement\" upon Gillan, but wrote that \"the pairing of an intellectually bright but emotionally dim male with a techno-illiterate but wised up female is a tired old trope of much drama and comedy\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Higgins|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/tv-review-doctor-who--the-doctors-back-with-his-snog-box-8555083.html | type =TV review | title = Doctor Who&nbsp;\u2014 The Doctor's back, with his snog box|work=[[The Independent]]|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe character's development has also been met with positive reviews. Martin praised how her backstory was fleshed out in \"The Rings of Akhaten\", as otherwise the character \"was danger of becoming simply a story arc in the shape of a girl\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Dan|last=Martin|url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/06/doctor-who-rings-of-akhaten |title= Doctor Who: The Rings of Akhaten&nbsp;\u2013 series 33, episode seven|newspaper= [[The Guardian]]|date= 6 April 2013| accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref>  ''SFX''<nowiki />'s Richard Edwards wrote that she had the potential to be \"a truly great companion\", and that it was \"refreshing to see a companion who isn't in total awe of the Doctor... and she's not afraid to take the lead when she needs to\".<ref name=\"SFX\">{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Edwards |url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/04/06/doctor-who-7-07-the-rings-of-akhaten-review/ |title=Doctor Who 7.07 \"The Rings of Akhaten\" Review |work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]] |date=6 April 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130408235001/http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/04/06/doctor-who-7-07-the-rings-of-akhaten-review/ |archivedate=8 April 2013 }}</ref> Debnath praised her \"caring nature\" and \"lovely maternal side\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Neela |last=Debnath |url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/06/review-of-doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten/ |type=review |title=Doctor Who 'The Rings of Akhaten' |work=[[The Independent]] |date=6 April 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130408103203/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/06/review-of-doctor-who-the-rings-of-akhaten/ |archivedate=8 April 2013 }}</ref> but felt that she could be \"annoyingly na\u00efve\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Neela|last=Debnath|url=http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/13/review-of-doctor-who-cold-war/|title=Review of 'Cold War'|work=[[The Independent]]|date=13 April 2013|accessdate=14 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413205025/http://blogs.independent.co.uk/2013/04/13/review-of-doctor-who-cold-war/|archivedate=13 April 2013}}</ref> Dave Golder of ''SFX'' stated that Clara was \"to an extent, a bit of a cartoon character\" and that Moffat was better at writing her in \"The Name of the Doctor\" than some of the preceding writers. He also commented that she \"still feels too new a companion (and an underdeveloped one) to really care about her sacrifice\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=Golder|url=http://www.sfx.co.uk/2013/05/18/doctor-who-7-13-the-name-of-the-doctor-review-2/|title=Doctor Who 7.13 \"The Name of The Doctor\" | type = review |work=[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]|date=18 May 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nClara Oswald has been very divisive among the ''Doctor Who fanbase'' with many criticizing her character traits such as being a \"control freak\" as \"irritating\" and \"unlikeable\" as well as her character progression throughout her journey in the TARDIS as \"boring\" and \"bland\". However Coleman's performance has been widely praised.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rryyj/profiles/clara-oswald Clara Oswald] at the [[BBC One]] ''Doctor Who'' website\n*[http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/characters/clara/ Clara] at [[BBC America]]'s ''Doctor Who'' website\n{{TardisDataCore|Clara Oswald}}\n\n{{Doctor Who companions|11|12}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oswald, Clara}}\n[[Category:Doctor Who companions]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Fictional nannies]]\n[[Category:Fictional hackers]]\n[[Category:Fictional governesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional schoolteachers]]\n", "name_user": "ArkhamBen17", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_Oswald"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in South Korea}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea\n | map1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea (Density).svg\n | legend1 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 16 April): {{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201399}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 100\u2013499}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 500\u2013999}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed 1000\u20139999}}{{legend|#630606|Confirmed \u226510000}}\n| map2 = Coronavirus Outbreak in South Korea over Time.gif\n| legend2 = Coronavirus pandemic in South Korea over time (since January 20, 2020).<br /><div style=\"{{linear-gradient|left|#ffffff, #ff0000}}; border:solid 1px black; width:50px; height:0.5em; float:left; position:relative; top:0.4em;\">&nbsp;</div> &nbsp; Number of cases ([[logarithmic scale|logarithmically]]){{legend|#e7e8e6|Day not included in map}}{{legend|#989896|Day included in map}}{{legend|#444443|Last day included in map}}\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = [[Incheon International Airport]]\n| location = [[South Korea]]\n| arrival_date = 20 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases = 7,757\n| confirmed_cases = 10,613\n| suspected_cases = 14,268\n| deaths = 229\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|ncov.mohw.go.kr/en}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[South Korea]] was announced on 20 January 2020.<ref name=\"mk\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4 \ud55c\uad6d\uc778 \uccab\ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778 |url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |website=MK |publisher=\uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |accessdate=24 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124134926/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The number of confirmed cases increased on 19 February by 20, and on 20 February by 58<ref name=\"Getnews_58_Shincheonji\">{{cite web|url=http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|script-title=ko:31\ubc88 \ud658\uc790 \uc5f0\uad00 \uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0\uad50\ud68c \ub300\ub0a8\ubcd1\uc6d0\uc11c \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 58\uba85, 1\uba85 \uc0ac\ub9dd|date=20 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102733/http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> or 70,<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\">{{cite news | last1= Shin | first1= Hyonhee | last2= Cha | first2= Sangmi | title= 'Like a zombie apocalypse': Residents on edge as coronavirus cases surge in South Korea |trans-title = <!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 20 February 2020 |agency=[[Thomson Reuters]] | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea-cases/like-a-zombie-apocalypse-residents-on-edge-as-coronavirus-cases-surge-in-south-korea-idUSKBN20E04F |accessdate=20 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/D1K5i |archivedate= 20 February 2020 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> giving a total of 346 confirmed cases on 21 February 2020, according to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea]] ([[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]]), with the sudden jump mostly attributed to \"Patient 31\" who participated in a gathering at a [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus|Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony]] church in [[Daegu]].<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korea reports 161 new cases, bringing total to 763; 7th death reported |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=24 February 2020 |date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224060714/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAmidst the fears of further contamination, mass gatherings in the affected cities were cancelled and a few hundred soldiers in [[Daegu]] are in isolation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seoul city to ban rallies, Shincheonji church services to curb virus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221112436/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soldiers in Daegu areas banned from leaving bases, meeting visitors |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221145843/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 4 February 2020, in order to help prevent the spread of COVID-19, South Korea is denying entry to foreigners traveling from [[Hubei|Hubei Province]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | title=S. Korea Bars Foreigners Traveling from Hubei Province | access-date=2 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309151058/http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | archive-date=9 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-28/as-virus-spreads-koreans-blame-refusal-to-stop-chinese-visitors |title=As Virus Spreads, Koreans Blame Refusal to Stop Chinese Visitors |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2020-02-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAs of 9 April 2020, South Korea has about 10,423 cases and 204 deaths,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|title=Coronavirus South Korea|website=Worldometer|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173023/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with over 494,711 people having been tested, a [[case fatality rate]] of 1.95%, which is lower than the WHO's global case fatality rate of 4.34%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coronaboard.kr/en/|title=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|website=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324053131/https://coronaboard.kr/en/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSouth Korea introduced what was considered one of the largest and best-organised epidemic control programs in the world, along with Taiwan,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |title=Taiwan Has Been Shut Out of Global Health Discussions |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323222040/https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324085234/https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |title=Coronavirus Lessons from Singapore, Taiwan and Hong Kong |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324174105/https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Different measures have been taken to screen the mass population for the virus, and isolate any infected people as well as trace and quarantine those who contacted them, without further lockdown.<ref name=science20200317 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |title=Coronavirus in South Korea: How 'trace, test and treat' may be saving lives |first=Laura |last=Bicker |work=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190601/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rapid and extensive tests taken by South Korea have been judged successful in limiting the spread of the outbreak despite not using the drastic measure of quarantining entire cities.<ref name=science20200317>{{cite journal |journal=Science |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success? |first=Dennis |last=Normile |date=17 March 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abb7566 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205413/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |title=South Korea's coronavirus lessons: Quick, easy tests; monitoring |first=Kelly |last=Kasulis |date=19 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320144222/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |title=South Korea took rapid, intrusive measures against Covid-19 \u2013 and they worked |first1=Alexis |last1=Dudden |first2=Andrew |last2=Marks |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320143716/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 200\n | direction = vertical\n\n | image1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea.svg\n | caption1 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 16 April): {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}{{legend|#00cc00|14 days no confirmed cases}}\n\n| image2 = COVID-19 outbreak South Korea per capita cases map.svg\n| caption2 = Confirmed cases per million residents by province or city\n\n | image3 = Confirmed Cases of Coronavirus in South Korea (English version).png\n | caption3 = Number of confirmed coronavirus cases by provinces & special cities.\n}}\n\nDuring the first four weeks, South Korea controlled the potential spread of COVID-19 by using high-tech resources like tracking the use of credit cards and checking CCTV footage of confirmed patients. However, since 18 February, the number of cases increased to more than 1,700 after discovery of the fact that patient No. 31 was a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus]]. Some media reported that was difficult for [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] to screen the patient because Shincheonji teaches that illness is sin. Many members were uncooperative with KCDC and could not be contacted.<ref name=fp20200227>{{cite web | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | title=Cults and Conservatives Spread Coronavirus in South Korea | access-date=4 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307042428/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | archive-date=7 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Shincheonji denied this, and other sources report that the sect did cooperate with the authorities.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| title=Opinion &#124; Being Called a Cult is One Thing, Being Blamed for an Epidemic is Quite Another| newspaper=The New York Times| date=9 March 2020| last1=Rashid| first1=Raphael| access-date=21 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321153230/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| archive-date=21 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> About half of confirmed cases were linked to the Shincheonji Church as of 27 February; this was verified by health officials.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title=How religion is playing a role in the spread of coronavirus in Korea | access-date=12 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301081155/https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | archive-date=1 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> As of 10 March, the KCDC was able to contact and test most of the Shincheonji Church members, with the total number of tests nationally standing at around 200,000.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===20 January \u2013 17 February===\n[[File:Shincheonji Daegu Church 9 20200302.jpg|thumb|left|Shincheonji Daegu Church]]\n[[File:0222 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uc608\ubc29\uc218\uce59 \ud3ec\uc2a4\ud130 \uc601\ubb38.jpg|thumb|right|Recommendations for preventing COVID-19 released by KCDC under the [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Ministry of Health and Welfare]] of South Korea.]]\nOn 20 January, the first confirmed case was identified as a 35-year-old Chinese woman. The first South Korean national to be infected occurred three days later was a 55-year-old man who worked in Wuhan and returned for a checkup with flu symptoms. The two infection reports were publicly released on 24 January.<ref name=\"mk\"/>\n\nOn 26 January, a third case as a 54-year-old South Korean man. He had used a rental car and visited three restaurants, a hotel, a convenience store and met his family before admitting himself to hospital. All these places were disinfected.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 27 January, a fourth case was reported as a 55-year-old South Korean man who returned from Wuhan on 20 January. He first experienced flu symptoms on 21 January and suffered further complications four days later, eventually turning himself in. Both cases were tallied into formal records on 27 January.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uad6d \ub124\ubc88\uc9f8 '\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098' \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u202655\uc0b4 \ub0a8\uc131 |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |work=[[The Hankyoreh]] |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=27 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127101855/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |archive-date=27 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, an update on the first four patients indicated that the first three patients were showing weaker symptoms and recovering well while the fourth patient was getting treatment from [[pneumonia]]. Rumours circulated that the fourth patient had died which health authorities denied.<ref name=\"twelve\" />\n\nTwo more confirmed cases were reported on 30 January with the fifth patient being a 32-year-old South Korean man who returned from his work at Wuhan on 24 January. The sixth patient was the first case in South Korea who had never visited Wuhan. The 56-year-old man caught the virus when visiting a restaurant with the third patient.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 2\uba85 \ub298\uc5b4\u00b7\u00b7\u00b76\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790, \uad6d\ub0b4 \ucd5c\ucd08 '2\ucc28\uac10\uc5fc' |url=http://www.doctorstimes.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=209807 |website=\uc758\uc0ac\uc2e0\ubb38 |publisher=\uc774\ud55c\uc194 |accessdate=30 January 2020|date = 30 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, a seventh patient was reported as a 28-year-old South Korean man returning from [[Wuhan]] on 23 January. He developed symptoms on 26 January, and was admitted to the hospital on 28 January.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098' 7\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u2026\uc6b0\ud55c\uc11c \uc785\uad6d\ud55c 28\uc138 \ud55c\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011368450&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver News |publisher=\uc5f0\ud569\ub274\uc2a4 |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> On the same day, four more patients were admitted into the record as the eighth patient, 62-year-old South Korean woman, returned from Wuhan. The ninth patient caught the virus from the fifth patient through direct contact while the tenth and the eleventh patient were the wife and child who were infected while visiting the sixth patient.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4: 11\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778...\ud604\uc7ac\uae4c\uc9c0 \ud655\uc9c4 \uc0ac\ub840 \uc815\ub9ac |url=https://www.bbc.com/korean/news-51320986 |newspaper=BBC News \ucf54\ub9ac\uc544 |accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, a 49-year-old Chinese national working in [[Japan]] as a tour guide was confirmed as the twelfth patient. He caught the virus while visiting a Japanese patient in Japan and entered South Korea through [[Gimpo International Airport]] on 19 January.<ref name=\"twelve\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098'\uad6d\ub0b4 12\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790\u2026\uc77c\ubcf8\ud658\uc790 \uc811\ucd09 49\uc138 \uc911\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011370927&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver |publisher=Yonhap News Agency |accessdate=1 February 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The KCDC confirmed an additional three cases on 2 February, bringing the total to fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|title=S. Korea Reports 3 More Cases of Novel Coronavirus, Total Now at 15|first=|date=2 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202014910/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|archive-date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA woman, who had returned from [[Thailand]] after a five-day vacation, was tested positive and confirmed as the sixteenth case on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korean woman travelling home from Thailand tests positive for virus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=4 February 2020 |date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204092646/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three more cases were confirmed on 5 February, bringing the total case count to 19. The seventeenth and nineteenth patients had attended a conference in Singapore and been in contact with an infected individual there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yna.kr/AEN20200205002356320|title=3 More Virus Cases Bring S. Korea's Total to 19, Two Confirmed after Trip to Singapore|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The very same day the KCDC announced that the second patient had been released from hospital after being tested negative in consecutive tests, becoming the country's first coronavirus patient to fully recover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|title=S. Korea Releases First Fully Recovered Coronavirus Patient from Hospital|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205133506/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ {{nowrap|Details of the first 30 confirmed cases in South Korea (As of 17 February 2020)}}\n! Case\n! Date\n! Age\n! Gender\n! Nationality\n! Place of stay\n! Hospital of admission\n! Visited Wuhan?\n! Entry date\n! Status\n! Contacts of case\n! Note\n! Source\n|-\n|1\n|20 January 2020\n|35\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|[[Incheon]]\n|Incheon Metropolitan City Medical Center, [[Incheon]]\n|Yes\n|19 January 2020\n|Discharged (6 February 2020)\n|45\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\">{{cite web |title=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d(COVID)-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669(\uc815\ub840\ube0c\ub9ac\ud551) |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea |date=12 February 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a20501000000&bid=0015 |access-date=28 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305155753/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a20501000000&bid=0015 |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|24 January 2020\n|55\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|22 January 2020\n|Discharged (5 February 2020)\n|75\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|3\n|26 January 2020\n|54\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Goyang\n|Myongji Hospital, [[Goyang]]\n|Yes\n|20 January 2020\n|Discharged (12 February 2020)\n|16\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|4\n|27 January 2020\n|55\n|Male\n|Korean\n|[[Pyeongtaek]]\n|[[Seoul National University Bundang Hospital]], [[Seongnam]]\n|Yes\n|20 January 2020\n|Discharged (9 February 2020)\n|95\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|5\n|30 January 2020\n|33\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|Seoul Metropolitan City Seoul Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|24 January 2020\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|31\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|6\n|30 January 2020\n|55\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (19 February 2020)\n|17\n|Friend of case 3\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|7\n|30 January 2020\n|28\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|Seoul Metropolitan City Seoul Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|23 January 2020\n|Discharged (15 February 2020)\n|9\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|8\n|31 January 2020\n|62\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Gunsan\n|[[Wonkwang University]] Hospital, [[Iksan]]\n|Yes\n|23 January 2020\n|Discharged (12 February 2020)\n|113\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|9\n|31 January 2020\n|28\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|Seoul Metropolitan City Seoul Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (24 February 2020)\n|2\n|Friend of case 5\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|10\n|31 January 2020\n|54\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (19 February 2020)\n|43\n|W