nd of case 6\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|22\n|6 February 2020\n|46\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Naju\n|[[Chosun University]] Hospital, [[Gwangju]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (15 February 2020)\n|1\n|Brother of case 16\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|23\n|6 February 2020\n|57\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Seoul\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|23 January 2020\n|Discharged (29 February 2020)\n|23\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|24\n|6 February 2020\n|28\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Asan\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|31 January 2020\n|Discharged (27 February 2020)\n|0\n|Passenger on board the evacuation flights from Wuhan\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|25\n|9 February 2020\n|73\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|[[Seoul National University Bundang Hospital]], [[Seongnam]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (5 March 2020)\n|12\n|Mother of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|26\n|9 February 2020\n|51\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (8 March 2020)\n|12\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|27\n|9 February 2020\n|37\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (7 March 2020)\n|38\n|Wife of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|28\n|10 February 2020\n|30\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Goyang\n|Myongji Hospital, [[Goyang]]\n|Yes\n|20 January 2020\n|Discharged (17 February 2020)\n|1\n|Friend of case 3\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|29\n|16 February 2020\n|82\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|117\n|Friend of case 83\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|30\n|16 February 2020\n|68\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|27\n|Wife of case 29\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|}\n\n===18 February \u2013 29 February===\n{{anchor|Daegu outbreak}}\n[[File:2020 coronavirus cases in South Korea.svg|350px|thumb|left|[[Epidemic curve]] of COVID-19 in South Korea]]\n\nOn 18 February, South Korea confirmed its 31st case in Daegu, a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji]] religious organisation. The patient continued to go to gatherings of Shincheonji days after showing symptoms, which are typically held with people in very close proximity and include physical contact of the members. Many of the patient's close contacts would turn out to be infected, triggering a drastic escalation of the South Korean spread of confirmed cases of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] infection.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|title=Coronavirus: South Korea cluster drives huge rise in cases|date=22 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305220400/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=fp20200227/>\n\nOn 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20. On 20 February 70<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> new cases were confirmed, giving a total of 104 confirmed cases, according to the KCDC. According to ''[[Reuters]]'', KCDC attributed the sudden jump of 70 cases linked to \"Patient No. 31\", who had participated in a gathering in [[Daegu]] at the Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony.<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" />\n\nOn 20 February, the streets of Daegu were empty in reaction to the Shincheonji outbreak. A resident described the reaction, stating \"It's like someone dropped a bomb in the middle of the city. It looks like a zombie apocalypse.\"<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> The first death was reported<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|title=South Korea reports first coronavirus death as infections linked to church rise|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310234601/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in a mental ward of Cheongdo Daenam Hospital in [[Cheongdo County]]. According to the mayor of Daegu, the number of suspected cases as of 21 February was 544 among 4,400 examined followers of the church.<ref>{{cite web |title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0 \uad00\ub828 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 76\uba85\uc73c\ub85c \ub298\uc5b4...\ub300\uad6c \uad50\uc778 \uc758\uc2ec\uc790\ub9cc 544\uba85 |publisher=Chosun.com |date=21 February 2020 |url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102756/https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hospital was suspected as the source of the present outbreak after it was visited by a woman who became the second fatal case of South Korea on that day. Upon investigation, it was determined that the infection had spread to that hospital through a funeral ceremony attended by members of the church.<ref name=\"b82186\" /><ref name=\"koreabiomed\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Han-soo |title=COVID-19 patients soar to 204 in Korea |url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Biomedical Review |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102842/http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAll South Korean military bases were on lockdown after tests confirmed three soldiers to be positive for the virus.<ref name=\"b82186\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|title = South Korea virus 'emergency' as cases increase|work = BBC News|date = 21 February 2020|access-date = 21 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200307193706/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|archive-date = 7 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Airlines cut connections and cultural schedules were being canceled due to fears of further spread.<ref>{{cite news |title=Airlines to suspend more flights over coronavirus |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221023912/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Song |first1=Seung-hyun |title=Foreign artists delay concerts in Korea due to spread of COVID-19 |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221190026/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[United States Forces Korea]] raised the alert level from low to moderate and cut off non-essential travel to and from USFK Daegu.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url = https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|title = US Forces Korea imposes new coronavirus protections after uptick in S Korea cases|date = 19 February 2020|access-date = 23 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200306190234/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|archive-date = 6 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> USFK Daegu's school facilities were closed and non-essential personnel were ordered to stay at home while any visitors going there were not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"MT\" /> USFK announced that the widow of a retired soldier who was in Daegu was diagnosed to be positive for the virus on 24 February.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | title=USFK dependent tests positive for coronavirus, putting military on high alert in South Korea | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102852/https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | archive-date=26 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Camp Humphreys]] enacted virus detection protocols, including temperature checks and raised the alert level to high.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | title=US troops in Korea are on high alert for coronavirus after widow of retired soldier tests positive | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227153541/https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | archive-date=27 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 February, an American soldier based at Camp Carroll was diagnosed to be positive and was quarantined away from bases via off-base housing unit<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| title=U.S. Soldier infected as South Korea coronavirus cases rise above 1,260| newspaper=Reuters| date=26 February 2020| access-date=26 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231232/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| archive-date=3 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> with contact tracing done that showed his movements to Camp Walker.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | title=First U.S. Soldier in South Korea tests positive for coronavirus; towns sealed off in northern Italy | access-date=26 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134342/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | archive-date=5 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 February, among 9,336 followers of the church, 1,261 reported symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|script-title=ko:\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669 (2\uc6d4 22\uc77c 09\uc2dc)|first=|date=22 February 2020|url-status=live|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102804/http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> At the time, 169 confirmed cases involved the same church and another 111 came from the Cheongdo Daenam Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.go.kr/|script-title=ko:\uc9c8\ubcd1\uad00\ub9ac\ubcf8\ubd80|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130022550/http://www.cdc.go.kr/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 23 February saw another 123 cases with 75 being from Shincheonji<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 123 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 23 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200223090022/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 23 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> and 24 February saw 161 additional cases with 129 being from the same religious group. Over 27,000 people have been tested for the virus with 19,127 negative results.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 161 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201926/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 24 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, 15 countries imposed travel restrictions to and from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|title=15 countries have travel restrictions on South Korea|last=|first=|date=24 February 2020|website=CNN|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224070457/https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|archive-date=24 February 2020|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that a senior health official overseeing the COVID-19 efforts in Daegu tested positive and was also a member of Shincheonji.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |title= Coronavirus: infected health official leading South Korea's fight against Covid-19 is member of Shincheonji Church of Jesus doomsday cult |last= Park |first= Chan-kyong |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher=  |access-date= 25 February 2020 |quote= Official in charge of fight against the virus in western Daegu admits being member of cult after testing positive; 50 coworkers quarantined |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200225032613/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |archive-date= 25 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\":750tested\"/> Within a few days, a petition to the nation's president urging for the disbandment of the church had over 750,000 signatures. Their headquarters in [[Gwacheon]] was raided by law enforcement and government officials said all 245,000 members of the religious group would be found and tested.<ref name=\":750tested\">{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |title= Were you on this bus with a coronavirus patient? South Korea is on the hunt for infections |last= Kim |first= Victoria |date= 27 February 2020 |website= [[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote= Even a public health official in charge of infection prevention in Seo-gu in Daegu was revealed to be a member of the church after he was diagnosed with the virus. Many members hide their affiliation with the controversial church. More than 750,000 signed a petition to the South Korean president urging that the church be disbanded. Authorities in Gyeonggi province raided the group\u2019s headquarters in the city of Gwacheon, alleging that the church had been slow to turn over its list of members. South Korean officials said they would track down and test all 245,000 members of the church. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227235952/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |archive-date= 27 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, over 2,000 confirmed cases were reported.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |title= The Updates of COVID-19 in Republic of Korea As of 28 February 2020 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=  |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229165550/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 29 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 2 March, there were over 4,200 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366416&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 476 additional cases are confirmed |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 2 March 2020 |quote= As of 0:00, 2 March 2020, 476 additional cases are confirmed, compared to yesterday afternoon (16:00, 1 March) which brings in total number of confirmed cases to 4,212.}}</ref> With an additional 4,000 cases of COVID-19 within two weeks, and roughly 60% of the total infections nationwide having stemmed from the church, the Seoul city government asked prosecutors to press charges against the religious group's founder and senior members for murder, causing harm, and for violating the Infectious Disease and Control Act.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |title= Seoul city seeks murder charges against sect founder over virus |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[Yahoo!]] |publisher= [[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200302103858/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |archive-date= 2 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Interviews have occurred with all 230,000 members of the religious group and nearly 9,000 were said to be showing symptoms of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |title= Coronavirus: South Korea sect leader to face probe over deaths |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[BBC]] |publisher=  |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303014749/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |archive-date= 3 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Due to the number of infections in the country, ninety-five countries have banned or limited entry for South Korean passport holders.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |title= How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak |last= Kim |first= Suki |date= 4 March 2020 |website= [[The New Yorker]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote= Citing the number of covid-19 diagnoses in South Korea, ninety-five countries, including China and Japan, now ban or limit entry by South Korean nationals. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305132902/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Testing is also conducted at drive-through testing sites where patients do not leave their vehicles, but are met by medical personnel in hazmat suits over several stations. The process is completed in a few minutes and results come in several days.<ref name=cnn20200302>{{cite web |url= https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |title= South Korea pioneers coronavirus drive-through testing station |last1= Watson |first1= Ivan |last2= Jeong |first2= Sophie |date= 3 March 2020 |website= [[CNN]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305011008/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\nOn 8 March, [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] in South Korea announced that 79.4% of confirmed COVID-19 cases were related to group infection. KCDC also announced that outbreak associated with [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji Church]] totaled 4,482 infections, accounting for 62.8% of the total confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:[\ucd9c\ucc98: \uc911\uc559\uc77c\ubcf4] [\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uc885\ud569] \uc11c\uc6b8\ubc31\ubcd1\uc6d0 \ud658\uc790 1\uba85 \ud655\uc9c4\u2026\"\ub300\uad6c \uac70\uc8fc \uc228\uae30\uace0 \ub0b4\uc6d0\" |url=https://news.joins.com/article/23724705 |work=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |language=ko-kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|title=New cases of infections drop for third day|date=9 March 2020|website=m.koreatimes.co.kr|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310190619/https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n13 March was the first time since the outbreak on 20 January in which the number of recoveries, 177, was larger than the number of those who newly tested positive, 110.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693 |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4'\u2026\uc644\uce58>\uc2e0\uaddc \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 |author1= \uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |author2= \uc774\uc11d\ud76c |author3= \uc6b0\uc131\ub355 |date= 13 March 2020 |website= \ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c MBN |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095345/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693/ |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |title= \ub300\uad6c\uc11c \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubcf4\ub2e4 \uc644\uce58\uc790 \ub9ce\uc740 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \ud655\uc5f0 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 15 March 2020 |website= DongA |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315182415/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |archive-date= 15 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |title= 15\uc77c \uc6b0\ud55c\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 8162\uba85\u2026'\uace8\ub4e0 \ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \uc0ac\ud758\uc9f8 |author= \uae40\ub3d9\uc6b0 |date= 15 March 2020 |website= New Daily |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095344/http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> <!--- This part is an analysis from South Korean media, please do not delete this section without any farther discussion on the talk page---> However, with the recent cluster of cases in the [[Seoul Capital Area]], there are new fears that infections may rise sharply.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |title=Commentary: South Korea has been exemplary. Even then, it hasn't slayed COVID-19 |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324084938/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe controversy about Shincheonji also continued, and generated international interest. After the lawsuit started by the Mayor of Seoul, the police raided the church premises to check whether the list of members supplied by Shincheonji pursuant to a request by the authorities was, as the Mayor argued, not complete. The authorities checked the list seized during the raid with the one Shincheonji had supplied, and concluded that discrepancies were minor.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kim |first=So-hyun |date=17 March 2020 |title='Shincheonji didn't lie about membership figures' |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |work=The Korea Herald |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318185856/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom]] (USCIRF) expressed concern that religious freedom rights of Shincheonji members may be violated in South Korea by \"exaggerating the church's role in the outbreak,\" and stated that, \"USCIRF has received reports of individuals encountering discrimination at work and spousal abuse because of their affiliation with the church.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/2020%20Factsheet%20Covid-19%20and%20FoRB.pdf |title=The Global Response to the Coronavirus: Impact on Religious Practice and Religious Freedom |last=U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom |date=March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> USCIRF reported that South Korean \"Vice Minister of Health Kim Kang-lip has publicly stated that the Shincheonji church has cooperated with authorities.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\"/> The Belgian NGO [[Human Rights Without Frontiers]] and [[CESNUR]] released a \"White Paper\" claiming that, although it did make \"mistakes\" in its management of the crisis, Shincheonji had also been discriminated because of its status as an unpopular group in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Human Rights without frontiers release white paper on Coronavirus |url=https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |work=[[Risingbd.com]] |location=[[Dhaka]] |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319233319/https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Mener kristen sekt er utsatt for jakt p\u00e5 syndebukk for koronautbruddet |url=https://www.vl.no/nyhet/mener-kristen-sekt-er-utsatt-for-jakt-pa-syndebukk-for-koronautbruddet-1.1691863?paywall=true |work=[[V\u00e5rt Land (Norwegian newspaper)|V\u00e5rt Land]] |location=Oslo |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus after attending the [[River of Grace Community Church]]. The infections were claimed to have been caused by spraying salt-water into followers' mouths, under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=16 March 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nearly 140 churches in Gyeonggi Province, which surrounds Seoul and is part of the [[Greater Seoul Area]], will be closed if they do not implement preventative measures, including temperature checks, two-meter separation, and the wearing of masks.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3075527/coronavirus-south-korea-threatens-close-churches-not-enforcing |title= Coronavirus: South Korea threatens to close churches for not enforcing preventive measures |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=17 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= Reuters and Associated Press |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> As more churches are holding services despite a government order for social distancing, on 30 March, the controversial Manmin Central Church in Guro, Seoul became a cluster with 22 infections linked to a gathering in early March in which the group was preparing stock footage to use for online worship services. Other church clusters have appears in the cities of Suwon, Busan, Geochang, and Bucheon.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3077497/coronavirus-cluster-emerges-another-south-korean |title= Coronavirus cluster emerges at another South Korean church, as others press ahead with Sunday services\n|author= Park Chan-kyong |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n===April \u2013 present outbreak===\nAs infection rates have risen outside Korea leading to increases of sick arriving in the country (476 of 9,661 cases were imported as of 30 March), the KCDC will be implanting stronger infectious disease control measures for travelers coming from overseas as of 1 April. Additionally, new self-quarantine measures for travelers coming from Europe or the United States will be in effect from the same day. For example, those showing symptoms but test negative, and those who are without symptoms and are staying short-term in Korea, need to quarantine for two weeks in a government provided facility.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366687&tag=&nPage=2 |title= The updates on COVID-19 in Korea as of 30 March |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> Costs for the stay at the facility are the responsibility of the individual and total 100,000 won (US$81) per day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/119_287412.html |title= Korea deports Taiwanese woman for refusing to stay at quarantine facility |author= Jung Min-ho |date= 6 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote=  }}</ref> A few days later, a Taiwanese woman was deported on 5 April for refusing to stay in a quarantine facility as she initially agreed and then later disagreed with paying for the cost of staying at the government designated facility, reportedly costing around 100,000 won per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200406004451315|title=(LEAD) Taiwanese woman deported for refusing to stay at quarantine facility|last=\uc774\ubbfc\uc9c0|date=2020-04-06|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n45 people are being investigated by the police for allegedly violating COVID-19 self-isolation. Under the revised anti-infectious disease law, violators can face up to a year in prison, a 10 million won fine, or in the case of foreign passport holders\u2014deportation.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/177_287168.html |title= Coronavirus: 45 under police investigation for breaking self-isolation rules |author= Park Si-soo |date= 1 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 2 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> \n\nSeeing the [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|infodemic]] on COVID-19 information starting in China and spreading to Korea and the US, fake news researcher [[Cha Meeyoung]] of [[KAIST]] and the [[Institute for Basic Science]], along with researchers from [[Ewha Womans University]], started the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= \u201cFact before rumors\u201d campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 26 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |author=[[Cha Meeyoung]] |date= 24 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= Donga Science |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nA Canadian cast member with the touring ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'' stage play entered Korea on March 12, participated for roughly two weeks, and tested positive 2 April. An American colleague tested positive on 4 April, which shut down production of the musical until 14 April while the venue could be disinfected and contacts of the staff, those staying in the same hotel, and over 8,000 people who recently attended were contacted by health authorities who told them to stay indoors and contact a testing center if they develop symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/04/398_287384.html |title= Over 8,000 audience members to be monitored after musical actors test positive for COVID-19 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 5 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= Yonhap News |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote= More than 8,000 people who attended the musical \"Phantom of the Opera\" in Seoul will be closely monitored after two cast members tested positive for the novel coronavirus, authorities said Friday.}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/South Korea medical cases chart}}\n[[File:CoViD-19 KR.svg|thumb|right|upright=2|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/South Korea medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Containment==\nIn its efforts to fight and contain the virus, South Korea has combined testing with contact tracing.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nInfected South Koreans are required to go into isolation in government shelters. Their phones and credit card data are used to trace their prior movements and find their contacts. Those who are determined to have been near the infected individual receive phone alerts with information about their prior movements.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Virus Can Be Stopped, but Only With Harsh Steps, Experts Say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/health/coronavirus-restrictions-us.html|website=The New York Times|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324001725/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/health/coronavirus-restrictions-us.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Chun Byung-Chul, an epidemiologist at Korea University, high-risk patients who have underlying illnesses are prioritized for hospitalization. Patients with moderate symptoms are sent to \"repurposed corporate training facilities and spaces provided by public institutions,\" where they receive observation and medical support. Patients who recover and test negative twice are released. Close contacts and infected individuals with minimal symptoms who can measure their own temperatures and whose family members are free of any chronic disease are required to self-quarantine for two weeks. Local monitoring teams calls the quarantined twice a day to make sure that they stay where they are and to ask about symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success?|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success|website=Science|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205413/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nThose ordered to self-quarantine are required to download an app that alerts officials if the patient moves outside of the quarantine. Violators are fined up to $2,500.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=How South Korea Flattened the Curve |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/world/asia/coronavirus-south-korea-flatten-curve.html |website=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323230039/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/world/asia/coronavirus-south-korea-flatten-curve.html |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Impacts and reactions ==\n[[File:20200322 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud0c0\uc2dc\ub3c4 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \uc774\uc1a1(\ubd80\uc0b0\uc758\ub8cc\uc6d0) 05.jpg|thumb|[[Commons:Category:Transfer of a COVID-19 confirmed patient by Busan Medical Center using Busan Fire Services ambulance, 22 March 2020|Transfer of a COVID-19 confirmed patient by Busan Medical Center]]]]\n[[File:Coronavirus Check by Drive-Through.jpg|thumb|At the drive-through test center the medical staff examines patients with suspected [[COVID-19]] while in the vehicle. <br /> <br />The entire procedure of collecting a sample of secretions taking less than 10 minutes, and it's deployed to dozens of locations including [[Seoul]],[[Daegu]],[[Goyang]], [[Incheon]] and [[Sejong]].<ref name=\"businessinsider1\">{{cite web|author=Hyonhee Shin, Reuters |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/south-korea-launches-drive-thru-coronavirus-testing-facilities-as-demand-soars-2020-2?r=AU&IR=T |title=South Korea sets up drive-thru clinics to test for coronavirus |publisher=Business Insider |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51836898 Coronavirus in South Korea: How 'trace, test and treat' may be saving lives] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312212652/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51836898 |date=12 March 2020 }}</ref> <br /> <br />*Banner: Coronavirus-19 drive-thru  screening clinic<ref>{{cite web|author=Dair\u00edn Frawley in Seoul |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/irishwoman-in-south-korea-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-no-human-contact-1.4197702 |title=Irishwoman in South Korea: Drive-through testing for coronavirus, no human contact |publisher=Irishtimes.com |date=2020-01-04 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html South Korea has 'passed the peak' of the coronavirus outbreak, health minister hopes ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310121826/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:COVID19 South Korea pharmacy with sold out sign.jpg|thumb|Sign in Daejeon pharmacy stating all masks are sold out]]\n[[File:COVID19 South Korea pharmacy long line.jpg|thumb|Line outside a pharmacy in Sejong City awaiting the store to open so they can buy masks]]\n\nAs of 18 March, South Korea's [[KOSPI]] stock index has dropped nearly 30% compared to a month ago. The drop precipitated on 23 February, when the country raised the coronavirus alert to 'highest level'.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Huang |first1=Eustance |title=South Korea stocks drop nearly 4% as country raises coronavirus alert to 'highest level' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/24/asia-markets-south-korea-coronavirus-currencies-china.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=23 February 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227131602/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/24/asia-markets-south-korea-coronavirus-currencies-china.html |archive-date=27 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 15 March, the KOSPI closed at 1,771.44 and the Kosdaq finished at 524 points, down 7%, prompting the Financial Supervisory Commission to impose a six-month ban on short-selling, the first such drastic action in nearly nine years. This was despite a markedly lower daily increase in cases. Automaker [[Hyundai Motor Company]], having shut down its factories as the outbreak intensified, saw exports drop 21.4% in February from the same month last year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirk |first1=Donald |title=Coronavirus Hits South Korean Markets Despite Easing Of Crisis |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/donaldkirk/2020/03/15/coronavirus-hits-south-korean-markets-despite-easing-of-crisis/ |website=Forbes |language=en |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151222/https://www.forbes.com/sites/donaldkirk/2020/03/15/coronavirus-hits-south-korean-markets-despite-easing-of-crisis/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Social impact ===\n[[File:20200311 \ud604\uc7a5\ubc29\ubb38 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uad00\ub828 \ucf54\ud638\ud2b8 \uaca9\ub9ac\ud574\uc81c \ubcd1\uc6d0 \ub4f1(\uc9c4\uad6c \ub4dc\ub77c\uc774\ube0c\uc2a4\ub8e8) 02.jpg|thumb|Drive-through test center in Busan]]\nAs of 25 February, Daegu officials were aggressively warning residents to take precautions, while allowing private businesses such as restaurants to stay open. As a precautionary measure, many restaurants check the temperatures of their customers before accepting them. It is common for \"offices, hotels, and other large buildings\" to use thermal image cameras in order to identify people with fevers.<ref name=\"auto\"/> All Daegu's public libraries, museums, churches, day-care centers and courts had been closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=In Coronavirus Crisis, Korean City Tries Openness, a Contrast to China |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/world/asia/daegu-south-korea-coronavirus.html |website=The New York Times |date=25 February 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303064635/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/world/asia/daegu-south-korea-coronavirus.html |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=What happened since then?|date=March 2020}}\n\nApart from the city of Daegu and the church community involved, most of South Korea is operating close to normality, although nine planned festivals have been closed and tax-free retailers are closing.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-affected-countries-south-korea-covid-19-outbreak-measures-impact/|title=South Korea Coronavirus: Outbreak, measures and impact|language=en-GB|access-date=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222033431/https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-affected-countries-south-korea-covid-19-outbreak-measures-impact/|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The South Korean military manpower agency made an announcement that conscription from Daegu will temporarily be suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2020022313237612860|script-title=ko:\uc774\uc778\uc601 \"\uc804\uad6d \ud559\uad50 '\uac1c\ud559\uc5f0\uae30' \uac80\ud1a0\ud574\uc57c\"\u2026 \uad50\uc721\ub2f9\uad6d\uc5d0 \ub300\ucc45 \uc8fc\ubb38 \u2013 \uba38\ub2c8\ud22c\ub370\uc774 \ub274\uc2a4|date=23 February 2020|website=news.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=23 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102822/https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2020022313237612860|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Daegu Office of Education'' decided to postpone the start of every school in the region by one week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221006900325|title=Military to temporarily suspend drafting soldiers from Daegu|last=\ucd5c\uc218\ud5a5|date=21 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223083157/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221006900325|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNumerous educational institutes have temporarily shut down, including dozens of kindergartens in [[Daegu]] and several elementary schools in [[Seoul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moe.go.kr/boardCnts/view.do?boardID=294&boardSeq=79822&lev=0&searchType=null&statusYN=W&page=1&s=moe&m=020402&opType=N|title= Korean Ministry of Education|last=|first=|date=|website=Ministry of Education (South Korea)|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> As of 18 February, most universities in South Korea had announced plans to postpone the start of the spring semester. This included 155 universities planning to delay the semester start by two weeks to 16 March, and 22 universities planning to delay the semester start by one week to 9 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=226388|script-title=ko:177\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \uac1c\uac15 \uc5f0\uae30\u00b7\u00b7\u00b780%\uac00 '2\uc8fc \uacb0\uc815'|date=18 February 2020|website=\ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|language=ko|access-date=23 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102832/http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=226388|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, on 23 February 2020, all kindergartens, elementary schools, middle schools, and high schools were announced to delay the semester start from 2 to 9 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200223/99835113/2|script-title=ko:\uad50\uc721\ubd80 \"\uc804\uad6d \uc720\u00b7\ucd08\u00b7\uc911\u00b7\uace0 1\uc8fc\uc77c \uac1c\ud559 \uc5f0\uae30\u20263\uc6d49\uc77c \uac1c\ud559\"|date=23 February 2020|website=donga.com|language=ko|access-date=24 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223204454/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200223/99835113/2|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Did they end up postponing? Was the duration extended?|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe economy of South Korea is forecast to grow 1.9%, which is down from 2.1%. The government has provided 136.7 billion [[South Korean won|won]] for local governments as support.<ref name=\":4\" /> The government has also organized the procurement of masks and other hygiene equipment.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nEntertainment agency [[SM Entertainment]] reportedly donated five hundred million [[South Korean won|won]] in efforts to fight the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailian.co.kr/news/view/871813?sc=Naver|script-title=ko:SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0 \ubc29\uc9c0 \uc704\ud55c \uc131\uae08 5\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80|publisher=Dailian|date=28 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228032331/https://www.dailian.co.kr/news/view/871813%3Fsc%3DNaver|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1241496 |script-title=ko:SM, \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 19 \uc0ac\ud0dc\uc5d0 5\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80 \"\uc758\ub8cc\uc9c4 \uc704\ud574 \ud798 \uc368\ub2ec\ub77c\" [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|publisher=X Sports News|date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2034049|script-title=ko:SM\uc5d4\ud130, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uc0ac\ud0dc 5\uc5b5 \uae30\ubd80\u2026\"\uc758\ub8cc\uc9c4\uc5d0 \ud798\ub418\uace0\uc790\" [\uacf5\uc2dd]|publisher=TV Report|date=28 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228032333/https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2034049|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[K-pop|K-POP]] industry, the rapid spread of the coronavirus within South Korea has led to the cancellations or postponing of concerts and other events for K-POP acts within and outside of South Korea, with example situations including the cancellation of the remaining Asia dates and the Europe leg for [[Seventeen (South Korean band)|Seventeen]]\u2019s Ode To You Tour on 9 February 2020 and the cancellation of all Seoul dates for [[BTS (band)|BTS]]' [[Map of the Soul Tour]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=pledis_17|number=1226355059794952193|date=9 February 2020 |script-title=ko:SEVENTEEN WORLD TOUR [ODE TO YOU] \ucde8\uc18c \uad00\ub828 \uacf5\uc9c0}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=bts_bighit|number=1233195543842549760|date=28 February 2020|script-title=ko:[\uacf5\uc9c0] #BTS MAP OF THE SOUL TOUR \u2013 SEOUL \uacf5\uc5f0 \ucde8\uc18c \uc548\ub0b4 (+ENG/JPN/CHN)}}</ref>\n\n===Travel restrictions===\n{{See|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Map of Travel restrictions related to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic - korea.svg|thumb|500px|\n{{legend|#55D400|South Korea}}\n{{legend|#AA0000|Entrance refused to people from South Korea}}\n{{legend|#FF5555|Entrance refused to people from some areas of South korea}}\n{{legend|#003380|Imposed quarantine on people arriving from South Korea}}\n{{legend|#9dc4ff|Other restrictions (self-quarantines, medical examination requirements, monitoring measures)}}]]\nAs of 20 March, a total of 171 countries and territories had issued entry bans or suspended visas for travelers from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u9751\uc774 '\ud0a4\ud2b8 \uc218\ucd9c \uc790\ub791' UAE\ub3c4 \uc5b4\uc81c \ube57\uc7a5\u2026 171\uad6d\uc774 \ud55c\uad6d\u767c \uc785\uad6d\uae08\uc9c0|date=20 March 2020|publisher=Chosun.com|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/20/2020032000121.html|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232044/http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/20/2020032000121.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, USFK announced that travel restrictions for Cheonan city had been removed due to a decline in COVID-19 cases. Troops and Defense Department personnel residing in Cheonan were told to \"contact their command prior to returning to work.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=USFK COVID-19 Information|date=16 March 2020|publisher=usfk.mil|url=https://www.usfk.mil/Media/News/Article/2070556/usfk-covid-19-information/|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228025801/https://www.usfk.mil/Media/News/Article/2070556/usfk-covid-19-information/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Government reactions ===\n[[File:20200227 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ub300\uc751 \uc911\uc559\uc7ac\ub09c\uc548\uc804\ub300\ucc45\ubcf8\ubd80 \ud68c\uc758(\uc7ac\ub09c\uc548\uc804\ub300\ucc45\ubcf8\ubd80) 01.jpg|thumb|Videotelephony of Central Disaster and Safety Countermeasure Headquarters]]\n\n===Number of inspections===\nThe Blue House announced on 28 February the current status of coronavirus tests in Korea, comparing the testing situation in the United States and Japan. The number of inspections was 26 and 120 times higher than in those countries respectively as of 28 Feb. The cumulative number of inspections was about 53,000 by South Korea, while Japan was about 2,000, and in US about 440 cases were examined.<ref name=chosun-numberoftests />\n\n===Reactions from KMA===\nOn 26 January, the Korean Medical Association (KMA) asked the government to temporarily bar entry to all travelers arriving from mainland China, but this recommendation was not followed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak|title=How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Suki|last=Kim|website=The New Yorker|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305132902/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 January, KMA President Choi Dae-zip said: \"The third confirmed case indicates that we have reached the point where we have to get rid of passive stance and actively prepare for the worsening of the situation, (and) the government should thoroughly monitor the trend of China's national outbreak of the virus and prepare administrative measures such as complete entry ban from China in case of the worst situation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7284|title=[2019-Novel Coronavirus] Doctors join general public calling for entry ban on Chinese - Korea Biomedical Review|date=27 January 2020|website=www.koreabiomed.com}}</ref> On 3 February, The KMA recommended halting all travel from China, rather than only from Hubei province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=151059|title=KMA Urges Expanding Restriction Measures to All of China|website=world.kbs.co.kr|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212225559/http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=151059|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After all, The KMA called for stronger government response in a total of six statements between 20 January, when the nation's first confirmed case occurred, and 18 February. A short time after that, cases spiked in Daegu and throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/public-anger-swells-in-south-korea-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Public Anger Swells in South Korea Over Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Tae-jun|last=Kang|website=thediplomat.com|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229141909/https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/public-anger-swells-in-south-korea-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Public reactions ===\n==== Presidential approval rating ====\nAlthough there are many confirmed cases of COVID-19, President [[Moon Jae-in]]'s approval rating rose by two percentage points to 44%. During the MERS crisis, the previous President [[Park Geun-hye]]'s approval rating had fallen sharply to 29% due to inadequate management the MERS infection.<ref>{{cite news|trans-title=At the time of MERS, Park Geun-hye support rate plunged\u2026 Corona 19 Moon Jae-in support rate rather rises |script-title=ko:\uba54\ub974\uc2a4 \ub550 \u6734 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 \ud3ed\ub77d\u2026\ucf54\ub85c\ub09819\uc5d4 \u6587 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 \uc624\ud788\ub824 \uc0c1\uc2b9 |url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/2020030620737 |work=[[Korea Economic Daily]] |language=ko-kr}}</ref>\n\nIn opinion poll conducted by Gallup Korea in the second week of March 2020, president Moon's approval rating has risen by 5% to 49%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gallup.co.kr/dir/GallupKoreaDaily/GallupKoreaDailyOpinion_392(20200313).pdf|title=\ub370\uc77c\ub9ac \uc624\ud53c\ub2c8\uc5b8 \uc81c392\ud638(2020\ub144 3\uc6d4 2\uc8fc) - \ucd1d\uc120 \uae30\ub300, \ucc28\uae30 \uc815\uce58 \uc9c0\ub3c4\uc790, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819, \ub9c8\uc2a4\ud06c \uad00\ub828 \uc778\uc2dd|work=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Anti-foreigner sentiment ====\nIn February 2020, an entrance to a South Korean restaurant in downtown [[Seoul]] reportedly had a sign in red Chinese characters stating: \"No Chinese Allowed.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/no-chinese-allowed-racism-and-fear-are-now-spreading-along-with-the-coronavirus-2020-01-29|title='No Chinese allowed': Racism and fear are now spreading along with the coronavirus|last=Fottrell|first=Quentin|website=MarketWatch |access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202231235/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/no-chinese-allowed-racism-and-fear-are-now-spreading-along-with-the-coronavirus-2020-01-29|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \"No Chinese\" signs have been cropping up, and some businesses are simply banning all foreigners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-brings-anti-chinese-sentiment-south-korea-200221094732254.html|title=Coronavirus brings out anti-Chinese sentiment in South Korea|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312151251/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-brings-anti-chinese-sentiment-south-korea-200221094732254.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some foreign residents have been excluded from the government mask distribution program as it is currently only allowed to 1.25 million foreigners who were subscribed to the public health insurance.<ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200314000082 [Exclusive] Expats sidelined in Seoul\u2019s mask-rationing {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314123806/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200314000082 |date=14 March 2020 }}</ref> Concerning COVID-19, more than 760,000 South Korean citizens have signed a petition lobbying the government to ban Chinese tourists from entering the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Not Enough Doctors in Daegu: As Virus Cases Rise, South Korea's Response Is Criticized |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-enough-doctors-in-daegu-as-virus-cases-rise-south-koreas-response-is-criticized-11582547600 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=24 February 2020 |access-date=29 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229101452/https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-enough-doctors-in-daegu-as-virus-cases-rise-south-koreas-response-is-criticized-11582547600 |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Shin28Jan2020\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|title=South Koreans call in petition for Chinese to be barred over virus|last=Shin|first=Hyonhee|date=28 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154836/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> The Daegu Lantern Festival mistakenly posted a notice in English that no foreigners are allowed to visit. However, the wrong sentence was removed and it was revealed a translation error by the PR agency regarding statement from a Daegu government official. The official in the Daegu city stated that the original message was the notification to foreign tourists about the delayed schedule of festival over COVID-19 concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/03/177_285607.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305161517/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/03/177_285607.html |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jamaicans have reported widespread discrimination,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200328/jamaican-feels-ostracised-south-korea-over-covid-19 |title=Jamaican feels ostracised in South Korea over COVID-19 &#124; News |publisher=Jamaica Gleaner |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> and foreigners were excluded from city wide stimulus funds, with the exception of Ansan city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200405000177 |title=Foreign residents shut out of virus relief funds |publisher=Koreaherald.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nOn 24 February, the United States [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)]] upgraded the status of South Korea to level 3 (avoid non-essential travels due to widespread community transmission).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|title=Coronavirus in South Korea \u2013 Warning \u2013 Level 3, Avoid Nonessential Travel \u2013 Travel Health Notices {{!}} Travelers' Health {{!}} CDC|website=wwwnc.cdc.gov|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051122/https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, [[Charles Schwab Corporation]] advised employees who had travelled to China and South Korea to self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-charles-schwab-idUSKCN20M2VS|title=Schwab tells employees to self-quarantine after visiting China, South Korea|date=28 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 February 2020|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023846/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-charles-schwab-idUSKCN20M2VS|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Multiple companies such as [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Google]], [[Toronto-Dominion Bank|TD Bank Group]], [[Bank of Nova Scotia]], [[London Stock Exchange Group]], and [[Cargill|Cargill, Inc.]] deferred all non-essential travels to areas affected by the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-amazon-com-idUSKCN20M2TZ|title=Amazon defers 'non-essential' moves even in U.S. as corporate travel bans spread|date=28 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 February 2020|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228222152/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-amazon-com-idUSKCN20M2TZ|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 8 March, [[United States Forces Korea|US military]] has suspended all travels to and from South Korea for all military personnel and their family over the concern of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-us-army-south-korea-suspends-travel-soldiers|title=US Army suspends travel for soldiers, families to and from South Korea amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Wallace|first=Danielle|date=8 March 2020|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308133810/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-us-army-south-korea-suspends-travel-soldiers|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 10 March, 109 countries or regions restrict entry of visitors from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u97d3 \uc785\uad6d \uc81c\ud55c 109\uacf3\u2026\uc774\ud0c8\ub9ac\uc544 \uc2dc\uc791\ud55c \uad6d\uac00\ubd09\uc1c4, \uc720\ub7fd \ubc88\uc9c0\ub098|date=10 March 2020 |publisher=JoongAng Ilbo|url=https://news.joins.com/article/23726399}}</ref>\n\n=== View of foreign media on COVID-19 in Korea ===\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' has praised the South Korean government's handling of coronavirus outbreak and stated that South Korea is a model for the U.S. response instead of Iran.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paige Winfield Cunningham|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-health-202/2020/03/13/the-health-202-why-south-korea-not-iran-is-a-model-for-u-s-coronavirus-response/5e6a58be88e0fa101a747d62/|title=The Health 202:Why-South Korea not Iran is a model for U.S. coronavirus response|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314074409/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-health-202/2020/03/13/the-health-202-why-south-korea-not-iran-is-a-model-for-u-s-coronavirus-response/5e6a58be88e0fa101a747d62/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' also appreciated South Korea's response as a successful model for democratic countries.<ref>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/south-korea-shows-that-democracies-can-succeed-against-coronavirus/|title=South Korea shows that democracies can succeed against the coronavirus|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=11 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314081252/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/south-korea-shows-that-democracies-can-succeed-against-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Agence France-Presse]] has compared South Korea's handling of coronavirus outbreak with China. The newspaper stated that \"While China locked down cities, Seoul embraced widespread testing and public notice of movements of those infected, raising some privacy concerns\". Also, AFP analyzed that the South Korean government handled the crisis using a model of open information, public participation, and widespread testing.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|title=Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries?|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=12 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316170319/https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, according to the paper, Masahiro Kami, a chairperson of the Tokyo-based Medical Governance Research Institute stated that South Korea is a good model for every country for handling the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|title=Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries?|quote=Japan \u2014 where nearly 600 people have been infected, with 12 deaths \u2014 has not undertaken widespread testing and could learn from South Korea\u2019s response, said Masahiro Kami, head of the Tokyo-based Medical Governance Research Institute.\"Testing is a crucial initial step to control the virus,\" Kami said, adding: \"It\u2019s a good model for every country.\"|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=12 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316170319/https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[WSJ]] analyzed the aggressive Coronavirus Test Program in South Korea. The government contacted the citizens proactively to test the coronavirus in various ways including a home visit, a quick 10 minutes drop off drive-through COVID-19 testing center free of charge. Although South Korea not yet defeated the outbreak, experts credit the emphasis on energetic COVID-19 test program with reducing case numbers and fatalities.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-south-korea-put-into-place-the-worlds-most-aggressive-coronavirus-testing-11584377217 How South Korea Put Into Place the World\u2019s Most Aggressive Coronavirus Test Program]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317074816/https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-south-korea-put-into-place-the-worlds-most-aggressive-coronavirus-testing-11584377217 |date=17 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast \u2014 And Free] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317032153/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free |date=17 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[UPI]] has analyzed that South Korea's model has worked on handling coronavirus outbreak without any further harder restrictions on foreigners.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=However, the South Korean model seems to have worked to curtail a rapid outbreak originally tied to a secretive religious sect while avoiding the heavy-handed lockdown of an authoritarian regime such as China.|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The paper also observed that Health authorities have aggressively promoted hygiene and social distancing.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=Health authorities have aggressively promoted hygiene and social distancing through widespread public information campaigns, while mass disinfections are being conducted regularly in high-traffic locations such as subway and train stations.|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, according to the paper Kim Jong-hwan, an administrator at Seoul Metropolitan Eunpyeong Hospital positively evaluated the government's deal with coronavirus outbreak by stating that \"The government's response has been so well-organized. I'm proud of it.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=\"The government's response has been so well-organized,\" Kim said. \"I'm proud of it.\"|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[BBC News]] concluded that the reason for the high number of confirmed cases of the coronavirus in South Korea is thanks to the relative \"openness\" and \"transparency\" in the Korean society.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Borowiec |first1=Steven |title=How South Korea's Coronavirus Outbreak Got so Quickly out of Control |url=https://time.com/5789596/south-korea-coronavirus-outbreak/ |website=Time |language=en |date=24 February 2020 |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305011745/https://time.com/5789596/south-korea-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As for the rapid spread of the virus, the reason was the religious group [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji Church]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51609840|title=Why did virus infections skyrocket in South Korea?|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020|website=bbc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191755/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51609840|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Blue House]] announced on 28 February the current status of coronavirus tests in three countries: Korea, the United States, and Japan, and analyzed statistically the reasons why there were so many confirmed cases in South Korea: the number of inspections was 26 or 120 times higher than other countries. The cumulative number of inspections was about 53,000 in South Korea, with only 2,000 in Japan and 440 cases examined in the United States. After the tests, the rate of confirmed cases was highest in Japan (9.04%), followed by Korea (3.3%) and the United States (3.15%).<ref name=chosun-numberoftests>{{cite news |trans-title=The number of corona tests in Korea is 26 times that of Japan-this could be the reason for many reasons for the confirmed cases |script-title=ko:\u9751 \"\ud55c\uad6d, \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac80\uc0ac \uc218 \uc77c\ubcf8\uc758 26\ubc30\"\u2026 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ub9ce\uc740 \uc774\uc720 \ud574\uba85? \ucd9c\ucc98 |url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/28/2020022803425.html |work=[[Chosun Ilbo]] |date=8 February 2020 |language=ko-kr |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301033030/https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/28/2020022803425.html |archive-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Bloomberg L.P.]] analyzed the reason for the low death rate in South Korea. South Korea experienced serious difficulties during the [[2015 Middle East respiratory syndrome outbreak in South Korea|outbreak of MERS]] in 2015 due to a lack of test kits. Afterwards, the country approved rapid deployment of COVID-19 test kits, and now they are able to test more than 10,000 people a day. In neighboring Japan, only about 2,700 people in total have been tested for COVID-19 as of 3 March. Officials in [[Seoul]] operate \"drive-thru\" testing stations for quick testing. Diagnostics company Seegene Inc. is also exporting its test kits to other countries including China, Europe and the US.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-04/south-korea-tests-hundreds-of-thousands-to-fight-virus-outbreak Virus Testing Blitz Appears to Keep Korea Death Rate Low] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309094739/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-04/south-korea-tests-hundreds-of-thousands-to-fight-virus-outbreak |date=9 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/seegene-launches-kfda-approved-covid-19-assay-301005858.html Seegene launches KFDA Approved COVID-19 Assay]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219191708/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/seegene-launches-kfda-approved-covid-19-assay-301005858.html |date=19 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] attributed the factors behind the low death rate of South Korea to the rigorous testing and the infected population profile. South Korea's widespread testing leads mild or asymptomatic cases to be identified so the proportion of dying goes down. Moreover, the infected population in the South Korea has a unique profile. Most of the country's infections are linked to the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus]] and most of its members are young women. Statistics show that the virus is most deadly among older generations and men. So the death rate in South Korea is lower than other countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries? |date=11 March 2020 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries |work=AFP |publisher=The Straits Times |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313052634/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[CNN]] reported the innovative drive-through testing for COVID-19 in the northern city of [[Goyang]], which was inspired by the drive-through counters at [[Starbucks]].<ref name=cnn20200302/> [[Reuters]] detailed the new testing facilities in South Korea. Several drive-through coronavirus screening centres were built, including roadside testing facilities. Their purpose is to diagnose patients quickly, while preventing the infection of others in, e.g., a hospital waiting room or a community health center. The entire testing procedure takes several minutes.<ref name=\"businessinsider1\"/>\nWilliam Schaffner, a professor of preventive medicine and infectious diseases at Vanderbilt University School of Medicine, stressed the importance of the broad testing efforts in South Korea. It would provide us with an unclouded picture of the COVID-19 illness.<ref>[https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3065187/coronavirus-south-koreas-aggressive-testing-gives Coronavirus: South Korea\u2019s aggressive testing gives clues to true fatality rate] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310082405/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3065187/coronavirus-south-koreas-aggressive-testing-gives |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\u2019s Chief Health Officer, Brett Sutton has recommended the drive-thru coronavirus testing in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/clinical/drive-thru-coronavirus-testing-now-a-reality-in-so |title=Drive-thru coronavirus testing \u2018needs to be explored\u2019: Victorian health chief |publisher=RACGP |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref> On 10 March, Australia opened the first drive-through testing station in [[Adelaide]].<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-10/australias-first-coronavirus-road-testing-station-opens-adelaide/12041978 First 'drive-thru' coronavirus testing station opens in South Australia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310081432/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-10/australias-first-coronavirus-road-testing-station-opens-adelaide/12041978 |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\n''[[Business Insider]]'' analyzed the difference of coverage of patient testing patients for COVID-19, comparing the USA to South Korea. Per million citizens, South Korea tested 700 times more than the USA.<ref name=fp20200227/> ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' explained South Korea's efforts of setting up several \"drive-thru\" coronavirus screening facilities as contributing to testing thousands of samples a day.<ref>[https://fortune.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-us-test/ Other countries are testing patients for coronavirus by the tens of thousands. Why the U.S. is so far behind] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304213846/https://fortune.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-us-test/ |date=4 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nBy 10 March, [[CNN]] had an interview with South Korea health minister [[Park Neung-hoo]]. Park expressed cautiously his desire that the coronavirus outbreak had 'passed the peak' as per the result regarding the number of new daily infections had declined in recent days.<ref name=\"CNN-12\"/> The South Korean government has the ability operate about 15,000 diagnostic tests per day and has conducted over 190,000 tests by 10 March nationwide. Park also answered the inquiry from CNN about practicable tips for controlling COVID-19. Park believes that dealing with outbreaks by focusing efforts on early testing and global cooperation would be crucial instead of the lockdown option, as the virus could still spread quickly without testing.<ref name=\"CNN-12\"/> S. Korean authorities have arranged the two types of facilities, one for about 10% of coronavirus patients who required hospitalization and another for the patients who were only suffering from mild symptoms.<ref name=\"CNN-12\">CNN NEWS- 10 March 2020:[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html South Korea has 'passed the peak' of the coronavirus outbreak, health minister hopes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310121826/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Coronavirus disease]]s, a group of closely related syndromes\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Korea|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mask.arrangy.com Mask Dashboard, real-time public surgical mask inventory information of nationwide and municipalities in Korea]\n{{commons category-inline}}<br>\n{{commons category-inline|Press releases about the COVID-19 pandemic in foreign languages by Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Press releases about the COVID-19 pandemic by Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in South Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:History of Daegu]]\n[[Category:Christianity-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Christianity and medicine]]\n", "name_user": "CRau080", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eView of foreign media on COVID-19 in Korea", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Korea"}
{"title_page": "Party for Freedom", "text_new": "{{About|the present-day Party for Freedom|the historic party|Freedom Party (Netherlands)}}\n{{short description|Dutch political party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| colorcode = {{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}\n| name = Party for Freedom\n| native_name = Partij voor de Vrijheid\n| logo = [[File:PVV_political_logo.png|225px]]\n| leader1_title = Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Geert Wilders]]\n| leader2_title = [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House Leader]]\n| leader2_name = [[Geert Wilders]]\n| leader3_title = [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate Leader]]\n| leader3_name = [[Marjolein Faber]]\n| leader4_title = [[European Parliament|European Leader]]\n| leader4_name = [[Marcel de Graaff]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and years ago|2006|2|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/>\n| split = [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]]\n| headquarters = [[Binnenhof]], [[The Hague]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pvv.nl/contact.html|title=Contact|publisher=Party for Freedom|accessdate=7 May 2018|language=nl}}</ref>\n| membership = 1 (with parliamentary representatives)<ref name=\"parlementparty\">\"[https://www.parlement.com/id/vhnnmt7m4rqi/partij_voor_de_vrijheid_pvv Partij voor de Vrijheid (PVV)]\" (in Dutch), ''Parlement & Politiek''. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/archief/favorita-en-de-duistere-financiering-van-partijen~a891355/ Favorita en de duistere financiering van partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[de Volkskrant]]'', 2008. Retrieved 20 February 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2010/11/24/ondemocratische-pvv-11973605-a1325361 Ondemocratische PVV]\" (in Dutch), ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 2010. Retrieved 20 February 2017.</ref>\n| ideology = {{nowrap|[[Nationalism|Dutch nationalism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\">{{cite book |last=Pauwels |first=Teun |title=Populism in Western Europe: Comparing Belgium, Germany and The Netherlands |year=2014 |publisher=Routledge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dmUtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=no&pg=PA117#v=onepage&q&f=false |pages=117\u2013118 |isbn=9781317653912}}</ref><ref name=\"europepolitique\">{{cite web |url=https://www.europe-politique.eu/wiki/Partij_voor_de_Vrijheid_(PVV) |title=Partij voor de Vrijheid (PVV) \u2014 Europe Politique |website=www.europe-politique.eu |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><br />[[National liberalism]]<ref>{{cite book |title=The Victorious Parties - Unity in Diversity? |work=The Extreme Right in Europe: Current Trends and Perspectives |first=Patrick |last=Moreau |page=106 |publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht}}</ref><br />[[Right-wing populism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Oudenampsen\">Merijn Oudenampsen (2013). \"[{{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=EUhMAQAAQBAJ |page=191}} Explaining the Swing to the Right: The Dutch Debate on the Rise of Right-Wing Populism]\". In Ruth Wodak, Majid KhosraviNik, Brigitte Mral. ''Right-Wing Populism in Europe: Politics and Discourse''. A&C Black. p. 191.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/netherlands.html |title=Netherlands |website=Parties and Elections in Europe |first=Wolfram |last=Nordsieck |year=2017 |accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref><br />[[Criticism of Islam|Anti-Islam]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Subramanian|first1=Samanth|title=Could the anti-Islam Party for Freedom come out on top in upcoming Netherlands election?|url=http://www.thenational.ae/world/europe/could-the-anti-islam-party-for-freedom-come-out-on-top-in-upcoming-netherlands-election |website=The National |accessdate=16 April 2017|date=9 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite book |first=Wayne C. |last=Thompson |year=2014 |title=Western Europe 2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlgtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=no&pg=PA185#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=185 |isbn=9781475812305}}</ref>}}<br />[[Opposition to immigration|Anti-immigration]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Thompson\"/><br />[[Euroscepticism]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/><ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n| position = [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tqlrRJHwjKoC&pg=PA239&dq=Party-for-Freedom+right-wing&hl=en&ei=NXk-TsL9LYqr-QaD-NWGBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=Party-for-Freedom%20right-wing&f=false|title=After the Nazi racial state: difference and democracy in Germany and Europe|author=Rita C-K Chin|publisher=University of Michigan Press|year=2009|ISBN=|page=239}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-38253122 Are Dutch voters really turning to populist Geert Wilders?]<br /></ref> to<br />[[Far-right politics|far-right]]<ref name=\"europepolitique\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trouw.nl/gs-b6725250|title='PVV is extreem-rechts'|first=Van onze|last=verslaggevers|date=10 December 2008|website=Trouw|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.rug.nl/research/portal/files/20875483/JB07LucardieDEF_1_.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/03/28/the-new-face-of-the-dutch-far-right-fvd-thierry-baudet-netherlands-pvv-geert-wilders/|title=The New Face of the Dutch Far-Right|first=Thijs|last=Kleinpaste|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/03/16/520376715/geert-wilders-dutch-donald-trump-takes-second-place-in-closely-watched-election|title=Geert Wilders, 'Dutch Donald Trump,' Takes Second Place In Closely Watched Election|website=NPR.org|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/mark-rutte-dutch-politics-eu-netherlands-european-union-brussels/|title=Mark Rutte\u2019s leaden touch|first=Tom-Jan|last=Meeus|date=22 October 2018|website=POLITICO|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/428866-far-right-former-dutch-lawmaker-who-said-the-quran-is-poison|title=Far-right former Dutch lawmaker who said the Quran is \u2018poison\u2019 converts to Islam|first=Owen|last=Daugherty|date=6 February 2019|website=TheHill|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| international = \n| european = \n| europarl = [[Identity and Democracy]]\n| colours = {{Color box|#AE1C28|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#21468B|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], [[white]], [[blue]]<br />([[Flag of the Netherlands|Dutch tricolour]])\n| seats1_title = [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|20|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|5|75|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[States-Provincial]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|41|570|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|1|29|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[King's Commissioner]]s\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|0|12|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.pvv.nl/}}\n| country = Netherlands\n}}\nThe '''Party for Freedom''' ({{lang-nl|Partij voor de Vrijheid}}, '''PVV''') is a [[Nationalism|nationalist]],<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/> [[Right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]<ref name=\"Pauwels\"/> [[list of political parties in the Netherlands|political party]] in the [[Netherlands]].\n\nFounded in 2006 as the successor to [[Geert Wilders]]' one-man faction in the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]], it won nine seats in the [[2006 Dutch general election|2006 general election]] making it the fifth-largest party in parliament. In the [[2010 Dutch general election|2010 general election]] it won 24 seats, making it the third-largest party. At that time the PVV agreed to support the [[minority government]] led by [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands|Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]] without having PVV ministers in the [[First Rutte cabinet|cabinet]]. However, the PVV withdrew its support in April 2012 due to differences over budget cuts at the Catshuis.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423035742/http://www.euronews.com/newswires/1490908-dutch-elections-loom-as-budget-talks-collapse/|archivedate=23 April 2012|title=Dutch elections loom as budget talks collapse|url=http://www.euronews.com/newswires/1490908-dutch-elections-loom-as-budget-talks-collapse/|publisher=[[Euronews]]|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref> In the following [[2012 Dutch general election]] it won 15 seats, having lost 9 seats in the elections, still being the third-largest party. Following the elections, the party returned to the opposition and in the 2017 election, the Party for Freedom won 20 seats, making it the second-largest party in [[Dutch Parliament|Parliament]].\n\nIt came third in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the Netherlands|2014 European Parliament election]], winning four out of 26 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/652748-cda-5-zetels-d66-en-pvv-4.html|title=Meeste stemmen D66, CDA grootst|work=nos.nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=25 May 2014 |title=CDA met vijf zetels grootste partij |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/special/cda-met-vijf-zetels-grootste-partij |website=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=26 May 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nThe PVV calls for items like [[administrative detention]] and a strong [[Cultural assimilation|assimilationist]] stance on the [[Integration law for immigrants to the Netherlands|integration]] of immigrants into Dutch society, differing from the established [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]] parties in the Netherlands (like the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]], VVD). The PVV has also proposed banning the [[Quran]] and shutting down all [[mosque]]s in the Netherlands.<ref name=politico/><ref name=voa/> In addition, the party is consistently [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Jos\u00e9 M. |last=Magone |title=Comparative European Politics: An Introduction |publisher=Routledge |year=2011 |page=17 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=g73UtvxJsFcC}}}}</ref><ref>{{citation |first1=Daniele |last1=Albertazzi |first2=Duncan |last2=McDonnell |title=Twenty-first century populism: The spectre of Western European democracy |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |year=2008 |page=164 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=tCGIAAAAMAAJ}}}}</ref> and since early July 2012, according to the platform it presented prior to elections in September, it strongly advocates withdrawal from the [[European Union|EU]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/artikel/390859-pvv-nederland-moet-uit-eu.html |title=PVV: Nederland moet uit EU. (The Netherlands should get out of the EU) |publisher=Nos.nl |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nParty for Freedom is an association with Geert Wilders as its sole member; thus the party is ineligible for Dutch government funding, and relies on donations.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bolopion |first=Philippe |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/geert-wilders-far-right-party-suffers-donation-downturn/ |title=Geert Wilders' far-right party suffers donation downturn |publisher=Politico.eu |date=8 March 2017|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n=== 2004\u20132005 ===\nThe party's history began with Geert Wilders' departure from the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]] in September 2004. Wilders could not accept the VVD's positive stance towards [[Accession of Turkey to the European Union|Turkey's possible accession to the European Union]], and left the party disgruntled.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAlthough the VVD expected Wilders to return his parliamentary seat to the party, he refused, and continued to sit in parliament as a one-man party, ''Groep Wilders'' (Wilders Group).{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn June 2005, Wilders was one of the leaders in the campaign against the [[Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe|European Constitution]], which was rejected by Dutch voters by 62%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch say 'No' to EU constitution|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4601439.stm| work= BBC News |date=2 June 2005|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== 2006\u20132010 ===\n[[File:Slotdebat verkiezingen (final debate elections) 2006.jpg|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] (left) with other politicians at the final television debate before the [[2006 Dutch general election]]]]\n\nOn 22 February 2006, the Party for Freedom was registered with the Electoral Council.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/>\n\n[[Bart Jan Spruyt]], director of the [[conservatism|conservative]] [[Edmund Burke Foundation]], joined Wilders in January 2006 in order to formulate a party programme and to train its prospective representatives for the forthcoming national election (then still scheduled for 2007).<ref>{{cite news|title=Spruyt sluit zich aan bij Geert Wilders|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/1062338/Nieuws/Politiek/Spruyt-sluit-zich-aan-bij-Geert-Wilders.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=4 January 2006|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\nSpruyt left the party in the summer of 2006 after it proved unable to build broad conservative backing, and people like [[Joost Eerdmans]] and [[Marco Pastors]] proved unwilling to join.<ref>{{cite news|title=Historische kans voorbij |language=Dutch |url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1271047 |newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]] |date=17 August 2006 |first=Addy |last=de Jong |accessdate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526150442/http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1271047 |archivedate=26 May 2008 }}</ref> After the [[2006 Dutch general election|2006 elections]], Spruyt said he was not surprised that the Party for Freedom had gained seats but maintained that, if the Party for Freedom had sought cooperation with Eerdmans and Pastors, it would have won more, even enough to bring about a [[Christian Democratic Appeal|CDA]]-[[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]] [[2006 Dutch general election#Possible coalitions|majority]] government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spruyt: Negeren van Wilders onverstandig|language=Dutch|url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1282578/Spruyt%3A+Negeren+van+Wilders+onverstandig.html|newspaper=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|date=23 November 2006|first=Jacob|last=Hoekman|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\nLater, Spruyt commented that the PVV had a 'natural tendency' toward fascism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Weimar in aanbouw (deel 1)|language=Dutch|url=http://bartjanspruyt.blogspot.com/2007/01/weimar-in-aanbouw-deel-1.html|publisher=The weblog of Bart J. Spruyt|first=Bart|last=Spruyt|date=1 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> He later qualified the statement, though he didn't withdraw it. Former PVV candidate [[Lucas Hartong]] called Spruyt's claims 'a cheap insinuation'.<ref>{{cite news|title=Het is me wat!| url=http://www.hetvrijevolk.com/?pagina=2295&titel=Het_is_me_wat|first=Lucas|last=Hartong|date=2 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Het Vrije Volk]]}}</ref>\n\nIn an ''[[HP/De Tijd]]'' profile dated December 2006, the party was described as a [[cult]], with an extremely distrustful Wilders only accepting fellow candidates completely loyal to him, and compared the PVV to the [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|Socialist Party]] led by [[Jan Marijnissen]] but without reaching that degree of organisational perfection.<ref name=HP2006>{{Cite journal|title=Haagse Sekte| language=Dutch| author=van der Horst, Alain |author2=Munk, Kirsten |author3=Niemoller, Joost|publisher=[[HP/De Tijd]]|date=1 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2007, the PVV announced it would not field candidates at the forthcoming Provincial elections. This meant it would be unrepresented in the [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Partij Wilders doet niet mee aan Statenverkiezingen|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article386300.ece/Partij_Wilders_doet_niet_mee_aan_Statenverkiezingen|publisher=[[Volkskrant]]|date=10 January 2007|language=Dutch|accessdate=4 April 2009|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau|ANP]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2007, ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' reported that a PVV intern had solicited for signatures on the website forums ''Dutch Disease Report'' and ''Polinco'', the latter a forum described as far-right by various organisations, among them the Dutch Complaints Bureau for Discrimination on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meldpunt.nl/dl/mdi-jaarverslag-2003.pdf|title=Meldpunt Discriminatie Internet|language=Dutch|publisher=Magenta Foundation|date=1 March 2004|accessdate=4 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20040808184259/http://www.meldpunt.nl/dl/mdi-jaarverslag-2003.pdf|archivedate=8 August 2004}}</ref> Any party participating in this election was required to collect at least 30 signatures from supporters in each of the 19 electoral districts; of the 1500 signatures the PVV received, the [[Antifaschistische Aktion|Dutch Antifascist]] group identified 34 known far-right supporters. In a response, Wilders said he regretted that far-right sympathisers had provided signatures, denied any personal responsibility for them and reasserted his dislike of far-right parties like [[National Front (France)|National Front]] of France and [[Vlaams Belang|Flemish Interest]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[NRC Handelsblad]]| language=Dutch| date=13 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|title=PVV riep steun van extreem-rechts in| url= http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article598698.ece/PVV_riep_steun_van_extreem-rechts_in| first=Joep| last=Dohmen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Trouw]]|language=Dutch|date=13 January 2007| title=Wilders ontkent oproep tot steun extreem rechts|url=http://www.trouw.nl/laatstenieuws/laatstenieuws/article598962.ece/Wilders_ontkent_oproep_tot_steun_extreem_rechts}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]]| date=15 January 2007|title=Extreem-rechtse steun verdriet Wilders|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article387621.ece/Extreem-rechtse_steun_verdriet_Wilders|accessdate=5 April 2009| language= Dutch}}</ref>\nNoted writer and columnist [[Leon de Winter]] later declared the affair to be the result of a campaign of [[demonization|demonisation]] against Geert Wilders led by ''NRC Handelsblad'' and ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' newspapers, as well as the broadcaster [[Omroepvereniging VARA|VARA]].<ref>{{Cite news| url= http://www.elsevier.nl/opinie/weblog/asp/artnr/134700/weblogid/4/index.html|title=De demonisering van Geert Wilders|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|date=15 January 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009| first=Leon| last=de Winter}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wilders.jpg|thumb|left|[[Geert Wilders]] in 2007]]\n\nFormer [[trade union]] leader and prominent [[Christian Democratic Appeal|Christian Democrat]] Doekle Terpstra proposed an initiative against Geert Wilders and the PVV on 30 November 2007, in the newspaper ''[[Trouw]]''.<ref>{{cite news|first=Doekle|last=Terpstra|title=\u2019Nee\u2019 tegen kwade boodschap Wilders| language=Dutch| url=http://www.trouw.nl/opinie/podium/article1518091.ece|newspaper=[[Trouw]]|date=30 November 2007| accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> Terpstra sees Wilders as promoting intolerance, and discrimination against Muslims. He is supported in his cause by the large Dutch trade unions and refugee organisations. Politicians and the public are divided on Terpstra's initiative.<ref name=\"radio\">{{cite news|title=Dutch show mixed reactions to anti-Muslim party |url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/071204-freedom-party-mc |publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] |date=4 December 2007 |accessdate=4 April 2009 |first=Hans |last=Andringa |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018231807/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/071204-freedom-party-mc |archivedate=18 October 2008 }}</ref> The newspaper ''[[De Pers]]'' reported the next day that much of Terpstra's claimed support did not materialise.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tekort aan redelijke positivo's|url=http://www.depers.nl/binnenland/135616/Tekort-aan-redelijke-positivos.html|language=Dutch|publisher=[[De Pers]]|date=5 December 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|first=Kustaw|last=Bessems}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the Friends of the Party of Freedom commissioned a producer, who acted under the name of \"Scarlet Pimpernel Productions\", a pseudonym adopted out of fear of reprisal,<ref name=\"scarlet\">{{cite news|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/article524165.ece/Rapper_wil_25.000_euro_van_Wilders|title=Rapper wil 25.000 euro van Wilders|publisher=[[de Volkskrant]]|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=8 April 2008|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau]]|language=Dutch}}</ref> to produce ''[[Fitna (film)|Fitna]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0650\u062a\u0652\u0646\u064e\u0629\u064c}}), a [[short film]] by Geert Wilders. Approximately 17 minutes in length, it shows selected excerpts from [[Surah|Suras]] of the [[Quran|Qur'an]], interspersed with media clips and newspaper cuttings showing or describing acts of violence or hatred by Muslims. The film attempts to demonstrate that the Qur'an motivates its followers to hate all who violate Islamic teachings. Consequently, the film argues that Islam encourages acts of terrorism, [[antisemitism]], [[violence against women]] and homosexuals, and Islamic [[universalism]]. A large part of the film deals with [[Islam in the Netherlands|the influence of Islam on the Netherlands]]. The film's title, the Arabic word \"[[fitna (word)|fitna]]\", means  either \"disagreement and division among people\" or a \"test of faith in times of trial\".<ref name=\"hatred\">{{cite news|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=137624|title=Hold your breath: \u2018Fitna' spreading seeds of hatred|date=29 March 2008|accessdate=1 April 2008|work=[[Today's Zaman]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402234115/http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=137624|archivedate=2 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Wilders described the film as \"a call to shake off the creeping tyranny of [[Islamization|Islamisation]]\".<ref name=\"foxiranwarn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,324406,00.html|title=Iran Warns Netherlands Not to Air Controversial 'Anti-Muslim' Film|publisher=Fox News|first=Michael|last=Park|date=21 January 2008|accessdate=8 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nPolling by [[Maurice de Hond]] published in March 2009 indicated that the PVV was the most popular parliamentary party. The polls predicted that the party would take 21 per cent of the national vote, giving it 32 out of 150 seats in the Dutch parliament. If the polling results were to be replicated at a genuine election, Wilders would be a major power broker and could become Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/news/zijlijn/6235703/Geert-Wilders-Freedom-Party-rises-to-32-seats |title=Geert Wilders' Freedom Party rises to 32 seats |date=29 March 2009 |accessdate=29 March 2009 |publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402002907/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/news/zijlijn/6235703/Geert-Wilders-Freedom-Party-rises-to-32-seats |archivedate=2 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/netherlands/4933687/Geert-Wilders-leads-Dutch-polls.html|title=Geert Wilders leads Dutch polls |first=Bruno|last=Waterfield|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 April 2009|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nisnews.nl/public/030309_1.htm|title=Wilders Now a Celebrity in US and Prime Minister in Poll|publisher=NIS News Bulletin|date=3 March 2009|accessdate=4 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722014951/http://www.nisnews.nl/public/030309_1.htm|archivedate=22 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, De Hond's results were not uncontroversial, as they were based on a panel of people who have signed up for the election poll on the Internet and thus were not a [[random sample]]. According to Joop van Holsteyn, professor of election research, therefore, De Hond's polls were not [[Face validity|representative]] of the population.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrc.nl/opinie/article2168483.ece/De_peiling_van_Maurice_de_Hond_deugt_niet|title=De peiling van Maurice de Hond deugt niet; De waarde van een peiling staat of valt met een representatieve steekproef|newspaper=NRC Handelsblad|author=Joop van Holsteyn}}</ref> Other Dutch polls (Politieke Barometer and TNS NIPO) have shown contrasting results, with the PVV often getting less support, though still remaining very popular.\n\nOn 15 May 2009, the PVV asked Balkenende to support the foundation of a [[Greater Netherlands]] actively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv.nl/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1975&Itemid=1|title=Partij Voor de Vrijheid|work=pvv.nl}}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=January 2012}}\n\nBy February 2010, the PVV had once more become the most popular party, according to a poll by Maurice de Hond which said it would win 27\u201332 parliameary seats in the next election, up two from the previous poll in early January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angus-reid.com/polls/view/35028/dutch_party_for_freedom_recovers_top_rank/ |title=Dutch Party for Freedom Recovers Top Rank |publisher=Angus-reid.com |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://digitalehofstad.wordpress.com/2010/01/31/2e-kamerverkiezingen-2010-%E2%80%93-peilingen-31-01-2010-maurice-de-hond-pvv-de-grootste/ |title=2e Kamerverkiezingen 2010 \u2013 Peilingen 31.01.2010 Maurice de Hond PVV de Grootste |publisher=Digitalehofstad.wordpress.com |date=31 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March 2010, elections for the local councils were held in the municipalities of the Netherlands. The PVV only contested these in [[The Hague]] and [[Almere]], because of a shortage of good candidates. MP Raymond de Roon headed the campaign in his home town of Almere. Fellow MP Sietse Fritsma was appointed head of the local election campaign in The Hague. Both men would continue to serve as MPs as well as local councillors after their election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2009/12/pvv_picks_second_mp_for_local.php |title=PVV picks second MP for local elections |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=21 December 2009 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The PVV made big gains, suggesting that the party and Wilders might dominate the political scene in the run-up to the parliamentary elections scheduled on 9 June 2010. The PVV won in Almere and came second to the Labour Party in The Hague. In Almere, the PVV won 21 percent of the vote to Labour's 18 percent, preliminary results showed. In The Hague, the PVV had 8 seats \u2013 second to Labour with 10 seats. The local elections were the first test of public opinion since the collapse of the 4th Balkenende cabinet in February 2010. The municipal elections were overshadowed by the fall of the cabinet and the forthcoming parliamentary elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrc.nl/international/Features/article2497139.ece/Local_elections_overshadowed_by_national_politics |title=Local elections overshadowed by national politics |publisher=Nrc.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2010, Wilders announced he would take a seat on The Hague city council, after it became clear that he had won 13,000 preference votes. Earlier he had said he would not do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/03/wilders_to_take_council_seat_i.php |title=Wilders to take council seat in the Hague |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/dutch-anti-Islam-MP-Wilders-wins-council-seat |title=Anti-Islam MP Geert Wilders has announced he will take up a seat on the local council of the city of The Hague |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=8 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> One week after these local elections, the PVV called for an inquiry into the elections in The Hague, since a YouTube clip allegedly showed irregularities, including more than one person entering polling booths at the same time and a voter not putting the ballot paper into the box. These calls were rejected. The Hague council said the municipal elections had gone well and that any complaint should anyway have been lodged immediately after the results were announced. In [[Rotterdam]], a full recount was held after a protest by [[Livable Rotterdam|Leefbaar Rotterdam]], a local party with a programme broadly similar to that of the PVV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/calls-local-poll-recount-hague |title=Calls for local poll recount in The Hague |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/rotterdam-investigate-proxy-voting |title=Rotterdam to investigate proxy voting |publisher=Rnw.nl |date=10 March 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March 2010, the PVV gave up trying to form a governing coalition in Almere. In a press release, the party said most of the other parties had refused to give ground to PVV demands on what it describes as ''\"essential issues\"''. These include what the party calls \u2018city commandos\u2019: street patrols to keep order in the face of inadequate proper law enforcement. Other obstacles were the PVV's demands for reduced taxes for Almere residents and its fight against what the party sees as ''\"the increasing influence of Islam in Dutch society\"''. The PVV complained that it was forced to stay in the opposition through the manoeuvring of the political elite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/news/dutch-rss-news/wilders-pvv-party-kept-in-almere-opposition_31769.html |title=Wilders' PVV party 'kept in Almere opposition' |publisher=Expatica.com |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010\u20132012 ===\n[[File:2010-presentatie-regeerakkoord2.jpg|thumb|[[Maxime Verhagen]] (left) and [[Mark Rutte]] (center) are presenting the coalition agreement with support of the PVV of [[Geert Wilders]] (right) in 2010]]\n[[File:Pvv.png|thumb|Distribution of the people that voted for the Party for Freedom in 2010]]\n\nIn the parliamentary elections of 9 June 2010, the PVV went from 9 to 24 seats (of 150), winning over 15% of the votes, making the PVV the third largest party in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nBy July 2010, the PVV again became the biggest party in the polls after the [[2010 Dutch general election|parliamentary elections]], following difficulties in forming a new coalition and the PVV technically being excluded from the coalition talks because the CDA showed reluctance to cooperate with the PVV. According to the polls, the PVV would get 35 seats in a new election, which is a record high number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nu.nl/politiek/2295043/pvv-historisch-hoog-in-peiling.html |title=PVV historisch hoog in peiling |publisher=www.nu.nl |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, during the difficult cabinet formation following the elections, the PVV emerged as a prominent player in a proposal for a new minority government in the Netherlands. While the party would not gain a ministerial appointment, the PVV would tolerate a centre-right minority government coalition: a proposed deal that would make the party one of the most influential forces. Led by [[Ivo Opstelten]], a former mayor of Rotterdam who was appointed mediator for the next stage of negotiations, the forming of a government of VVD and [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] (CDA) with support of the PVV was negotiated; the resulting coalition agreement \"included elements it pushed for, such as a [[Islamic dress in Europe#Netherlands|burqa ban]],\" though the ban was never put in place.<ref>{{cite news| title= Dutch government collapses after far right pulls plug| url= http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/23/world/europe/netherlands-politics/ |date= 23 April 2012| publisher= CNN| quote= The Party for Freedom did not get control of any government ministries, but the coalition agreement included elements it pushed for, such as a burqa ban. No ban has been put in place.| accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref>  The VVD and CDA would have to rely on the PVV to get important legislation through. With this deal the Netherlands would follow the \"Danish model\", since in Denmark the anti-immigration [[Danish People's Party]] also stayed out of government but supported a minority center-right [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal]]-[[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative]] government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Castle |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/06/world/europe/06dutch.html |title=Outspoken Dutch Politician Makes Inroads |location=Netherlands |newspaper= The New York Times |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref> The very fact of the participation of the PVV in these coalition negotiations has caused fierce discussions in political circles{{which|date=December 2017}} and was considered{{by whom|date=December 2017}} very unlikely until recently.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAfter the elections, CDA parliamentary fraction president Maxime Verhagen first had stated that as a matter of principle he refused to negotiate with VVD and PVV about a centre-right government, saying that the PVV represented views that could not be reconciled with Dutch law. These objections on principle disappeared in five weeks and Verhagen turned out to be willing to negotiate over a cabinet whose fate would (also) lie in the hands of Wilders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trouw.nl/opinie/commentaar/article3153262.ece/Vooral_het_CDA_heeft_niets_te_zoeken_in_zo_rsquo_n__rsquo_bijzonder_rsquo__kabinet_.html |title=Vooral het CDA heeft niets te zoeken in zo\u2019n \u2019bijzonder\u2019 kabinet |publisher=Trouw.nl |language=Dutch| accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2012, [[Hero Brinkman]] quit the party, citing a lack of democratic structure within the PVV among other things; qualifying this with a statement of continued support for the minority [[First Rutte cabinet|Rutte cabinet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hero Brinkman quits the PVV, opposition call for new elections| url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/03/hero_brinkman_quits_the_pvv_op.php| publisher=DutchNews.nl|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> Two days later, three members of the [[States of North Holland]] representing the PVV followed his example.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://article.wn.com/view/WNAT0cc025902c4813c68046c95b3a128b8b/| title= Drie Statenleden PVV Noord-Holland mee met Brinkman| language=Dutch|accessdate=8 April 2012| publisher= World News Network | work= wn.com}}</ref> In July 2012, [[Marcial Hernandez]] and [[Wim Kortenoeven]] quit the PVV, both citing what they considered to be Wilders' autocratic leadership of the party.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chesal|first=Robert|title=Wilders gives Dutch politics a roller-coaster ride|url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/wilders-gives-dutch-politics-a-roller-coaster-ride|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]]|accessdate=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012\u20132017 ===\n[[File:Congresso federale straordinario - Torino, 15 dicembre 2013 29.JPG|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] speaking at a [[Lega Nord]] event in 2013]]\n\nIn the [[2012 Dutch general election|parliamentary elections of 12 September 2012]], the PVV went from 24 to 15 seats (of 150), winning 10% of the vote.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn October 2013, the party expelled [[Louis Bontes]], but he kept his seat in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} In March 2014, [[Roland van Vliet]] and [[Joram van Klaveren]] left the party and also kept their seats in parliament.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nIn the [[2014 European Parliament election in the Netherlands|European Parliament election]] on 22 May 2014, the party kept its four seats in the [[European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |date=26 May 2014 |title=Dit zijn de Nederlandse leden van het Europees parlement |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/special/dit-zijn-de-nederlandse-leden-van-het-europees-parlement |website=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=26 May 2014 |language=Dutch }}</ref> MEP [[Hans Jansen]] died on 5 May 2015 and was replaced by [[Auke Zijlstra]] on 1 September 2015.<ref>\"[https://www.parlement.com/id/vjvuh0bgrcmd/nieuws/auke_zijlstra_pvv_bevestigt_toetreding Auke Zijlstra (PVV) bevestigt toetreding tot Europees Parlement]\" (in Dutch), ''Parlement & Politiek'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2015, the Party for Freedom and other right-wing nationalist parties in the European Parliament formed the [[Political groups of the European Parliament|political group]] [[Europe of Nations and Freedom]].<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33147247 France's Le Pen announces far-right bloc of anti-EU MEPs]\", ''[[BBC News]]'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref><ref name=\"foundationenf\">Eric Maurice, \"[https://euobserver.com/political/129140 Le Pen becomes group leader in EU parliament]\", ''[[EUobserver]]'', 2015. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref> [[Marcel de Graaff]] of the PVV and [[Marine Le Pen]] of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] became the first co-presidents of this group.<ref name=\"foundationenf\"/>\n\n=== 2017\u2013present ===\n[[File:Geert Wilders tijdens een politieke campagne in Spijkenisse.jpg|thumb|[[Geert Wilders]] during the campaign of the [[2017 Dutch general election|2017 general election]]]]\n\nFor the [[2017 Dutch general election]], the Party for Freedom had an [[election platform]] of a single page.<ref>\"[http://pubnpp.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/FILES/root/verkiezingsprogramma/TK/pvv2017con/PVV2017-2021con.pdf Concept-verkiezingsprogramma PVV 2017-2021]\" (in Dutch), [[University of Groningen]]. Retrieved 19 March 2017.</ref> Before the election, all major parties said they would not form a government coalition with the PVV.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2017/01/vvd-leader-mark-rutte-says-zero-chance-of-coalition-with-geert-wilders|title=VVD leader Mark Rutte says 'zero' chance of coalition with Geert Wilders|publisher=DutchNews.nl|date=16 January 2017}}</ref> A typical House of Representatives has a large number of parties represented, since it takes as little as 0.67 percent of the vote to get a seat.  With such a fragmented vote, the PVV would have needed the support of other parties in order to make Wilders prime minister, even if it won the most seats in the House of Representatives. Wilders hinted that a \"revolution\" would occur if the PVV won the most seats and was still locked out of power.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/dutch-election-far-right-could-win-not-rule-country-known-liberal/|title=Dutch election: How the far Right could win but not rule in a country known for its liberal values|author1=Ashley Kirk|author2=Patrick Scott|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 20 seats (of 150) according to the preliminary results, which is 5 seats more than in the previous [[2012 Dutch general election|election in 2012]] and made it the second-largest party in Parliament.<ref>\"[http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/27813134/__VVD_de_grootste__.html VVD de grootste, zwaar verlies PvdA]\" (in Dutch), ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', 2017. Retrieved 17 March 2017.</ref>\n\nThe party performed poorly in the [[2019 Dutch provincial elections]], losing 26 seats, with the [[Forum for Democracy]] taking many of its voters.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Politico]]|date=25 March 2019|title=5 things to know about Dutch far right\u2019s new figurehead|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/thierry-baudet-forum-for-democracy-netherlands-5-things-to-know-about-dutch-far-rights-new-figurehead/}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology==\n{{Updatesection|date=October 2016}}\nThe Party for Freedom combines conservative, liberal, right and left standpoints in a populistic programme.<ref name=\"www.parlement.com\">[http://www.parlement.com/9291000/modulesf/g45eq8f7 Partijen in de Eerste en Tweede Kamer - PVV], Parlement.com.</ref> On certain themes like healthcare, social services and elderly care the PVV can be seen as left and social, though selective.<ref>[https://nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/03/12/de-pvv-is-best-sociaal-maar-wel-selectief-7328509-a1549996 De PVV is best sociaal, maar wel selectief], ''NRC Handelsblad'', 12 maart 2017 (ism. Parlementair Documentatiecentrum)</ref> Regarding immigration and culture the party is nationalistic. It believes that the [[Judeo-Christian]] and [[humanism|humanist]] traditions should be taken as the dominant culture in the Netherlands, and that immigrants should adapt accordingly. The party wants a halt to immigration especially from non-Western countries. It is hostile towards the EU, is against future [[Enlargement of the European Union|EU enlargement]] to Muslim-majority countries like Turkey and opposes a dominant presence of Islam in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv-europa.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410003337/http://pvv-europa.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 April 2009|title=Standpunten|language=Dutch|work=Voor Nederland in Europa|publisher=Party for Freedom|date=1 April 2009|accessdate=7 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More specifically, the party has called for a banning the [[Quran]], and shutting down all mosques in the Netherlands.<ref name=politico>{{cite news|title=Dutch party wants to outlaw mosques, Islamic schools, Koran|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/far-right-dutch-politician-backs-mosques-koran-ban-islamic-schools/|publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref name=voa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/europe/dutch-far-right-leader-seeks-ban-quran-mosques|title=Dutch Far-right Leader Seeks Ban on Quran, Mosques|website=Voice of America|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/netherlands-pvv-leader-geert-wilders-koran-islam-mosque-ban-holland-dutch-pm-favourite-a7214356.html|title=The Netherlands' most popular party wants to ban all mosques|date=28 August 2016|website=The Independent|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> The party is also opposed to [[dual citizenship]] (see below).\n\nThe Parliamentary Documentation Center (Parlementair Documentatie Centrum) of the [[Leiden University]] characterises the PVV as \"[[populism|populist]], with both [[conservatism|conservative]], [[liberalism|liberal]], [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] and [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] positions\".<ref name=\"parlement.com\">[http://www.parlement.com/9291000/modulesf/g45eq8f7 Partijen in de Eerste en Tweede Kamer - PVV], Parlement.com</ref>\n\n[[File:Pol-landschap-2012.png|thumb|On [[Andr\u00e9 Krouwel]]'s map of the Dutch political spectrum in 2012, the Party for Freedom is [[Conservatism|conservative]] on the socio-cultural axis, and [[Centrism|centrist]] on the socio-economic axis.]]\nIn December 2008, the eighth study \"Monitor Racism and Extremism\",<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.annefrank.org/upload/Downloads/Monitor2008-8.pdf |first1=Jaap |last1=Van Donselaar |first2=Peter R. |last2=Rodrigues |title=Monitor Racisme & Extremisme |publisher=Pallas Publications |year=2008 |language=Dutch}}</ref> conducted by the [[Anne Frank Foundation]] and the [[Leiden University]], has found that the Party for Freedom can be considered [[Far-right politics|extreme right-wing]], although \"with ifs and buts\". Economically they are viewed as a left-wing party. Peter Rodrigues and Jaap van Donselaar, who have academically guided the study, explain this classification with the [[Islamophobia]], [[nationalism]], and \"sharp aversion to the strange\", subsumed as [[racism]], which they have observed within the party.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nieuws.leidenuniv.nl/nieuwsarchief/monitor-racisme-en-extremisme.html |title=Monitor Racisme en Extremisme |publisher=University of Leiden |date=10 December 2008 |language=Dutch |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1880292/pvv-volgens-onderzoekers-extreemrechts.html |title=PVV volgens onderzoekers extreemrechts |publisher=NU.nl |date=10 December 2008|language=Dutch |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, the report ''Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland''<ref>{{Citation |last=Moors |first=Hans|title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009 |publisher=IVA beleidsonderzoek en advies |year=2009 |language=Dutch |url=http://www.rijksoverheid.nl/bestanden/documenten-en-publicaties/kamerstukken/2010/01/27/polarisatie-en-radicalisering-in-nederland-een-verkenning-van-de-stand-van-zaken-in-2009/verkenningpr-definitieveversie16-12.pdf|display-authors=etal}}</ref> (transl. \"Polarisation and radicalisation in the Netherlands\") by political researchers Moors, Lenke Balogh, Van Donselaar and De Graaff from the [[Tilburg University]] research group IVA<ref name=\"IVA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lokaalcentraal.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Polarisering-radicalisering-in-NL.pdf |first1=Hans |last1=Moors |first2=Lenke |last2=Balogh |first3=Jaap |last3=van Donselaar |first4=Bob |last4=de Graaff |title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland: Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009 |publisher=IVA |year=2009 |accessdate=6 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316195636/http://www.lokaalcentraal.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Polarisering-radicalisering-in-NL.pdf |archivedate=16 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> stated that the PVV was not an extreme right-wing party, but contained some radical right-wing elements. The study claims that the PVV holds [[Xenophobia|xenophobic]] ideas, but not antisemitic ideas \u2013 the PVV describes its culture as [[Judeo-Christian|Jewish-Christian]] humanistic.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Hans Moors|author2=Lenke Balogh|author3=Jaap van Donselaar|author4=Bob de Graaff|title=Polarisatie en radicalising in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009|year=2009|location=Tilburg|url=http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|format=PDF|language=Dutch|page=15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154546/http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"The PVV statements on [[Islamization|Islamisation]] and non-Western immigrants appear to be discriminatory and the party organisation is authoritarian rather than democratic\", said the researchers, who were looking into polarisation and radicalism across the Netherlands. They described the PVV as the \"new radical right\", a party with a national democratic ideology but without extreme right-wing roots. In particular, the report stated that the party's pro-Israel stance showed that it was not [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]]. It tends however towards a national democratic ideology. Wilders called the report \"scandalous\"\u2014in particular the link between defending the national interest and the radical right.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAn alleged earlier version of the report, leaked to the Dutch daily newspaper ''[[de Volkskrant]]'' in November 2009, said that Wilders' party is an extreme right-wing grouping and a threat to social cohesion and democracy. The paper claimed at the time the researchers were under pressure to water down the conclusions because of their political sensitivity.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} The Dutch [[Ministry of the Interior and Kingdom Relations|Minister of the Interior and Kingdom Relations]] [[Guusje ter Horst]], (2007\u20132010), [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour (PvdA)]], who commissioned the research, denied exerting any interference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2010/01/wilders_party_is_new_radical_r.php |title=Wilders' party is 'new radical right' |publisher=Dutchnews.nl |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/putting-geert-wilders-political-map |title=Putting Geert Wilders on the political map |publisher=Rnw.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529054622/http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/putting-geert-wilders-political-map |archivedate=29 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In response, Wilders accused her of \"playing a dirty game\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extra.volkskrant.nl/opinie/artikel/show/id/5059/WC-eend_adviseert_Guusje_ter_Horst |title=WC-eend adviseert Guusje ter Horst |publisher=Extra.volkskrant.nl |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202133613/http://extra.volkskrant.nl/opinie/artikel/show/id/5059/WC-eend_adviseert_Guusje_ter_Horst |archivedate=2 February 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/257065/Wilders-Minister-Ter-Horst-speelt-vuil-spelletje.htm |title=Wilders: Minister Ter Horst speelt vuil spelletje |publisher=Elsevier.nl |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152439/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/257065/Wilders-Minister-Ter-Horst-speelt-vuil-spelletje.htm |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSome commentators and international scholarly publications have argued that the party is far-right; for example, the ex-prime minister [[Dries van Agt|Van Agt]] regards the party as ultra-right-wing, and [[Bert de Vries]] (CDA) draws comparisons with the small [[Centre Party (Netherlands)|Centre Party]].<ref>{{Citation|author1=Hans Moors|author2=Lenke Balogh|author3=Jaap van Donselaar|author4=Bob de Graaff|title=Polarisatie en radicalisering in Nederland. Een verkenning van de stand van zaken in 2009|year=2009|location=Tilburg|url=http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|format=PDF|language=Dutch|page=96|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154546/http://www.iva.nl/uploads/documents/166.pdf|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The political scientist Lucardie, on the other hand, considers it necessary to reserve the 'far-right' qualification for [[Nazism|national socialists]] and fascists, though PVV is itself widely accused of fascism.<ref>A. Lucardie, \u2018Rechtsextremisme, populisme of democratisch patriotisme? Opmerkingen over de politieke plaatsbepaling van de Partij voor de Vrijheid en Trots op Nederland\u2019, in: G. Voerman (ed.), Jaarboek 2007, Groningen z.j.</ref> International media outlets, similarly, have followed this classification.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=uWX_7eIGEHkC |page=142 }} |title=The governance of Britain: review of voting systems, the experience of new voting systems in the United Kingdom since 1997|author=Ministry of Justice|publisher=The Stationery Office|year=2008|ISBN=0-10-173042-X|page=142}}<br />{{cite book|author=David Marquand|title=The End of the West: The Once and Future Europe|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2011|ISBN=0-691-14159-2|page=51 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=XuhL44T-X8MC |page=51 }} }}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=fM27iN7438kC}} |first=Johannes |last=Lindvall |title=Mass Unemployment and the State |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |page=118}}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=9dUTXJakqLoC |page=187 }} |first=David |last=Art |title=Inside the Radical Right |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2011 |page=187}}<br />{{Citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=8kB6gvNZtNgC |page=106 }} |first1=Thierry |last1=Chopin |first2=Michel |last2=Foucher |title=Schuman Report on Europe: State of the Union 2011 |publisher=Springer |year=2011 |page=106}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2010/0602/1224271677559.html |title=Dutch liberal leader topping polls ahead of next week's election \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Wed, 2 June 2010 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}<br />{{cite news|author=Peter Beaumont, Almere |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/16/geert-wilders-pvv-holland-netherlands |title=Geert Wilders, the ultra-right firebrand, campaigns to be Holland's prime minister &#124; World news &#124; The Observer |work=Guardian |location=UK |date= 16 May 2010|accessdate=18 June 2010 }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2010/0610/Dutch-voters-boost-far-right-party-of-Geert-Wilders |title=Dutch voters boost far-right party of Geert Wilders |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/newsbook/2010/06/dutch_elections?source=hptextfeature |title=The Dutch elections: Right turn |work=The Economist |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> The party has been regarded by some as [[Anti-Polish sentiment|anti-Polish]], [[Anti-Slavic sentiment|anti-Slavic]], [[Anti-Romanyism|anti-Romani]] and [[Islamophobia|anti-Muslim]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Immigration and Conflict in Europe |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=vTRzzVMzhScC |page=287 }} |page=287 |year=2010 |first=Rafaela M. |last=Dancygier |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}<br />{{Cite book |title=The challenge of pluralism: church and state in five democracies |year=2009 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |first1=Stephen V. |last1=Monsma |first2=J. Christopher |last2=Soper |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=LqtOyWU3D54C |page=68 }} |page=68}}<br />{{Cite journal |journal=Contemporary Sociology |first=Asef |last=Bayat |volume=36 |issue=6 |date=November 2007 |title=When Muslims and Modernity Meet}}</ref><ref name=\"radio\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/11/01/tea.party.europe.uk/index.html |publisher=CNN |title=UK far-right group boasts Tea Party links |first=Dan |last=Rivers |first2=Simon |last2=Hooper |date=2 November 2010}}<br />{{Cite news |agency=Agence France-Presse |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gn5AXQSKWbiyTMQ3hnbTnEBHn8SA |first=Mariette |last=Le Roux |date=10 June 2010 |title=Far-right election breakthrough shocks Netherlands}}</ref> [[Geert Wilders|Wilders]] however maintains that he is not anti-Muslim, only anti-Islam, summing up his views by stating \"I don't hate Muslims, I hate Islam\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/feb/17/netherlands.islam|title='I don't hate Muslims. I hate Islam,' says Holland's rising political star|last=Traynor|first=Ian|date=17 February 2008|accessdate=15 March 2009|work=The Guardian | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Positions==\n===Dual nationality===\nIn February 2007, PVV parliamentarian Fritsma introduced a motion that would have prohibited any parliamentarian or executive branch politician from having [[dual citizenship]]. The PVV claimed that dual nationals have unclear loyalty. The motion would have made it difficult, if not impossible for [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour]] MPs [[Ahmed Aboutaleb]] and [[Nebahat Albayrak]] to become members of the [[fourth Balkenende cabinet]]. The motion had to be withdrawn, however, after objection from the [[List of Speakers of the House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Speaker]] of the [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]], Gerdi Verbeet (Labour Party).<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs unimpressed with motion from PVV|url=http://www.expatica.com/nl/news/local_news/mps-unimpressed-with-motion-from-pvv-36615.html|publisher=Expatica|date=16 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> [[Maastricht University]] law professor [[:nl:Twan Tak|Twan Tak]] has commented on the risk in executive branch officials having dual citizenship.<ref>{{cite news|title='Smoren discussie dubbel paspoort schandalig'|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10112390/Nieuws/Politiek/Smoren-discussie-dubbel-paspoort-schandalig.htm|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=15 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152348/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10112390/Nieuws/Politiek/Smoren-discussie-dubbel-paspoort-schandalig.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> however the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] as reviewed in 2010 ECtHR jurisprudence has reaffirmed that form of discrimination is a violation of a human right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/sites/eng/pages/search.aspx?i=001-98428|title=HUDOC Search Page|work=coe.int}}</ref> However, in 2007 the PVV planned to call for a vote of no confidence against junior ministers Aboutaleb and Albayrak when the [[fourth Balkenende cabinet|new cabinet]] had its first meeting with the House of Representatives, claiming that their respectively Moroccan and Turkish passports put their loyalties into question.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch politician doubts Muslim ministers' loyalty|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL242937120070224|agency=Reuters  |date=24 February 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> In the event, the motion was only supported by the PVV itself.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opposition criticises cabinet in debate|url=http://www.expatica.com/actual/article.asp?subchannel_id=19&story_id=37138|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929103132/http://www.expatica.com/actual/article.asp?subchannel_id=19&story_id=37138|archivedate=29 September 2007|publisher=Expatica|date=1 March 2007|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe issue of dual nationality, however, was not over yet. On 2 March 2007, [[Radio Netherlands Worldwide]] reported that Labour Party MP [[Khadija Arib]], who had been sworn into parliament the day before, was sitting on a commission appointed by the [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|king of Morocco]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dutch MP to serve as advisor to Moroccan king|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/currentaffairs/dut070302mc|publisher=[[Radio Netherlands]]|date=2 March 2007|author=el Ayoubi, Mohammed|author2=den Boer, Nicolien|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref> The PVV said that this commission work endangers Arib's loyalty to the Netherlands, and that she should choose between being a member of the Dutch parliament or the Moroccan commission. Geert Wilders said that Arib's remark on national television that her loyalty lay neither with the Netherlands nor Morocco was shameful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kamer akkoord met Marokkaans advieswerk Arib|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10115100/Nieuws/Politiek/Kamer-akkoord-met-Marokkaans-advieswerk-Arib.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152355/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10115100/Nieuws/Politiek/Kamer-akkoord-met-Marokkaans-advieswerk-Arib.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The liberal VVD party similarly remarked that her \"double orientation would hurt Dutch integration.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Kamp: Nevenfunctie Arib schaadt integratie|language=Dutch|url=http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1294450/Kamp:+Nevenfunctie+Arib+schaadt+integratie.html|publisher=[[Reformatorisch Dagblad]]|work=[[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau|ANP]]|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526215256/http://www.refdag.nl/artikel/1294450/Kamp:+Nevenfunctie+Arib+schaadt+integratie.html|archivedate=26 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All other parties were appalled by the PVV and VVD's comments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lange dag in de Kamer met veel hatelijkheden|language=Dutch|url=http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article1777410.ece/Lange_dag_in_de_Kamer_met_veel_hatelijkheden|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120905102032/http://www.nrc.nl/binnenland/article1777410.ece/Lange_dag_in_de_Kamer_met_veel_hatelijkheden|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 September 2012|newspaper=[[NRC Handelsblad]]|first=Derk|last=Stokmans|date=9 March 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nPerhaps in the light of the ''Moldova'' ruling, in the first Rutte government in 2010 chaired by the VVD leader, supported by the PVV, [[Marlies Veldhuijzen van Zanten]] became the new State Secretary for Health, Welfare and Sport, having both Dutch and [[Sweden|Swedish]] nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/Nieuws/Politiek/278676/Nieuwe-CDAstaatssecretaris-heeft-dubbele-nationaliteit.htm |title=Nieuwe CDA-staatssecretaris heeft dubbele nationaliteit |publisher=Elsevier.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nThe party fielded a controversial motion in the 2007 ''[[prinsjesdag|general deliberations]]'' on the immigration budget, calling for a stop to immigration from Muslim countries. The [[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] at first declined to bring the motion forward for debate. Justice Minister [[Ernst Hirsch Ballin]] said it was in violation of the Dutch constitution and international law.<ref>{{cite news|title=Minister: Wilders' moslimmotie is onmogelijk|language=Dutch|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10147551/Nieuws/Politiek/Minister-Wilders-moslimmotie-is-onmogelijk.htm|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=22 November 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724152402/http://www.elsevier.nl/web/10147551/Nieuws/Politiek/Minister-Wilders-moslimmotie-is-onmogelijk.htm|archivedate=24 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another motion by the PVV, against police officers wearing [[veil]]s, did gain a parliamentary majority.<ref>{{cite news|title='Agente met hoofddoek absoluut onwenselijk'|language=Dutch|url=http://www.nu.nl/algemeen/1342274/agente-met-hoofddoek-absoluut-onwenselijk.html|publisher=[[NU.nl]]|date=4 December 2007|accessdate=5 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the PVV party launched a website named ''Reporting Centre on Central and East Europeans'' to receive complaints about Central and East European immigrants in the Netherlands. 'Do you have problems with people from Central and Eastern Europe? Have you lost your job to a Pole, a Bulgarian, a Romanian or another East European? We want to know,' the website states. It displays newspaper headlines such as 'Wouldn't it be better if you went back home?' and '[[East Europeans]], increasingly criminal'. The European Commission has condemned the website, and EU Justice Commissioner [[Viviane Reding]] declared, \"We call on all citizens of the Netherlands not to join in this intolerance. Citizens should instead clearly state on the PVV's website that Europe is a place of freedom.\"<ref>\"[http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/02/problems_with_poles_report_the.php Problems with Poles? Report them to us, says new PVV website]\". DutchNews.nl. 8 February 2012.</ref><ref>\"[https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE8191ML20120210 Dutch allow Wilders' anti-Pole website, EU critical]\". ''Reuters.'' 10 February 2012.</ref> The website caused a lot of controversy within the [[European Union]].<ref>\"[http://www.sofiaecho.com/2012/02/16/1767592_controversy-continues-over-wilders-anti-eastern-european-website Sofiaecho.com 16 February 2012]\". {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217125414/http://www.sofiaecho.com/2012/02/16/1767592_controversy-continues-over-wilders-anti-eastern-european-website |date=17 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Financing political parties===\nThe PVV has declared that, since it is against state subsidies, it rejects the idea of itself being financially supported by the government and believes the \"taxpayers should not pay for political parties they don't support\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/video/407199-zomergesprek-geert-wilders-pvv.html |title=Zomergesprek: Geert Wilders (PVV) - NOS Nieuws |publisher=Nos.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Dutch Parliament discussed tightening the financial rules for political parties, forcing them to become more transparent. The PVV indicated that it would use any means available to avoid disclosing the identity of its donors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parool.nl/parool/nl/3587/POLITIEK-BINNENLAND/article/detail/3139689/2012/01/26/PVV-zoekt-mazen-in-wet-over-giften.dhtml |title=PVV zal alles doen om bekendmaking donateurs te vermijden - POLITIEK BINNENLAND - PAROOL |publisher=Parool.nl |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Party platform===\n{{Update-section|date=December 2017}}\n{{third-party|section|date=March 2012}}\nOther policies that Wilders mentions in his party programme for the [[2010 Dutch general election|2010 general election]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pvv.nl/images/stories/Webversie_VerkiezingsProgrammaPVV.pdf|language=Dutch|title=De agenda van hoop en optimisme|publisher=Party for Freedom}}</ref>\n* Harsh punishment of [[Antisemitism|violence against Jews]] and the [[LGBT]] community, which it claims is disproportionately committed by Muslims (p.&nbsp;13)\n* Recording the ethnicity of all Dutch citizens. (p.&nbsp;11)\n* Prohibition of [[Dhabihah#Islamic slaughtering|halal]] and [[Shechita|kosher slaughter]] (p.&nbsp;55) (However, Wilders has stated that opposition to kosher slaughter was not part of his party's agenda and that support for the ban had been withdrawn)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora?id=282105|title=Diaspora &#124; Jewish diaspora &#124; The Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Limitation of [[Coffeeshop (Netherlands)|cannabis coffee shops]] within a radius of no less than 1 [[Kilometre|kilometer]] from schools (p.&nbsp;11)\n* Active repatriation of criminals of foreign citizenship and Dutch nationals originating from the [[Netherlands Antilles]] (p.&nbsp;11)\n* [[Deportation]] of criminals having foreign nationality or [[multiple citizenship]] back to their country of origin, after a prison sentence (p.&nbsp;13)\n* Restrictions on immigrant labour from new EU member states and Islamic countries (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Removal of resources from anti-climate change programs, development aid, and immigration services (p.&nbsp;17)\n* Abolition of the Dutch [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]] (p.&nbsp;19)\n* Shutting down of all Islamic schools (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Ban on [[Women in Islam|Islamic gender apartheid]] (p.&nbsp;15)\n* The General Pension (AOW) age not to be increased beyond 65 (p.&nbsp;21)\n* Governmental communication to be exclusively in Dutch or Frisian (p.&nbsp;35)\n* Dutch language proficiency and a 10-year Dutch residency and work experience requirement for welfare assistance (p.&nbsp;15)\n* Constitutional protection of the dominance of the Judeo-Christian and humanistic culture of the Netherlands (p.&nbsp;35)\n* Choosing to defend the essential elements of Dutch culture: freedom of the LGBT community, as well as assured equality of men and women which Islam may challenge (p.&nbsp;33)\n* Respect for [[Remembrance of the Dead|May 4]] as a day to remember victims of [[Nazism|National Socialism]]. (p.&nbsp;35)\n* Repeal of anti-smoking legislation in bars (p.&nbsp;39)\n* Referring to [[Jordan]] as 'Palestine' (p.&nbsp;43)\n* [[One-state solution]] to the Israel-Palestine conflict (p.&nbsp;43)\n* Investment in more nuclear power plants and clean coal plants to reduce dependency on imported oil and because coal is cheaper (p.&nbsp;47)\n* Withdrawal from the [[European Union]].\n* Return to the [[Dutch guilder|guilder]] (old Dutch currency) and abandonment of the [[euro]].\n* Abolition of the European Parliament and no cooperation in any EU activity.\n* Ask the EU to remove the \"Dutch\" star in the European flag.\n* Repeal flight tax or [[Carbon tax|carbon dioxide tax]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n* Binding referendum on subjects like the EU and a multicultural society.\n* No more tax money to (political) left organisations.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n* Keeping track of the ethnicity of people who have committed crimes.\n* Select policemen on \"decisiveness\".\n* Binding assimilation contracts for immigrants.\n* Taxes on the [[Hijab|Islamic headscarf]] and prohibition of the [[Quran|Koran]]. {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n* Ban on headscarves in any public function.\n* Support [[Afrikaners]], as it is Dutch heritage.\n* Opposition to Turkey's membership in NATO; support for remaining in NATO.\n* Halt all support and propaganda for Palestine and Palestinians.\n* No more [[Wind turbine|windmills]] and funding for durability or CO2 reduction; no more \"fiscal greening\". {{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n== Name and symbols ==\nThe name 'Party for Freedom' (''Partij voor de Vrijheid'') is a reference to the [[Freedom Party (Netherlands)|Freedom Party]] (''Partij van de Vrijheid''), a Dutch political party founded in 1946, shortly after [[World War II]]. In 1948, the Freedom Party went on as the [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]] (''Volkspartij voor Vrijheid en Democratie''), which is the party Wilders split from.<ref>{{cite news|title=Groep Wilders wordt Partij voor de Vrijheid|url=http://www.elsevier.nl/nieuws/politiek/artikel/asp/artnr/88062/index.html|language=Dutch|publisher=[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]|date=23 February 2006|accessdate=5 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200935/http://www.elsevier.nl/nieuws/politiek/artikel/asp/artnr/88062/index.html|archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe party logo consists of the party name and a [[gull]] in red, white, and blue, which are the colors of the [[Flag of the Netherlands|Dutch flag]].<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"sargasso\">Willem Visser, \"[http://sargasso.nl/kleur-en-symboliek-nederlandse-politiek/ Kleur en symboliek in de Nederlandse politiek]\" (in Dutch), ''Sargasso.nl'', 2017. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref> The gull symbolises freedom or liberty.<ref name=\"sargasso\"/><ref name=\"historischnieuwsblad\">Bas Kromhout, \"[https://www.historischnieuwsblad.nl/nl/nieuws/10749/Wilders_gebruikt_%5c%e2%80%98besmet%5c%e2%80%99_logo.html Wilders gebruikt 'besmet' logo]\" (in Dutch), ''Historisch Nieuwsblad'', 2008. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref> The gull had also been used as a symbol by the [[National Socialist Movement in the Netherlands]] on propaganda posters and for their youth wing, but Wilders claimed it was not inspired by Nazi usage.<ref name=\"historischnieuwsblad\"/><ref>\"[http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/20624246/__Wilders_woedend_na_NSB-vergelijking__.html Wilders woedend over vergelijking met NSB]\" (in Dutch), ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', 2008. Retrieved 5 March 2017.</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\nIn order to register for elections in the Netherlands, a political party needs to be an [[Voluntary association|association]] ({{Lang-nl|vereniging}}), which can be founded by two or more members.<ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/onderwerpen/democratie/vraag-en-antwoord/hoe-richt-ik-een-politieke-partij-op Hoe richt ik een politieke partij op?]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]''. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.notaris.nl/een-vereniging-oprichten Hoe richt ik een vereniging op?]\" (in Dutch), ''Notaris.nl''. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref> The Vereniging Groep Wilders (Association Group Wilders) was founded by the [[natural person]] Geert Wilders and Stichting Groep Wilders ([[Foundation (nonprofit)|Foundation]] Group Wilders), of which Wilders is the only board member.<ref name=\"montesquieu\">Koen Vossen, \"[http://www.montesquieu-instituut.nl/id/vj5eflkxm6yg/een_unieke_partij_de_organisatie_van_de Een unieke partij. De organisatie van de PVV]\" (in Dutch), ''Montesquieu Instituut'', 2012. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref><ref>Paul Lucardie, \"[http://dnpp.ub.rug.nl/dnpp/pp/pvv/geschied PVV partijgeschiedenis]\" (in Dutch), ''[[University of Groningen]]'', 2013. Retrieved 4 March 2017.</ref> The association was later renamed to Partij voor de Vrijheid (Party for Freedom).<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/> After the creation of the association, Wilders disabled new member registration, resulting in his remaining the sole member of the party.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"montesquieu\"/> The party does not organise public [[party conference]]s and does not have local departments, a [[youth wing]], or a [[Think tank|research institute]].<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"montesquieu\"/>\n\n==Financing==\nIn the Netherlands, a political party needs to have 1,000 members or more to be eligible for government funding, a requirement which the Party for Freedom does not meet with Wilders being the only member.<ref name=\"parlementparty\"/><ref name=\"financinglaw\">\"[http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0033004/2016-01-01 Wet financiering politieke partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2016. Retrieved 9 March 2017.</ref>\n\nOn several instances the PVV applied for and received European Union funding.<ref>\"[http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2012/09/pvv_wrongly_claims_13000_from.php PVV wrongly claims \u20ac13,000 from Brussels for euro report: tv show]\", ''DutchNews.nl'', 2012.</ref>\n\nFinancially, the party has been largely relying on donations. The party has not disclosed any of its finances until 2013. According to [[Hero Brinkman]], a former MP for the party, the PVV received most of its finances from certain foreign (American) lobby-groups.<ref>\"[http://www.nu.nl/politiek/2768411/lobbykantoren-vs-steunen-pvv.html 'Lobbykantoren VS steunen PVV']\" (in Dutch), ''[[NU.nl]]'', 2012.</ref> According to [[Reuters]], [[Daniel Pipes|Daniel Pipes']] [[Middle East Forum]] paid for the trials and security of Geert Wilders and [[David Horowitz]] paid Wilders \"a good fee\" for two speeches given in the US.<ref>Anthony Deutsch & Mark Hosenball, \"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/10/us-dutch-wilders-us-idUSBRE8890Q820120910 Exclusive: U.S. groups helped fund Dutch anti-Islam politician Wilders]\", ''[[Reuters]]'', 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://vorige.nrc.nl/binnenland/article2544752.ece/Partners_Wilders_in_VS_verdienen_aan_acties_tegen_moslimextremisme Partners Wilders in VS verdienen aan acties tegen moslimextremisme]\" {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111012085802/http://vorige.nrc.nl/binnenland/article2544752.ece/Partners_Wilders_in_VS_verdienen_aan_acties_tegen_moslimextremisme |date=12 October 2011 }} (in Dutch), ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 2010.</ref>\n\nSince 2013, Dutch political parties are required by law to disclose all donations of 4,500 euro or more.<ref name=\"financinglaw\"/><ref name=\"politicofinances\">Cynthia Kroet, \"[http://www.politico.eu/article/geert-wilders-far-right-party-suffers-donation-downturn/ Geert Wilders\u2019 far-right party suffers donation downturn]\", ''[[Politico Europe]]'', 2017. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> The Party for Freedom disclosed no donations for 2013.<ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2014/10/01/pvv-financieel-verslag-over-2013 Financieel verslag PVV 2013]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2014. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> For 2014 to 2016, the party disclosed a total of 148,391.07 euro in donations from the California-based [[David Horowitz Freedom Center]], a total of 18,700 euro in donations from a private donor in the Netherlands, and a donation of 6,853.70 euro from the New York-based company FOL Inc.<ref name=\"politicofinances\"/><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2015/09/21/pvv---financieel-verslag-over-2014 Financieel verslag PVV 2014]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2015. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2016/10/13/financiele-verslagen-over-2015-van-politieke-partijen Financi\u00eble verslagen over 2015 van politieke partijen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2016. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/documenten/publicaties/2017/03/08/overzicht-giften-en-schulden-politieke-partijen-tweede-kamerverkiezingen Overzicht giften en schulden politieke partijen Tweede Kamerverkiezingen]\" (in Dutch), ''[[Government of the Netherlands]]'', 2017. Retrieved 8 March 2017.</ref> The 2015 donations of just over 108,244 euro from the Freedom Center was \"the largest individual contribution to a Dutch political party that year.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/928684/the-dutch-far-rights-election-donors-are-almost-exclusively-american/|title=The Dutch far right\u2019s election donors are almost exclusively American|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|work=Quartz|access-date=11 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n===House of Representatives===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election year\n! # of votes\n! % of overall vote\n!Rank\n! # of seats won\n! Change\n! Government \n|-\n! [[2006 Dutch general election|2006]]\n| 579,490<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\">\"[http://www.verkiezingsuitslagen.nl/Na1918/Verkiezingsuitslagen.aspx?VerkiezingsTypeId=1 Verkiezingsuitslagen Tweede Kamer 1918 - heden]\" (in Dutch), ''Kiesraad''. Retrieved 9 March 2017.</ref>\n| 5.89%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#5\n| {{Composition bar|9|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| new\n| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2010 Dutch general election|2010]]\n| 1,454,493<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n| 15.45%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#3\n| {{Composition bar|24|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 15\n| {{Yes-No|In support of the [[First Rutte cabinet|VVD-CDA minority coalition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2012 Dutch general election|2012]]\n| 950,263<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n| 10.08%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults\"/>\n|#3\n| {{Composition bar|15|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 9\n| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2017 Dutch general election|2017]]\n| 1,372,941<ref name=\"generalelectionresults2017\">\"[https://www.kiesraad.nl/binaries/kiesraad/documenten/rapporten/2017/3/kerngegevens-tweede-kamerverkiezing-2017/kerngegevens-tweede-kamerverkiezing-2017/Kerngegevens+Tweede+Kamerverkiezing+2017.pdf Uitslag van de verkiezing van de leden van de Tweede Kamer van 15 maart 2017 \u2013 Kerngegevens]\" (in Dutch), ''Kiesraad'', 2017. Retrieved 24 March 2017.</ref>\n| 13.1%<ref name=\"generalelectionresults2017\"/>\n|#2\n| {{Composition bar|20|150|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 5\n| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|}\n\n===Senate===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Election year\n! # of votes\n! % of overall vote\n!Rank\n! # of seats won\n! Change\n!Government\n|-\n! [[2011 Dutch Senate election|2011]]\n| 72<ref name=\"senateelectionresults\">\"[http://www.verkiezingsuitslagen.nl/Na1918/Verkiezingsuitslagen.aspx?VerkiezingsTypeId=2 Verkiezingsuitslagen Eerste Kamer 1918 - heden]\" (in Dutch), ''Kiesraad''. Retrieved 9 March 2017.</ref>\n| 12.74%<ref name=\"senateelectionresults\"/>\n|#4\n| {{Composition bar|10|75|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| new|| {{Yes-No|In support of the [[First Rutte cabinet|VVD-CDA minority coalition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2015 Dutch Senate election|2015]]\n| 66<ref name=\"senateelectionresults\"/>\n| 11.58%<ref name=\"senateelectionresults\"/>\n|#4\n| {{Composition bar|9|75|hex={{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 1|| {{no2|In the [[Opposition (politics)|opposition]]}}\n|-\n! [[2019 Dutch Senate election|2019]]\n| 38<ref name=\"senateelectionresults\"/>\n| 6.46%<ref 